{"title_page": "Homai", "text_new": "{{for|the villages in Iran|Homai, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Homai, Iran}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Homai\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|37|01|S|174|53|E|display=it|region:NZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 8,196\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  = [[Homai Train Station]]\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Manukau|Manukau Central]]\n| northeast      = \n| east           = [[Hill Park, New Zealand|Hill Park]]\n| southeast      = [[Manurewa]]\n| south          = \n| southwest      = [[Clendon Park]]\n| west           = \n| northwest      = [[Wiri]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n'''Homai''' is a suburb of [[Auckland]] in New Zealand surrounded by [[Manukau|Manukau Central]], [[Wiri]], [[Hill Park, New Zealand|Hill Park]], [[Clendon Park]] and [[Manurewa]]. It was formerly under the local governance of the [[Manukau City]] Council. It has since been integrated with the rest of Auckland under [[Auckland Council]] in 2010.\n\nAs of the 2013 census, Homai has a population of 8,196, an increase of 276 since 2006.<ref>Homai covers two statistical areas: {{NZ Quickstats2013|13554|Homai East}} and {{NZ Quickstats2013|13552|Homai West}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/collection/photos/search/searchterm/Homai/field/title/ Photographs of Homai] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n\n\n{{Auckland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the villages in Iran|Homai, Iran (disambiguation){{!}}Homai, Iran}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Homai\n| image          = \n| caption1       = \n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           =\n| established    =\n| coordinates    = {{coord|37|01|S|174|53|E|display=it|region:NZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 8,196\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  = [[Homai Train Station]]\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Manukau|Manukau Central]]\n| northeast      = \n| east           = [[Hill Park, New Zealand|Hill Park]]\n| southeast      = [[Manurewa]]\n| south          = \n| southwest      = [[Clendon Park]]\n| west           = \n| northwest      = [[Wiri]]\n| map            =\n| caption2       =\n}}\n'''Homai''' is a suburb of [[Auckland]] in New Zealand surrounded by [[Manukau|Manukau Central]], [[Wiri]], [[Hill Park, New Zealand|Hill Park]], [[Clendon Park]] and [[Manurewa]]. It was formerly under the local governance of the [[Manukau City]] Council. It has since been integrated with the rest of Auckland under [[Auckland Council]] in 2010.\n\nAs of the 2013 census, Homai has a population of 8,196, an increase of 276 since 2006.<ref>Homai covers two statistical areas: {{NZ Quickstats2013|13554|Homai East}} and {{NZ Quickstats2013|13552|Homai West}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/?p=q&collection=p20062coll1&search=homai&field=title&mode=all&conn= Photographs of Homai] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n\n\n{{Auckland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Agh47", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated photographs link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homai"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Peyton", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox saint \n|name           = [[Venerable]] <br> Patrick Peyton\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|1992|6|3|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|image          = Patrick_Peyton.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|birth_place    = [[Attymass]], [[County Mayo]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|death_place    = [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|titles         = Priest\n|beatified_date   = \n|beatified_place  =\n|beatified_by     = \n|canonized_date   = \n|canonized_place  =\n|canonized_by     = \n|attributes       =\n|patronage        = \n|major_shrine     = \n|suppressed_date  = \n|issues           = \n|feast_day = \n|venerated_in   = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n{{infobox person|child=yes|\n|signature        = father patrick peyton signature.gif|signature_size=250px|signature_alt=Peyton's signature}}\n}}\n'''Patrick Peyton''' {{Audio|Father patrick peyton prayer appeal.ogg|Patrick Peyton}}  (January 9, 1909 \u2013 June 3, 1992), also known as \"The Rosary Priest\", was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Catholic]] [[priest]] and promoter of the [[Rosary]].\n\nPeyton is the founder of the \"[[Family Rosary Crusade]]\". He staged massive [[Rosary]] rallies in key cities of the world and extensively utilized mass communication, helped by world-recognized celebrities of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] at that time, promoting his ministry of binding families through prayer under the Family Rosary. Peyton was a popular and charismatic figure in [[Latin America]] and the [[Philippines]], where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and was known for his strong [[Irish people|Irish]] accent.\n\nPeyton popularized the phrases \"[[The family that prays together stays together]]\" and \"A world at prayer is a world at peace\".\n\n[[Pope Francis]] furthered Peyton towards sainthood by confirming his [[heroic virtue]] and naming him as [[Venerable]] on December 18, 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nPeyton was born Patrick Joseph Peyton in [[Attymass]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]],<ref name=chc>[http://holycrosscongregation.org/holy-ones/servant-of-god-patrick-peyton/ \"Venerable Patrick Peyton\", Congregation of Holy Cross]</ref> to subsistence-farmers John and Mary Gillard Peyton. Peyton was the sixth in a deeply religious family of four girls and five boys living in a small cottage at a 14-acre (5.66&nbsp;hectares) stony farmland near the foot of the Ox Mountains. Later on, some members of the family migrated to the United States.\n\nPeyton was sent to his mother's relatives in [[Bonniconlon]] to study at a school run by Tadhg O\u2019Leary in Bofield. As a young man, Peyton was rebellious and had moments of defying authority, resulting in dropping out of school. Despite the youthful rebellion, he remained close to his family, and deeply religious.\n\nBy his teen years, he was contemplating a vocation to become a priest. Although religious recruiters such as the [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchins]] and the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|Redemptorist]] fathers visited Carracastle in search of young men wanting to pursue the priesthood, Peyton concentrated on helping his family earn a living when their father became too ill to work the farm. Some of his elder sisters were already in America and were sending remittances to help the family left in Ireland. In 1927, his sisters sent word that Patrick and his older brother Thomas could sail to the United States and join them in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. On May 13, 1928, the Peyton brothers set sail.\n\n==America==\nThe brothers arrived in [[New York City|New York]] after a 10-day trip, traveling by steerage. The two took the train from New York to [[Pennsylvania]] and lived at the home of their already married sister Beatrice, who was working as a housekeeper for [[Thomas J. Baldrige]], the state Attorney General. Peyton's sister Nellie had already spoken to [[Monsignor]] Paul Kelly of [[St. Peter's Cathedral (Scranton, Pennsylvania)|Saint Peter's Cathedral]] and mentioned Peyton's interest in pursuing a [[Seminary|priestly vocation]]. Monsignor Kelly told Nellie to bring her younger brother Patrick to the cathedral as soon as he arrived. By June 1928, with hard luck in finding a job, Peyton finally met Monsignor Kelly and was offered a job of becoming the cathedral's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]]. In the words of Peyton at that time, \"a sexton was just another name for a janitor''.\"''\n\nPeyton took the job with initial hesitation but his daily presence at the cathedral brought back the calling for a vocation and he finally decided to pursue the priesthood. Monsignor Kelly insisted that Peyton should complete his high school education prior to admission to the [[novitiate]].  He and his older brother Thomas both pursued their religious vocations while working at the cathedral. During the spring of 1929, Father Pat Dolan of the [[Congregation of Holy Cross]] came to the cathedral in Scranton in search of new seminarians. Peyton and his brother Thomas entered the minor seminary of the Congregation of Holy Cross in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]].<ref name=chc/>\n\nAfter completing their high school studies at the Holy Cross School in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]], Peyton was admitted to the Moreau Seminary within the [[University of Notre Dame]] in 1932, where he pursued a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, and excelled in [[Philosophy]]. He credited Cornelius Hagerty, a professor of ethics, as the one who provided him with counseling. As a young seminarian, Peyton was attracted to become a Holy Cross Father, for the order's focus on the Holy Family and towards obedience and conscience.\n\n==Marian devotion==\n[[File:Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Perez Murillo - Virgin and Child with a Rosary - WGA16360.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Peyton hosted a number of televised shows abroad promoting the [[Rosary]], where an image of [[Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Murillo]]'s painting of the [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] was always present in the background. Oil on canvas. [[Museo del Prado]].]]\n\nIn October 1938, during Peyton's second year of theology at [[Catholic University of America]], he was diagnosed with tuberculosis. He was transferred back to Notre Dame to the Infirmary. Father Cornelius Hagerty was influential in this stage of Peyton's life, encouraging the young seminarian to seek the help of the Blessed Virgin Mary. The doctors discovered that the patches in his lungs disappeared.<ref name=chc/>\n\nHe immediately packed his bags and left for Washington, D.C., to complete his theology studies and take his final vows. On June 15, 1941, Peyton and his brother Thomas were ordained at the [[Basilica of the Sacred Heart, Notre Dame|Basilica of the Sacred Heart]] at the University of Notre Dame as members of the Congregation of Holy Cross.<ref>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-enduring-legacy-of-now-venerable-father-patrick-peyton Pronechen, Joseph. \"The Enduring Legacy of Now-\u2018Venerable\u2019 Father Patrick Peyton\", ''National Catholic Register'', January 4, 2018]</ref>\n\n==Lifetime crusade==\n{{Main|Family Rosary Crusade|Family Theater}}\nPeyton was given very light duties following the completion of his theological studies. His first assignment was in [[Albany, New York]], as the chaplain of the [[Holy Cross Brothers]] of the Vincentian Institute. Peyton started sending letters to bishops, Catholic laity, and other groups promoting the importance of families praying the Rosary as the war raged on.\n\nUtilizing radio, [[films]], [[outdoor advertising]] and later television, with the help of celebrities, artists and advertising practitioners, Peyton was one of the first pioneers of evangelism using [[mass media]]. He would also pioneer in conducting public rallies to bring families to pledge to pray the Rosary as a unit. These Rosary rallies attended by millions would become the most significant event where Peyton could be best remembered.  According to historian Hugh Wilford, \"Peyton himself was deeply conscious of the political dimension of his mission, proudly proclaiming in a 1946 radio broadcast, 'The rosary is the offensive weapon that will destroy Communism\u2014the great evil that seeks to destroy the faith'\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=GRIBBLE |first1=RICHARD  |date=2003 |title=Anti-Communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A. |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=535\u2013558 |doi= 10.1093/jcs/45.3.535|jstor=23920511 }}</ref>\n\nThese Rosary Crusades were duplicated in different dioceses with attendees growing in numbers, taking Peyton across the globe from [[Brussels, Belgium]], to [[Madrid, Spain]], across Asia to [[Manila, Philippines]], down south of the [[equator]] to New Zealand and [[Papua New Guinea]] and into several South American cities like [[Lima, Peru]], to [[Rio de Janeiro]] in [[Brazil]]. With the help of a non-Catholic advertising practitioner, Peyton would popularize the slogan, \"The family that prays together stays together.\"\n\n==Death and legacy==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:father patrick peyton rosary rally philippines.gif|left|thumb|350px|Peyton shaking hands with [[Filipinos]] who gathered for the Rosary Rally in [[Archdiocese of Manila|Manila]]. 1953]] -->\n\nWith the [[Cold War]] threatening a new world peace, Peyton's work in promoting prayer was recognized by the Holy See. His efforts earned him the title \"The Rosary Priest\".\n\nControversy hounded Peyton throughout his ministry as some accused him of being a front for American intelligence during his missions in Latin America. Peyton's Rosary Crusades in Latin America were funded and, to some extent, directed by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], which was interested in combating leftist political movements in Latin America.  This came about through Peyton's connection to [[J. Peter Grace]], the great-grandson of the founder of [[W.R. Grace and Company]], a multinational corporation with interests in transport, [[sugar]], and mining in South America, whom Peyton had met in 1946 on a trans-Atlantic voyage.  Grace, who was involved with other [[CIA]] front operations as well, wrote to John Moore, the chair of the Business Advisory Council, and the two men approached [[Allen Dulles]].  Dulles later met with Grace in the White House office of Vice President [[Richard Nixon]], who expressed enthusiasm.  The CIA decided for several years where the crusades would take place, and CIA funds were expended in [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Colombia]], until Peyton's provincial superior, Richard H. Sullivan, learned of the secret funding from [[Theodore Hesburgh]], the chair of the board of trustees of the [[University of Notre Dame]], in October 1964.  It took the [[Holy See|Vatican]] more than a year and a half to oblige Peyton to give up his CIA financing.<ref>Hugh Wilford, ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America'' [Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008], pp.&nbsp;182\u201396 .</ref> While the CIA determined the locations of the Crusades, it did not influence the content or Peyton's goal of promoting family prayer \u2013 the Rosary and devotion to the Blessed Mother.\n\nOthers accused Peyton of living an ostentatious lifestyle, living a life with Hollywood artists who volunteered their efforts in helping promote his mission. But Peyton maintained that he never solicited funds for his ministry, and the well-off were more than generous to voluntarily donate a portion of their wealth all in the name of the Blessed Mother.\n\nPeyton died peacefully on June 3, 1992, holding a rosary, in a small room at the Little Sisters of the Poor Jeanne Jugan Residence in [[San Pedro, California]]. His remains were brought to the Holy Cross Cemetery on the grounds of [[Stonehill College]] in [[Easton, Massachusetts]].\n\nBefore Peyton died, he continued to work on what was to be the last major Rosary Rally. On December 8, 1992, at the [[Rizal Park]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], Manila Archbishop [[Jaime Cardinal Sin]] led the celebrations for the Golden Jubilee Celebration of the [[Family Rosary Crusade]]; the Archbishop of Los Angeles, [[Roger Cardinal Mahony]] was sent as [[Papal Legate]] on behalf of [[Pope John Paul II]]. Among [[Filipino people|Filipino]] Catholics, Peyton is remembered for his Sunday televised shows, where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and [[Marian devotion]] along with his famous slogan. Peyton also encouraged many businesses to start making and selling large amounts of Rosaries for distribution, which he gave freely to impoverished Filipinos living in the slums.\n\nPeyton's work continues today in his original ministries \u2013 Family Rosary, Family Theater and Family Rosary International \u2013 and in the Father Patrick Peyton Family Institute.\n\n==Sainthood==\nCardinal [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Sean Patrick O\u2019Malley]] announced a formal declaration opening the cause for [[sainthood]] of Father Peyton on June 1, 2001, a few days after receiving approval from the Vatican's [[Congregation for the Causes of the Saints]]. The declaration paved the way for the process of determining Peyton's holiness, and in the process earning the revered title of \"[[Servant of God]]\".\n\nThe [[Positio]] was sent to the C.C.S. in 2015 for assessment and theologians approved his cause on June 1, 2017. [[Pope Francis]] named him as [[Venerable]] on December 18, 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Citation\n|last=Peyton, CSC\n|first=Patrick\n|title=All For Her: An Autobiography of Father Patrick Peyton, CSC\n|publisher=Family Theater Publications, Hollywood California\n|origyear=1967|year=1996\n|asin= B0006CCAGY\n|url=http://www.christian-pages.com/si/2353.html}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Shiel\n|first=Tom\n|title=Cardinal urges Christians to twitter\n|publisher=Irish Times\n|date=April 27, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0427/1224245444798.html\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n |last        = Matilla\n |first       = Dexter R.\n |title       = 'Rosary priest' to be honored with sculpture\n |publisher   = Philippines Daily Inquirer\n |date        = March 31, 2009\n |url         = http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090430075846/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |archivedate = April 30, 2009\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Bourke\n|first=Toni\n|title=Fr Peyton remembered at 100th anniversary celebrations\n|publisher=Mayo Advertiser\n|date=April 17, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/mayo/article/11149\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Schworm\n|first=Peter\n|title=Dozens in Easton pray for canonization of the 'Rosary Priest'\n|work=Boston Globe\n|date=June 8, 2008\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2008/06/08/dozens_in_easton_pray_for_canonization_of_the_rosary_priest/\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Gribble\n|first=Richard\n|title=Anti-communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A.(Congregation of Holy Cross)\n|publisher=Journal of Church and State/J.M. Dawsons Studies on Church and State\n|date=June 22, 2003\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-829121_ITM\n}}.\n* \"Fifty Golden Years of the Family Rosary Crusade in the Philippines (1951-2001)\" written by Father [[James B. Reuter]], SJ; Gennie Q. Jota; Dean M. Bernardo, edited by Stella J. Villegas 2001 Family Rosary Crusade Foundation, Inc. \u00a9 2001\n* Wilford, Hugh. ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America''.  Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fatherpeyton.org Father Patrick Peyton, C.S.C. - Memorial Website]\n* [http://www.museumsofmayo.com/peyton1.htm Museum of Mayo]\n* [https://blog.familyrosary.org/ Family Rosary]\n* [http://www.familytheater.org Family Theater Productions]\n* [http://www.attymass.ie/peyton.htm Father Peyton Memorial Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120304053147/http://www.familyrosaryph.org/ Family Rosary Crusade - Philippines]\n\n{{canonization}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peyton, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century venerated Christians]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:American venerated Catholics]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Catholic television]]\n[[Category:Congregation of Holy Cross]]\n[[Category:Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Irish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish film producers]]\n[[Category:Irish radio producers]]\n[[Category:Irish television producers]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from County Mayo]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Television evangelists]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame people]]\n[[Category:Venerated Catholics by Pope Francis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish clergy]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox saint \n|name           = [[Venerable]] <br> Patrick Peyton\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|1992|6|3|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|image          = Patrick_Peyton.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|birth_place    = [[Attymass]], [[County Mayo]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|death_place    = [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|titles         = Priest\n|beatified_date   = \n|beatified_place  =\n|beatified_by     = \n|canonized_date   = \n|canonized_place  =\n|canonized_by     = \n|attributes       =\n|patronage        = \n|major_shrine     = \n|suppressed_date  = \n|issues           = \n|feast_day = \n|venerated_in   = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n{{infobox person|child=yes|\n|signature        = father patrick peyton signature.gif|signature_size=250px|signature_alt=Peyton's signature}}\n}}\n'''Patrick Peyton''' {{Audio|Father patrick peyton prayer appeal.ogg|Patrick Peyton}}  (January 9, 1909 \u2013 June 3, 1992), also known as \"The Rosary Priest\", was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Catholic]] [[priest]] and promoter of the [[Rosary]].\n\nPeyton is the founder of the \"[[Family Rosary Crusade]]\". He staged massive [[Rosary]] rallies in key cities of the world and extensively utilized mass communication, helped by world-recognized celebrities of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] at that time, promoting his ministry of binding families through prayer under the Family Rosary. Peyton was a popular and charismatic figure in [[Latin America]] and the [[Philippines]], where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and was known for his strong [[Irish people|Irish]] accent.\n\nPeyton popularized the phrases \"[[The family that prays together stays together]]\" and \"A world at prayer is a world at peace\".\n\n[[Pope Francis]] furthered Peyton towards sainthood by confirming his [[heroic virtue]] and naming him as [[Venerable]] on December 18, 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nPeyton was born Patrick Joseph Peyton in [[Attymass]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]],<ref name=chc>[http://holycrosscongregation.org/holy-ones/servant-of-god-patrick-peyton/ \"Venerable Patrick Peyton\", Congregation of Holy Cross]</ref> to subsistence-farmers John and Mary Gillard Peyton. Peyton was the sixth in a deeply religious family of four girls and five boys living in a small cottage at a 14-acre (5.66&nbsp;hectares) stony farmland near the foot of the Ox Mountains. Later on, some members of the family migrated to the United States.\n\nPeyton was sent to his mother's relatives in [[Bonniconlon]] to study at a school run by Tadhg O\u2019Leary in Bofield. As a young man, Peyton was rebellious and had moments of defying authority, resulting in dropping out of school. Despite the youthful rebellion, he remained close to his family, and deeply religious.\n\nBy his teen years, he was contemplating a vocation to become a priest. Although religious recruiters such as the [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchins]] and the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|Redemptorist]] fathers visited Carracastle in search of young men wanting to pursue the priesthood, Peyton concentrated on helping his family earn a living when their father became too ill to work the farm. Some of his elder sisters were already in America and were sending remittances to help the family left in Ireland. In 1927, his sisters sent word that Patrick and his older brother Thomas could sail to the United States and join them in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. On May 13, 1928, the Peyton brothers set sail.\n\n==America==\nThe brothers arrived in [[New York City|New York]] after a 10-day trip, traveling by steerage. The two took the train from New York to [[Pennsylvania]] and lived at the home of their already married sister Beatrice, who was working as a housekeeper for [[Thomas J. Baldrige]], the state Attorney General. Peyton's sister Nellie had already spoken to [[Monsignor]] Paul Kelly of [[St. Peter's Cathedral (Scranton, Pennsylvania)|Saint Peter's Cathedral]] and mentioned Peyton's interest in pursuing a [[Seminary|priestly vocation]]. Monsignor Kelly told Nellie to bring her younger brother Patrick to the cathedral as soon as he arrived. By June 1928, with hard luck in finding a job, Peyton finally met Monsignor Kelly and was offered a job of becoming the cathedral's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]]. In the words of Peyton at that time, \"a sexton was just another name for a janitor''.\"''\n\nPeyton took the job with initial hesitation but his daily presence at the cathedral brought back the calling for a vocation and he finally decided to pursue the priesthood. Monsignor Kelly insisted that Peyton should complete his high school education prior to admission to the [[novitiate]].  He and his older brother Thomas both pursued their religious vocations while working at the cathedral. During the spring of 1929, Father Pat Dolan of the [[Congregation of Holy Cross]] came to the cathedral in Scranton in search of new seminarians. Peyton and his brother Thomas entered the minor seminary of the Congregation of Holy Cross in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]].<ref name=chc/>\n\nAfter completing their high school studies at the Holy Cross School in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]], Peyton was admitted to the Moreau Seminary within the [[University of Notre Dame]] in 1932, where he pursued a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, and excelled in [[Philosophy]]. He credited Cornelius Hagerty, a professor of ethics, as the one who provided him with counseling. As a young seminarian, Peyton was attracted to become a Holy Cross Father, for the order's focus on the Holy Family and towards obedience and conscience.\n\n==Marian devotion==\n[[File:Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Perez Murillo - Virgin and Child with a Rosary - WGA16360.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Peyton hosted a number of televised shows abroad promoting the [[Rosary]], where an image of [[Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Murillo]]'s painting of the [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] was always present in the background. Oil on canvas. [[Museo del Prado]].]]\n\nIn October 1938, during Peyton's second year of theology at [[Catholic University of America]], he was diagnosed with tuberculosis. He was transferred back to Notre Dame to the Infirmary. Father Cornelius Hagerty was influential in this stage of Peyton's life, encouraging the young seminarian to seek the help of the Blessed Virgin Mary. The doctors discovered that the patches in his lungs disappeared.<ref name=chc/>\n\nHe immediately packed his bags and left for Washington, D.C., to complete his theology studies and take his final vows. On June 15, 1941, Peyton and his brother Thomas were ordained at the [[Basilica of the Sacred Heart, Notre Dame|Basilica of the Sacred Heart]] at the University of Notre Dame as members of the Congregation of Holy Cross.<ref>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-enduring-legacy-of-now-venerable-father-patrick-peyton Pronechen, Joseph. \"The Enduring Legacy of Now-\u2018Venerable\u2019 Father Patrick Peyton\", ''National Catholic Register'', January 4, 2018]</ref>\n\n==Lifetime crusade==\n{{Main|Family Rosary Crusade|Family Theater}}\nPeyton was given very light duties following the completion of his theological studies. His first assignment was in [[Albany, New York]], as the chaplain of the [[Holy Cross Brothers]] of the Vincentian Institute. Peyton started sending letters to bishops, Catholic laity, and other groups promoting the importance of families praying the Rosary as the war raged on.\n\nUtilizing radio, [[films]], [[outdoor advertising]] and later television, with the help of celebrities, artists and advertising practitioners, Peyton was one of the first pioneers of evangelism using [[mass media]]. He would also pioneer in conducting public rallies to bring families to pledge to pray the Rosary as a unit. These Rosary rallies attended by millions would become the most significant event where Peyton could be best remembered.  According to historian Hugh Wilford, \"Peyton himself was deeply conscious of the political dimension of his mission, proudly proclaiming in a 1946 radio broadcast, 'The rosary is the offensive weapon that will destroy Communism\u2014the great evil that seeks to destroy the faith'\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=GRIBBLE |first1=RICHARD  |date=2003 |title=Anti-Communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A. |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=535\u2013558 |doi= 10.1093/jcs/45.3.535|jstor=23920511 }}</ref>\n\nThese Rosary Crusades were duplicated in different dioceses with attendees growing in numbers, taking Peyton across the globe from [[Brussels, Belgium]], to [[Madrid, Spain]], across Asia to [[Manila, Philippines]], down south of the [[equator]] to New Zealand and [[Papua New Guinea]] and into several South American cities like [[Lima, Peru]], to [[Rio de Janeiro]] in [[Brazil]]. With the help of a non-Catholic advertising practitioner, Peyton would popularize the slogan, \"The family that prays together stays together.\"\n\n==Death and legacy==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:father patrick peyton rosary rally philippines.gif|left|thumb|350px|Peyton shaking hands with [[Filipinos]] who gathered for the Rosary Rally in [[Archdiocese of Manila|Manila]]. 1953]] -->\n\nWith the [[Cold War]] threatening a new world peace, Peyton's work in promoting prayer was recognized by the Holy See. His efforts earned him the title \"The Rosary Priest\".\n\nControversy hounded Peyton throughout his ministry as some accused him of being a front for American intelligence during his missions in Latin America. Peyton's Rosary Crusades in Latin America were funded and, to some extent, directed by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], which was interested in combating leftist political movements in Latin America.  This came about through Peyton's connection to [[J. Peter Grace]], the great-grandson of the founder of [[W.R. Grace and Company]], a multinational corporation with interests in transport, [[sugar]], and mining in South America, whom Peyton had met in 1946 on a trans-Atlantic voyage.  Grace, who was involved with other [[CIA]] front operations as well, wrote to John Moore, the chair of the Business Advisory Council, and the two men approached [[Allen Dulles]].  Dulles later met with Grace in the White House office of Vice President [[Richard Nixon]], who expressed enthusiasm.  The CIA decided for several years where the crusades would take place, and CIA funds were expended in [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Colombia]], until Peyton's provincial superior, Richard H. Sullivan, learned of the secret funding from [[Theodore Hesburgh]], the chair of the board of trustees of the [[University of Notre Dame]], in October 1964.  It took the [[Holy See|Vatican]] more than a year and a half to oblige Peyton to give up his CIA financing.<ref>Hugh Wilford, ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America'' [Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008], pp.&nbsp;182\u201396 .</ref> While the CIA determined the locations of the Crusades, it did not influence the content or Peyton's goal of promoting family prayer \u2013 the Rosary and devotion to the Blessed Mother.\n\nOthers accused Peyton of living an ostentatious lifestyle, living a life with Hollywood artists who volunteered their efforts in helping promote his mission. But Peyton maintained that he never solicited funds for his ministry, and the well-off were more than generous to voluntarily donate a portion of their wealth all in the name of the Blessed Mother.\n\nPeyton died peacefully on June 3, 1992, holding a rosary, in a small room at the Little Sisters of the Poor Jeanne Jugan Residence in [[San Pedro, California]]. His remains were brought to the Holy Cross Cemetery on the grounds of [[Stonehill College]] in [[Easton, Massachusetts]].\n\nBefore Peyton died, he continued to work on what was to be the last major Rosary Rally. On December 8, 1992, at the [[Rizal Park]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], Manila Archbishop [[Jaime Cardinal Sin]] led the celebrations for the Golden Jubilee Celebration of the [[Family Rosary Crusade]]; the Archbishop of Los Angeles, [[Roger Cardinal Mahony]] was sent as [[Papal Legate]] on behalf of [[Pope John Paul II]]. Among [[Filipino people|Filipino]] Catholics, Peyton is remembered for his Sunday televised shows, where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and [[Marian devotion]] along with his famous slogan. Peyton also encouraged many businesses to start making and selling large amounts of Rosaries for distribution, which he gave freely to impoverished Filipinos living in the slums.\n\nPeyton's work continues today in his original ministries \u2013 Family Rosary, Family Theater and Family Rosary International \u2013 and in the Father Patrick Peyton Family Institute.\n\n==Sainthood==\nCardinal [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Sean Patrick O\u2019Malley]] announced a formal declaration opening the cause for [[sainthood]] of Father Peyton on June 1, 2001, a few days after receiving approval from the Vatican's [[Congregation for the Causes of the Saints]]. The declaration paved the way for the process of determining Peyton's holiness and in the process earning the revered title of \"[[Servant of God]]\".\n\nThe [[Positio]] was sent to the C.C.S. in 2015 for assessment and theologians approved his cause on 1 June 2017. [[Pope Francis]] named him as [[Venerable]] on 18 December 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Citation\n|last=Peyton, CSC\n|first=Patrick\n|title=All For Her: An Autobiography of Father Patrick Peyton, CSC\n|publisher=Family Theater Publications, Hollywood California\n|origyear=1967|year=1996\n|asin= B0006CCAGY\n|url=http://www.christian-pages.com/si/2353.html}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Shiel\n|first=Tom\n|title=Cardinal urges Christians to twitter\n|publisher=Irish Times\n|date=April 27, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0427/1224245444798.html\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n |last        = Matilla\n |first       = Dexter R.\n |title       = 'Rosary priest' to be honored with sculpture\n |publisher   = Philippines Daily Inquirer\n |date        = March 31, 2009\n |url         = http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090430075846/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |archivedate = April 30, 2009\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Bourke\n|first=Toni\n|title=Fr Peyton remembered at 100th anniversary celebrations\n|publisher=Mayo Advertiser\n|date=April 17, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/mayo/article/11149\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Schworm\n|first=Peter\n|title=Dozens in Easton pray for canonization of the 'Rosary Priest'\n|work=Boston Globe\n|date=June 8, 2008\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2008/06/08/dozens_in_easton_pray_for_canonization_of_the_rosary_priest/\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Gribble\n|first=Richard\n|title=Anti-communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A.(Congregation of Holy Cross)\n|publisher=Journal of Church and State/J.M. Dawsons Studies on Church and State\n|date=June 22, 2003\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-829121_ITM\n}}.\n* \"Fifty Golden Years of the Family Rosary Crusade in the Philippines (1951-2001)\" written by Father [[James B. Reuter]], SJ; Gennie Q. Jota; Dean M. Bernardo, edited by Stella J. Villegas 2001 Family Rosary Crusade Foundation, Inc. \u00a9 2001\n* Wilford, Hugh. ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America''.  Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fatherpeyton.org Father Patrick Peyton, C.S.C. - Memorial Website]\n* [http://www.museumsofmayo.com/peyton1.htm Museum of Mayo]\n* [https://blog.familyrosary.org/ Family Rosary]\n* [http://www.familytheater.org Family Theater Productions]\n* [http://www.attymass.ie/peyton.htm Father Peyton Memorial Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120304053147/http://www.familyrosaryph.org/ Family Rosary Crusade - Philippines]\n\n{{canonization}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peyton, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century venerated Christians]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:American venerated Catholics]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Catholic television]]\n[[Category:Congregation of Holy Cross]]\n[[Category:Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Irish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish film producers]]\n[[Category:Irish radio producers]]\n[[Category:Irish television producers]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from County Mayo]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Television evangelists]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame people]]\n[[Category:Venerated Catholics by Pope Francis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish clergy]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSainthood:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Peyton"}
{"title_page": "Quotation", "text_new": "{{short description|Repetition of one expression as part of another one}}\n{{About|quoting text and speech|information about the punctuation mark|Quotation mark|economic usage|Financial quote|7=Quotation (disambiguation)|10=other uses|11=Quotation (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''quotation''' is the repetition of a sentence, phrase, or passage from speech or text that someone has said or written.<ref name=\"oxford\">{{cite book |editor1-last=McArthur |editor1-first=Tom |editor2-last=Lam-McArthur |editor2-first=Jacqueline |editor3-last=Fontaine |editor3-first=Lisa |title=The Oxford Companion to the English Language |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191744389 |edition=2nd}}</ref> In oral speech, it is the representation of an utterance (i.e. of something that a speaker actually said) that is introduced by a quotative marker, such as a verb of saying. For example: John said: \"I saw Mary today\". Quotations in oral speech are also signaled by special [[prosody (linguistics)|prosody]] in addition to quotative markers. In written text, quotations are signaled by quotation marks.<ref name=\"sdq bonami\">{{cite web |last1=Bonami |first1=Olivier |last2=Godard |first2=Dani\u00e8le |title=On the Syntax of Direct Quotation in French | date=2008 | url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00751080/document |website=HAL |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Quotations are also used to present well-known statement parts that are explicitly attributed by [[citation]] to their original source; such statements are marked with ([[punctuation|punctuated]] with) [[quotation mark]]s.\n\nQuotations are often used as a literary device to represent someone's point of view. They are also widely used in spoken language when an interlocutor wishes to present a proposition that they have come to know via hearsay.\n\n\n==Quotations as a literary device==\nA quotation can also refer to the repeated use of units of any other form of expression, especially parts of artistic works: elements of a [[painting]], scenes from a [[film|movie]] or sections from a [[musical composition]].\n\n===Reasons for using quotations as a literary device===\nQuotations are used for a variety of reasons: to illuminate the meaning or to support the arguments of the work in which it is being quoted, to provide direct information about the work being quoted (whether in order to discuss it, positively or negatively), to pay homage to the original work or [[author]], to make the user of the quotation seem well-read, and/or to comply with copyright law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elc.edu/english-grammar-lesson-using-quotes/|title=English Grammar Lesson - Using Quotes! - ELC|date=2016-11-16|work=ELC - English Language Center|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Quotations are also commonly printed as a means of inspiration and to invoke philosophical thoughts from the reader. Pragmatically speaking, quotations can also be used as language games (in the Wittgensteinian sense of the term) to manipulate social order and the structure of society.<ref>Capone, A., & Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2014). On indirect reports and language games: Evidence from Persian. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 8(2), 26-42.</ref><ref>Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2015). The secret life of slurs from the perspective of reported speech. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 9(2), 92-112.</ref>\n\n===Common quotation sources===\nFamous quotations are frequently collected in books that are sometimes called quotation dictionaries or treasuries.  Of these, ''[[Bartlett's Familiar Quotations]]'', ''[[The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations]]'', ''The [[Columbia University Press|Columbia]] Dictionary of Quotations'', ''[[The Yale Book of Quotations]]'' and ''The [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Book of Proverbs, Maxims, and Famous Phrases'' are considered among the most reliable and comprehensive sources.  Diaries and calendars often include quotations for entertainment or inspirational purposes, and small, dedicated sections in newspapers and weekly magazines\u2014with recent quotations by leading personalities on current topics\u2014have also become commonplace.\n\n===Misquotations===\n{{further|False attribution}}\n{{See also|List of movie misquotes}}\nMany quotations are routinely incorrect or attributed to the wrong authors, and quotations from obscure or unknown writers are often attributed to far more famous writers. Examples of this are [[Winston Churchill]], to whom many political quotations of uncertain origin are attributed, and [[Oscar Wilde]], to whom anonymous humorous quotations are sometimes attributed.<ref>See ''A Book of Misquotations'', edited by Elizabeth Knowles, Oxford University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Trek'' catchphrase \"[[Beam me up, Scotty]]\" did not appear in that form in the original series. Other misquotations include \"[[Just the facts, ma'am]]\" (attributed to [[Jack Webb]]'s character of [[Joe Friday]] on ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''), \"Heavy lies the crown\" from Shakespeare's Play [[Henry IV, Part 2]], \"[[Sherlock Holmes#\"Elementary, my dear Watson\"|Elementary, my dear Watson]]\" (attributed to [[Sherlock Holmes]]; it was, however, said in the films ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1929 film)|The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]''), \"[[Luke, I am your father]]\" (attributed to [[Darth Vader]] in [[Star Wars]]), \"[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Play it again, Sam]]\" (attributed to Ilsa in ''[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Casablanca]]''), \"[[Do you feel lucky, punk?]]\" (attributed to [[Dirty Harry (character)|Harry Callahan]] in ''[[Dirty Harry]]'') and \"[[Stinking badges|We don't need no stinkin' badges!]]\" (attributed to Gold Hat in ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'').<ref>The Holmes phrase originated in a radio play. See [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/quotes/signature/elementary.asp \"Elementary, My Dear Watson\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>Webb ''did'' say: \"All we want are the facts ma'am\". See [[Just the facts, ma'am]], [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/tv/dragnet.asp \"Just the Facts\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/moments02.html Greatest Film Misquotes - Part 2], Tim Dirks at filmsite.org</ref><ref>{{youtube|nsdZKCh6RsU|We Dont Need No Stinkin Badges!}} although the last of these is spoken by one of the Mexican Bandits that Hedley Lamarr attempts to hire as mercenaries in ''Blazing Saddles''</ref>\n\n===Quotative inversion===\nSubject-verb inversion occurs most often in written works, being rare in speech. <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref> Quotes may appear before the inverted verb, but can also appear after the subject <ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>, such as: \n\n:\"I am going to follow you all the rest of my life,\" declared the man.<ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>\n:Said the woman: \"I see you with both my eyes.\"<ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>\n\n\nIn English, both subject-verb and verb-subject word orders are permitted:\n\n:\"Don't turn back!\" warned Marcel <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref>\n:\"Who's on first?\" Joe demanded <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref>\n\n\nThis however, is not the case in all languages. For example, in Peninsular Spanish, this inversion is not allowed. Quotatives must follow verb-subject order:\n\n:''\u00abNo, no es un enanito\u00bb, rectifica el viejo.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Su\u00f1er |first1=Margarita |title=The Syntax of Direct Quotes with Special Reference to Spanish and English |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=August 2000 |volume=18 |issue=3 |page=532 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4047939 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n:\"No, he is not a gnome\", corrects the old man.\n\n:''*\u00abNo, no es un enanito\u00bb, el viejo rectifica.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matos |first1=Gabriel |title=Quotative Inversion in Peninsular Portuguese and Spanish, and in English |journal=Catalan Journal Of Linguistics |date=2013 |volume=12 |page=112 |doi=10.5565/rev/catjl.86 }}</ref>\n:\"No, he is not a gnome\", the old man corrects.\n\n==Quotations in spoken discourse==\n\nQuotations in spoken discourse are not intended to be [[verbatim]] reproductions of an utterance that has been produced. Instead, they convey the approximative meaning of such an utterance along with the way in which that utterance was produced. From a [[sociolinguistics|sociolinguistic]] perspective, a quotation in spoken discourse can therefore also be defined as \u201ca performance whereby speakers re-enact previous behaviour (speech/thought/sound/voice effect and gesture) while assuming the dramatic role of the original source of this reported behaviour\u201d.<ref name=\"buch\">{{cite book |last1=Buchstaller |first1=Isabelle |title=Quotatives: New Trends and Sociolinguistic Implications |date=2014 |publisher=Wiley Blackwell |isbn=9780470657188 |edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, quotations\u2014more specifically known as direct quotations<ref name=\"clark\" />\u2014have been distinguished from indirect quotations. Direct quotations differ from indirect quotations in that they are reported from the perspective of the experiencer, while indirect quotations are reported from the perspective of the reporting speaker (e.g. \"He said: 'I am leaving now'\u201d versus \"He said (that) he was leaving immediately\"); are free in their syntactic form, while indirect quotations are subject to language-specific structural requirements (e.g. indirect quotations in many [[Indo-European languages]] are required to have the syntactic form of a [[Well-formedness|well-formed]] declarative [[dependent clause|subordinate clause]]); incorporate extralinguistic material and pragmatic markers, while indirect quotations do not. Crucially, direct quotations have a performative aspect (i.e. occur simultaneously with re-enactments of previous behaviours), which indirect quotations lack.<ref name=\"buch\" /><ref name=\"clark\">{{cite journal |last1=Clark |first1=Herbert |last2=Gerrig |first2=Richard |title=Quotations as Demonstrations |journal=Language |date=December 1990 |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=764\u2013805 |doi=10.2307/414729 |jstor=414729 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Quotations-as-Demonstrations.-Clark-Gerrig/54571a1199be1954678338a879189359fab44182 |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reasons for using quotations in spoken discourse===\n\nQuotations are employed in spoken discourse for many reasons. They are often used by speakers to depict stories and events that have occurred in the past to other [[Interlocutor (linguistics)|interlocutors]]. The speaker does not necessarily have to have been an original participant in the story or event. Therefore, they can quote something that they did not hear firsthand. Quotations are also used to express thoughts that have never been uttered aloud prior to being quoted. For example, while telling a story, a speaker quotes inner thoughts that they had during a specific situation. Finally, speakers use quotations to propose future dialogue for participants in a situation that may take place in the future. For example, two friends talk about their 10-year high school reunion that will take place in the future and propose what they would say. While future dialogue can be proposed for a situation that will likely happen, it can also be based on a situation that will not actually take place. In the latter usage, the proposed dialogue only exists in the conversational context.<ref name=\"jessie\">{{cite journal |last1=Sams |first1=Jessie |title=Quoting the unspoken: An analysis of quotations in spoken discourse |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=November 2010 |volume=42 |issue=11 |pages=3147\u20133160 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2010.04.024 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216610001220 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe quoted material is usually not a verbatim replication of an utterance that someone originally said. Instead, quotations in spoken discourse reproduce what a speaker wishes to communicate to their recipients; quotations demonstrate something that someone said, the manner in which that person said it, and the current speaker\u2019s feelings about what was said.<ref name=\"jessie\" /><ref name=\"clark\" /> In this way, quotations are an especially effective storytelling device; the speaker is able to give a voice to the protagonists in their stories themselves, which allows the speaker\u2019s audience to experience the situation in the way that the speaker themselves experienced it.<ref name=\"buch\" />\n\n===Form of quotation===\n\nIn most languages, quotations in spoken discourse are introduced by a verb of saying and a pronoun. For example, a quotation in English can be introduced by \u201cShe said\u201d. In some languages, there is a discourse marker in addition to the verb of saying that functions as verbal quotation marks.<ref name=\"tracy\">{{cite book |authorlink1=Quotatives |editor1-last=Tracy |editor1-first=Karen |title=The international encyclopedia of language and social interaction |date=2015 |publisher=Wiley Blackwell |isbn=9781118611463 |pages=1272-1276}}</ref> For example, Japanese uses the quotative particle (a type of quotative marker) ''to'' along with the conjugated verb of saying ''itta'':\n\nGloss: TOP=Topic Marker DAT=Dative NOM=Nominative COM=complementizer\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u3086\u304d || \u306f || \u3042\u306a\u305f\u3000|| \u306b\u306f || \u5f7c\u5973 || \u304c || \u597d\u304d || \u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u305f \u3002<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n|-\n| Yuki || wa || anata|| ni wa || kanocho || ga || suki || '''to''' || '''itta''' .\n|-\n| Yuki|| TOP || you || DAT || her || NOM || like || COM || said\n|-\n| colspan=9|\"''Yuki said that you liked her.''\"\n|}\n\nVerbs of saying (also known as quotative verbs) and quotative particles, along with quotative evidentials, are different types of quotative markers, which signal quotations in utterances.<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\n====Quotative markers====\nQuotative markers are used to mark a section of an utterance as quoted speech (i.e. a quotation). In oral speech, quotative markers act as quotation marks and often include a verb of saying (e.g. ''say''). A quotative marker appears either before or after the reported speech or thought, depending on the syntax of the language.<ref name=\"tracy\"/> For example, compare English and Japanese:\n\n'''English:'''\n\nIn English, the quotative verb ''say'' occurs before the quotation:<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n  She '''said''' \u201cWill you answer the phone, will you answer the phone\u201d<ref name=\"frederica\"> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005.</ref>\n\nIn English, verbs such as ''be like'', ''go'', and ''be all'' are non-standard quotatives that are commonly used in colloquial speech.<ref name=\"tracy\"/> They are observed in the speech of young people not only in American English, but in English spoken in places like Glasgow, Scotland as well.<ref name=\"adfoolen\">{{cite book |authorlink1=New quotative markers in spoken discourse |editor1-last=Ahrenholz |editor1-first=Bernt |editor2-last=Bredel |editor2-first=Ursula |editor3-last=Klein |editor3-first=Wolfgang |editor4-last=Rost-Roth |editor4-first=Martina |editor5-last=Skiba |editor5-first=Romuald |title=Empirische Forschung und Theoriebildung |date=2008 |publisher=Peter Lang |location=Frankfurt am Main |isbn=978-3-631-56930-6 |pages=117-128}}</ref><ref name=\"frederica\"/> Though not semantically considered a verb of saying, they are used as verbs of saying. Like ''say'', ''be like'', ''go'', and ''be all'' occur before the quotation:<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n  I'm '''like''' \"I'm so sorry you had to wait\"<ref name=\"frederica\"/>\n\nIn conversational speech, the use of ''say'' and ''be like'' occurs at about the same frequency<ref name=\"frederica\"/>, though ''say'' tends to be used in more formal contexts (e.g. office hours between professors and students) and ''be like'' tends to occur in more informal contexts (e.g. a conversation between two young people).<ref name=\"adfoolen\"/>\n\n'''Japanese:'''\n\nIn Japanese, the quotative particle ''to'' along with the verb of saying ''iu'' (say) occur after the quotation; the conjugated form of ''iu'' (say) is ''itta'':<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\nGloss: TOP=Topic Marker AKK=Accusative COM=Complementizer HON=Honorific/Polite form\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u592a\u90ce || \u306f || \u6674\u6d77\u3000|| \u3092 || \u618e\u3093\u3067\u3044\u308b || \u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u305f\u3002<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\"/>\n|-\n| Taro || wa || Harumi || o || nikundeiru || '''to''' || '''itta'''.\n|-\n| Taro || TOP || Harumi || AKK || nikundeiru || COM || said\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''Taro said that he hated Harumi.''\" lit. \"''that 'I hated Harumi''''\"\n|}\n\nThe quotative particle ''to'' can also occur with verbs of thinking, such as ''omou'' (think). Like ''to'' and ''iu'' (say),  ''to'' and ''omou'' occur after the quotation.\n\n\nIn addition to quotative markers, speakers also use prosodic shifts, pauses, pronominal choices, and tense to detect the occurrence and boundaries of quotations in spoken utterances.<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\n==== Spanish ====\n===== Quotative Verb =====\n\n===Syntax of quotation===\nDifferent versions of quotative verbs, particles, and evidentials can be used to express the same idea with varying nuances, often to frame how the primary speaker, or the person who is quoting, feels about a quotation. The syntax of quotations varies cross-linguistically. A primary speaker may use the tense and linguistic idiosyncrasies of the speech at the time it was uttered in a quotation, independent from the tense in the main clause in some languages, or use the same tense in both the main clause and quotation in other languages. They will also use [[coreference|coreferenced]] pronouns to the direct quotation's first-person subject in the main clause: She<sub>x</sub> said, \"I<sub>x</sub>...\"; they<sub>y</sub> said \"we<sub>y</sub> ...\" In many languages, the primary speaker may also attempt to quote an utterance in the same language the original speaker used, even if an interlocutor does not understand it; however, it is mainly context-dependent such as when telling stories.  <ref name=\"Evans Canonical\">{{cite book |last1=Evans |first1=Nicholas |title=Canonical Morphology and Syntax |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |chapter=Some problems in the typology of quotation: a canonical approach}}</ref><ref name=\"Klamer report\">{{cite journal |last1=Klamer |first1=Marian |title=How report verbs become quote markers and complementisers |journal=Lingua |date=2000 |volume=110 |issue=2 |pages=69\u201398 |doi=10.1016/S0024-3841(99)00032-7|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0024384199000327 | accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DarcyA Review>{{cite journal |last1=D'Arcy |first1=Alexandra |title=Quotation and advances in understanding syntactic systems |journal=Annual Review of Linguistics |date=2015 |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=43-61 |doi=10.1146/annurev-linguist-030514-125220}}</ref>\n\n=====Quotative verbs=====\nQuotative verbs are lexical verbs that indicate the speech, thoughts, or perceptions of the original speaker.<ref name=\"Evans Canonical\"/><ref name=\"Klamer report\"/>\n\nQuotations can be introduced as the complement to a quotative verb or as the head phrase to an adjunct phrase containing a quotative verb in some languages like English and French.<ref name=\"sdq bonami\"/><ref name=\"DarcyA Review/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! ||Quotation as complement || Quotation as head phrase adjunct <ref name=\"sdq bonami\"/>\n|-\n| English || Marie said, \u201cMy brother has arrived.\u201d || \u201cMy brother has arrived,\" as Marie said.\n|-\n| French || Marie a dit, \u201cMon fr\u00e8re est arriv\u00e9.\u201d || \u201cMon fr\u00e8re est arriv\u00e9,\" comme a dit Marie.\n|}\nEnglish also displays [[verb-second]] (V2) order vestige only in quotation contexts (quotative inversion), requiring the finite verb to appear in the second position of a clause. For example: \"No no no\" ''says'' Harry. <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/>\n\nDirect and indirect quotations are sometimes not distinguishable. Traditionally, English uses an overt complementizer ''that'' after a quotative verb to indicate indirect quotation, but it is also seen to prompt direct quotation in some English varieties like Indian English, Hong Kong English, and Kenyan English.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Hong Kong English || After the movie I just ''said that'' \"Oh Frank I cannot walk.\" <ref name=\"DarcyA Review\"/>\n|-\n| Indian English || Never a husband ''says that'' \"I'll make a cup of tea okay, you sit. I'll make a cup of tea.\"\n|-\n| Kenyan English || So Kabuwe Abuwe ''told'' us ''that'' \"If it is for wedding I am not going to contribute.\"\n|}\n\n=====Quotative particles=====\nQuotative or hearsay particles are grammatical markers equivalent to full lexical verbs with meanings of ''\"say, mention, tell, etc.\"'' In many languages, they are [[grammaticalization|grammaticalized]] to different extremes from their previously lexical form. Common patterns of grammaticalization trajectories include verb to complementizer in many African and Asian languages and verb to [[tense-aspect-mood]] markers primarily in African languages, but also in Australian languages and multiple other [[language family|language families]]. <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/><ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\">{{cite journal |last1=Matsui |first1=Tomoko |last2=Yamamoto |first2=Taeko |title=Developing sensitivity to the sources of information: Early use of the Japanese quotative particles tte and to in mother\u2013child conversation |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=2013 |volume=59 |issue= |pages=5\u201325 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2013.06.008 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216613001598|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapanese, for example, uses a sentence-final quotative particle ''tte'' verbally to mean \"I heard (quote)\" with some uncertainty. In sentence-medial position, ''tte'' is sometimes regarded along with ''to'' to be either a quotative particle or complementizer meaning \"I heard (quote)\" with less uncertainty and often more knowledge of the origin of the quote.\n\nGloss: QP=Quotative Particle FP=Final Particle\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u660e\u65e5 || \u6674\u308c\u308b || -\u3063\u3066\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''It will be fine tomorrow, I heard.''\"\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u660e\u65e5 || \u6674\u308c\u308b || -\u3063\u3066/\u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u3066\u305f\u3000||\u3000\u3088\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''/''to'' || itteta || yo.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP || said || FP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''(X) said that it would be fine tomorrow.''\"\n|}\n\nVerbs of saying are highly restricted in Australian languages and almost always immediately proceed the complement verb. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  [[Ngarinyin language|Ngarinyin]] example <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/> !!!!\n|-\n| wurlan || wurr-u-miyangga || bud-ma-ra-ngarrugu\n|-\n| word || 3PL-FUT-know || 3PL-say-PST-1PL.OBL.IRR\n|-\n| colspan=7|''\"They will know this word\" they said to us.''\n|}\n\n=====Quotative evidentials=====\nQuotative evidentials provide knowledge of who or where information originated from in speech. Languages indicate this in various ways such as through additional words and phrases, prosody, gestures, or required endings of verbs. For example, English can express evidentials with an optional adverb, \"''Allegedly'', Annie pulled the trigger.\" The interlocutor then knows where the source of the quotation is from. <ref name=\"SRL Ev>{{cite journal |last1=San Roque |first1=Lila |title=Evidentiality |journal=Annual Review of Anthropology |date=2019 |volume=48 |issue= |pages=353\u2013370 |doi=10.1146/annurev-anthro-102218-011243 }}</ref> Similar to quotative particles, quotative evidentials are usually [[grammaticalization|grammaticalized]] from full lexical verbs. <ref name=\"Chojnicka Latvian\">{{cite journal |last1=Chojnicka |first1=Joanna |title=Latvian verbs of speaking and their relations to evidentiality |journal=Kalbotyra |issue=69 |page=59-81}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource portal|Quotations}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adage]]\n*[[Aphorism]]\n*[[Block quotation]]\n*[[Epigram]]\n*[[Fallacy of quoting out of context]]\n*[[Saying|Maxim (saying)]]\n*[[Musical quotation]]\n*[[Nested quotation]]\n*[[Proverb]]\n*[[Scare quotes]]\n*[[Sic]]\n*[[Use\u2013mention distinction]]\n*[[Quotation mark]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\">Florian Coulmas (Ed.). ''Direct and Indirect Speech (Trends in Linguistics: Studies and Monographs)'', p.164. {{ISBN|978-3110105995}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Appropriation in the arts|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Quotations| ]]\n[[Category:Communication]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Repetition of one expression as part of another one}}\n{{About|quoting text and speech|information about the punctuation mark|Quotation mark|economic usage|Financial quote|7=Quotation (disambiguation)|10=other uses|11=Quotation (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''quotation''' is the repetition of a sentence, phrase, or passage from speech or text that someone has said or written.<ref name=\"oxford\">{{cite book |editor1-last=McArthur |editor1-first=Tom |editor2-last=Lam-McArthur |editor2-first=Jacqueline |editor3-last=Fontaine |editor3-first=Lisa |title=The Oxford Companion to the English Language |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191744389 |edition=2nd}}</ref> In oral speech, it is the representation of an utterance (i.e. of something that a speaker actually said) that is introduced by a quotative marker, such as a verb of saying. For example: John said: \"I saw Mary today\". Quotations in oral speech are also signaled by special [[prosody (linguistics)|prosody]] in addition to quotative markers. In written text, quotations are signaled by quotation marks.<ref name=\"sdq bonami\">{{cite web |last1=Bonami |first1=Olivier |last2=Godard |first2=Dani\u00e8le |title=On the Syntax of Direct Quotation in French | date=2008 | url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00751080/document |website=HAL |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Quotations are also used to present well-known statement parts that are explicitly attributed by [[citation]] to their original source; such statements are marked with ([[punctuation|punctuated]] with) [[quotation mark]]s.\n\nQuotations are often used as a literary device to represent someone's point of view. They are also widely used in spoken language when an interlocutor wishes to present a proposition that they have come to know via hearsay.\n\n\n==Quotations as a literary device==\nA quotation can also refer to the repeated use of units of any other form of expression, especially parts of artistic works: elements of a [[painting]], scenes from a [[film|movie]] or sections from a [[musical composition]].\n\n===Reasons for using quotations as a literary device===\nQuotations are used for a variety of reasons: to illuminate the meaning or to support the arguments of the work in which it is being quoted, to provide direct information about the work being quoted (whether in order to discuss it, positively or negatively), to pay homage to the original work or [[author]], to make the user of the quotation seem well-read, and/or to comply with copyright law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elc.edu/english-grammar-lesson-using-quotes/|title=English Grammar Lesson - Using Quotes! - ELC|date=2016-11-16|work=ELC - English Language Center|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Quotations are also commonly printed as a means of inspiration and to invoke philosophical thoughts from the reader. Pragmatically speaking, quotations can also be used as language games (in the Wittgensteinian sense of the term) to manipulate social order and the structure of society.<ref>Capone, A., & Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2014). On indirect reports and language games: Evidence from Persian. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 8(2), 26-42.</ref><ref>Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2015). The secret life of slurs from the perspective of reported speech. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 9(2), 92-112.</ref>\n\n===Common quotation sources===\nFamous quotations are frequently collected in books that are sometimes called quotation dictionaries or treasuries.  Of these, ''[[Bartlett's Familiar Quotations]]'', ''[[The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations]]'', ''The [[Columbia University Press|Columbia]] Dictionary of Quotations'', ''[[The Yale Book of Quotations]]'' and ''The [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Book of Proverbs, Maxims, and Famous Phrases'' are considered among the most reliable and comprehensive sources.  Diaries and calendars often include quotations for entertainment or inspirational purposes, and small, dedicated sections in newspapers and weekly magazines\u2014with recent quotations by leading personalities on current topics\u2014have also become commonplace.\n\n===Misquotations===\n{{further|False attribution}}\n{{See also|List of movie misquotes}}\nMany quotations are routinely incorrect or attributed to the wrong authors, and quotations from obscure or unknown writers are often attributed to far more famous writers. Examples of this are [[Winston Churchill]], to whom many political quotations of uncertain origin are attributed, and [[Oscar Wilde]], to whom anonymous humorous quotations are sometimes attributed.<ref>See ''A Book of Misquotations'', edited by Elizabeth Knowles, Oxford University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Trek'' catchphrase \"[[Beam me up, Scotty]]\" did not appear in that form in the original series. Other misquotations include \"[[Just the facts, ma'am]]\" (attributed to [[Jack Webb]]'s character of [[Joe Friday]] on ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''), \"Heavy lies the crown\" from Shakespeare's Play [[Henry IV, Part 2]], \"[[Sherlock Holmes#\"Elementary, my dear Watson\"|Elementary, my dear Watson]]\" (attributed to [[Sherlock Holmes]]; it was, however, said in the films ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1929 film)|The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]''), \"[[Luke, I am your father]]\" (attributed to [[Darth Vader]] in [[Star Wars]]), \"[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Play it again, Sam]]\" (attributed to Ilsa in ''[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Casablanca]]''), \"[[Do you feel lucky, punk?]]\" (attributed to [[Dirty Harry (character)|Harry Callahan]] in ''[[Dirty Harry]]'') and \"[[Stinking badges|We don't need no stinkin' badges!]]\" (attributed to Gold Hat in ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'').<ref>The Holmes phrase originated in a radio play. See [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/quotes/signature/elementary.asp \"Elementary, My Dear Watson\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>Webb ''did'' say: \"All we want are the facts ma'am\". See [[Just the facts, ma'am]], [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/tv/dragnet.asp \"Just the Facts\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/moments02.html Greatest Film Misquotes - Part 2], Tim Dirks at filmsite.org</ref><ref>{{youtube|nsdZKCh6RsU|We Dont Need No Stinkin Badges!}} although the last of these is spoken by one of the Mexican Bandits that Hedley Lamarr attempts to hire as mercenaries in ''Blazing Saddles''</ref>\n\n===Quotative inversion===\nSubject-verb inversion occurs most often in written works, being rare in speech. <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref> Quotes may appear before the inverted verb, but can also appear after the subject <ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>, such as: \n\n:\"I am going to follow you all the rest of my life,\" declared the man.<ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>\n:Said the woman: \"I see you with both my eyes.\"<ref name=\"bruening\">{{cite journal |last1=Bruening |first1=Benjamin |title=Alignment in Syntax: Quotative Inversion in English |journal=Syntax |date=15 April 2016 |volume=19 |issue=2 |page=113 |doi=10.1111/synt.12121 }}</ref>\n\n\nIn English, both subject-verb and verb-subject word orders are permitted:\n\n:\"Don't turn back!\" warned Marcel <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref>\n:\"Who's on first?\" Joe demanded <ref name=\"collins\">{{cite journal |last1=Collins |first1=Chris |last2=Branigan |first2=Phil |title=Quotative Inversion |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=February 1997 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=1-41 |doi=10.1023/A:1005722729974 }}</ref>\n\n\nThis however, is not the case in all languages. For example, in Peninsular Spanish, this inversion is not allowed. Quotatives must follow verb-subject order:\n\n:''\u00abNo, no es un enanito\u00bb, rectifica el viejo.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Su\u00f1er |first1=Margarita |title=The Syntax of Direct Quotes with Special Reference to Spanish and English |journal=Natural Language & Linguistic Theory |date=August 2000 |volume=18 |issue=3 |page=532 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4047939 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n:\"No, he is not a gnome\", corrects the old man.\n\n:''*\u00abNo, no es un enanito\u00bb, el viejo rectifica.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matos |first1=Gabriel |title=Quotative Inversion in Peninsular Portuguese and Spanish, and in English |journal=Catalan Journal Of Linguistics |date=2013 |volume=12 |page=112 |doi=10.5565/rev/catjl.86 }}</ref>\n:\"No, he is not a gnome\", the old man corrects.\n\n==Quotations in spoken discourse==\n\nQuotations in spoken discourse are not intended to be [[verbatim]] reproductions of an utterance that has been produced. Instead, they convey the approximative meaning of such an utterance along with the way in which that utterance was produced. From a [[sociolinguistics|sociolinguistic]] perspective, a quotation in spoken discourse can therefore also be defined as \u201ca performance whereby speakers re-enact previous behaviour (speech/thought/sound/voice effect and gesture) while assuming the dramatic role of the original source of this reported behaviour\u201d.<ref name=\"buch\">{{cite book |last1=Buchstaller |first1=Isabelle |title=Quotatives: New Trends and Sociolinguistic Implications |date=2014 |publisher=Wiley Blackwell |isbn=9780470657188 |edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally, quotations\u2014more specifically known as direct quotations<ref name=\"clark\" />\u2014have been distinguished from indirect quotations. Direct quotations differ from indirect quotations in that they are reported from the perspective of the experiencer, while indirect quotations are reported from the perspective of the reporting speaker (e.g. \"He said: 'I am leaving now'\u201d versus \"He said (that) he was leaving immediately\"); are free in their syntactic form, while indirect quotations are subject to language-specific structural requirements (e.g. indirect quotations in many [[Indo-European languages]] are required to have the syntactic form of a [[Well-formedness|well-formed]] declarative [[dependent clause|subordinate clause]]); incorporate extralinguistic material and pragmatic markers, while indirect quotations do not. Crucially, direct quotations have a performative aspect (i.e. occur simultaneously with re-enactments of previous behaviours), which indirect quotations lack.<ref name=\"buch\" /><ref name=\"clark\">{{cite journal |last1=Clark |first1=Herbert |last2=Gerrig |first2=Richard |title=Quotations as Demonstrations |journal=Language |date=December 1990 |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=764\u2013805 |doi=10.2307/414729 |jstor=414729 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Quotations-as-Demonstrations.-Clark-Gerrig/54571a1199be1954678338a879189359fab44182 |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reasons for using quotations in spoken discourse===\n\nQuotations are employed in spoken discourse for many reasons. They are often used by speakers to depict stories and events that have occurred in the past to other [[Interlocutor (linguistics)|interlocutors]]. The speaker does not necessarily have to have been an original participant in the story or event. Therefore, they can quote something that they did not hear firsthand. Quotations are also used to express thoughts that have never been uttered aloud prior to being quoted. For example, while telling a story, a speaker quotes inner thoughts that they had during a specific situation. Finally, speakers use quotations to propose future dialogue for participants in a situation that may take place in the future. For example, two friends talk about their 10-year high school reunion that will take place in the future and propose what they would say. While future dialogue can be proposed for a situation that will likely happen, it can also be based on a situation that will not actually take place. In the latter usage, the proposed dialogue only exists in the conversational context.<ref name=\"jessie\">{{cite journal |last1=Sams |first1=Jessie |title=Quoting the unspoken: An analysis of quotations in spoken discourse |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=November 2010 |volume=42 |issue=11 |pages=3147\u20133160 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2010.04.024 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216610001220 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe quoted material is usually not a verbatim replication of an utterance that someone originally said. Instead, quotations in spoken discourse reproduce what a speaker wishes to communicate to their recipients; quotations demonstrate something that someone said, the manner in which that person said it, and the current speaker\u2019s feelings about what was said.<ref name=\"jessie\" /><ref name=\"clark\" /> In this way, quotations are an especially effective storytelling device; the speaker is able to give a voice to the protagonists in their stories themselves, which allows the speaker\u2019s audience to experience the situation in the way that the speaker themselves experienced it.<ref name=\"buch\" />\n\n===Form of quotation===\n\nIn most languages, quotations in spoken discourse are introduced by a verb of saying and a pronoun. For example, a quotation in English can be introduced by \u201cShe said\u201d. In some languages, there is a discourse marker in addition to the verb of saying that functions as verbal quotation marks.<ref name=\"tracy\">{{cite book |authorlink1=Quotatives |editor1-last=Tracy |editor1-first=Karen |title=The international encyclopedia of language and social interaction |date=2015 |publisher=Wiley Blackwell |isbn=9781118611463 |pages=1272-1276}}</ref> For example, Japanese uses the quotative particle (a type of quotative marker) ''to'' along with the conjugated verb of saying ''itta'':\n\nGloss: TOP=Topic Marker DAT=Dative NOM=Nominative COM=complementizer\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u3086\u304d || \u306f || \u3042\u306a\u305f\u3000|| \u306b\u306f || \u5f7c\u5973 || \u304c || \u597d\u304d || \u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u305f \u3002<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n|-\n| Yuki || wa || anata|| ni wa || kanocho || ga || suki || '''to''' || '''itta''' .\n|-\n| Yuki|| TOP || you || DAT || her || NOM || like || COM || said\n|-\n| colspan=9|\"''Yuki said that you liked her.''\"\n|}\n\nVerbs of saying (also known as quotative verbs) and quotative particles, along with quotative evidentials, are different types of quotative markers, which signal quotations in utterances.<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\n====Quotative markers====\nQuotative markers are used to mark a section of an utterance as quoted speech (i.e. a quotation). In oral speech, quotative markers act as quotation marks and often include a verb of saying (e.g. ''say''). A quotative marker appears either before or after the reported speech or thought, depending on the syntax of the language.<ref name=\"tracy\"/> For example, compare English and Japanese:\n\n'''English:'''\n\nIn English, the quotative verb ''say'' occurs before the quotation:<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n  She '''said''' \u201cWill you answer the phone, will you answer the phone\u201d<ref name=\"frederica\"> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005.</ref>\n\nIn English, verbs such as ''be like'', ''go'', and ''be all'' are non-standard quotatives that are commonly used in colloquial speech.<ref name=\"tracy\"/> They are observed in the speech of young people not only in American English, but in English spoken in places like Glasgow, Scotland as well.<ref name=\"adfoolen\">{{cite book |authorlink1=New quotative markers in spoken discourse |editor1-last=Ahrenholz |editor1-first=Bernt |editor2-last=Bredel |editor2-first=Ursula |editor3-last=Klein |editor3-first=Wolfgang |editor4-last=Rost-Roth |editor4-first=Martina |editor5-last=Skiba |editor5-first=Romuald |title=Empirische Forschung und Theoriebildung |date=2008 |publisher=Peter Lang |location=Frankfurt am Main |isbn=978-3-631-56930-6 |pages=117-128}}</ref><ref name=\"frederica\"/> Though not semantically considered a verb of saying, they are used as verbs of saying. Like ''say'', ''be like'', ''go'', and ''be all'' occur before the quotation:<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n  I'm '''like''' \"I'm so sorry you had to wait\"<ref name=\"frederica\"/>\n\nIn conversational speech, the use of ''say'' and ''be like'' occurs at about the same frequency<ref name=\"frederica\"/>, though ''say'' tends to be used in more formal contexts (e.g. office hours between professors and students) and ''be like'' tends to occur in more informal contexts (e.g. a conversation between two young people).<ref name=\"adfoolen\"/>\n\n'''Japanese:'''\n\nIn Japanese, the quotative particle ''to'' along with the verb of saying ''iu'' (say) occur after the quotation; the conjugated form of ''iu'' (say) is ''itta'':<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\nGloss: TOP=Topic Marker AKK=Accusative COM=Complementizer HON=Honorific/Polite form\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u592a\u90ce || \u306f || \u6674\u6d77\u3000|| \u3092 || \u618e\u3093\u3067\u3044\u308b || \u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u305f\u3002<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\"/>\n|-\n| Taro || wa || Harumi || o || nikundeiru || '''to''' || '''itta'''.\n|-\n| Taro || TOP || Harumi || AKK || nikundeiru || COM || said\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''Taro said that he hated Harumi.''\" lit. \"''that 'I hated Harumi''''\"\n|}\n\nThe quotative particle ''to'' can also occur with verbs of thinking, such as ''omou'' (think). Like ''to'' and ''iu'' (say),  ''to'' and ''omou'' occur after the quotation.\n\n\nIn addition to quotative markers, speakers also use prosodic shifts, pauses, pronominal choices, and tense to detect the occurrence and boundaries of quotations in spoken utterances.<ref name=\"tracy\"/>\n\n==== Spanish ====\n===== Quotative Verb =====\n\n===Syntax of quotation===\nDifferent versions of quotative verbs, particles, and evidentials can be used to express the same idea with varying nuances, often to frame how the primary speaker, or the person who is quoting, feels about a quotation. The syntax of quotations varies cross-linguistically. A primary speaker may use the tense and linguistic idiosyncrasies of the speech at the time it was uttered in a quotation, independent from the tense in the main clause in some languages, or use the same tense in both the main clause and quotation in other languages. They will also use [[coreference|coreferenced]] pronouns to the direct quotation's first-person subject in the main clause: She<sub>x</sub> said, \"I<sub>x</sub>...\"; they<sub>y</sub> said \"we<sub>y</sub> ...\" In many languages, the primary speaker may also attempt to quote an utterance in the same language the original speaker used, even if an interlocutor does not understand it; however, it is mainly context-dependent such as when telling stories.  <ref name=\"Evans Canonical\">{{cite book |last1=Evans |first1=Nicholas |title=Canonical Morphology and Syntax |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |chapter=Some problems in the typology of quotation: a canonical approach}}</ref><ref name=\"Klamer report\">{{cite journal |last1=Klamer |first1=Marian |title=How report verbs become quote markers and complementisers |journal=Lingua |date=2000 |volume=110 |issue=2 |pages=69\u201398 |doi=10.1016/S0024-3841(99)00032-7|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0024384199000327 | accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DarcyA Review>{{cite journal |last1=D'Arcy |first1=Alexandra |title=Quotation and advances in understanding syntactic systems |journal=Annual Review of Linguistics |volume=1 |issue=1 |page=43-61 |doi=10.1146/annurev-linguist-030514-125220}}</ref>\n\n=====Quotative verbs=====\nQuotative verbs are lexical verbs that indicate the speech, thoughts, or perceptions of the original speaker.<ref name=\"Evans Canonical\"/><ref name=\"Klamer report\"/>\n\nQuotations can be introduced as the complement to a quotative verb or as the head phrase to an adjunct phrase containing a quotative verb in some languages like English and French.<ref name=\"sdq bonami\"/><ref name=\"DarcyA Review/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! ||Quotation as complement || Quotation as head phrase adjunct <ref name=\"sdq bonami\"/>\n|-\n| English || Marie said, \u201cMy brother has arrived.\u201d || \u201cMy brother has arrived,\" as Marie said.\n|-\n| French || Marie a dit, \u201cMon fr\u00e8re est arriv\u00e9.\u201d || \u201cMon fr\u00e8re est arriv\u00e9,\" comme a dit Marie.\n|}\nEnglish also displays [[verb-second]] (V2) order vestige only in quotation contexts (quotative inversion), requiring the finite verb to appear in the second position of a clause. For example: \"No no no\" ''says'' Harry. <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/>\n\nDirect and indirect quotations are sometimes not distinguishable. Traditionally, English uses an overt complementizer ''that'' after a quotative verb to indicate indirect quotation, but it is also seen to prompt direct quotation in some English varieties like Indian English, Hong Kong English, and Kenyan English.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Hong Kong English || After the movie I just ''said that'' \"Oh Frank I cannot walk.\" <ref name=\"DarcyA Review\"/>\n|-\n| Indian English || Never a husband ''says that'' \"I'll make a cup of tea okay, you sit. I'll make a cup of tea.\"\n|-\n| Kenyan English || So Kabuwe Abuwe ''told'' us ''that'' \"If it is for wedding I am not going to contribute.\"\n|}\n\n=====Quotative particles=====\nQuotative or hearsay particles are grammatical markers equivalent to full lexical verbs with meanings of ''\"say, mention, tell, etc.\"'' In many languages, they are [[grammaticalization|grammaticalized]] to different extremes from their previously lexical form. Common patterns of grammaticalization trajectories include verb to complementizer in many African and Asian languages and verb to [[tense-aspect-mood]] markers primarily in African languages, but also in Australian languages and multiple other [[language family|language families]]. <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/><ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\">{{cite journal |last1=Matsui |first1=Tomoko |last2=Yamamoto |first2=Taeko |title=Developing sensitivity to the sources of information: Early use of the Japanese quotative particles tte and to in mother\u2013child conversation |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=2013 |volume=59 |issue= |pages=5\u201325 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2013.06.008 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216613001598|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapanese, for example, uses a sentence-final quotative particle ''tte'' verbally to mean \"I heard (quote)\" with some uncertainty. In sentence-medial position, ''tte'' is sometimes regarded along with ''to'' to be either a quotative particle or complementizer meaning \"I heard (quote)\" with less uncertainty and often more knowledge of the origin of the quote.\n\nGloss: QP=Quotative Particle FP=Final Particle\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u660e\u65e5 || \u6674\u308c\u308b || -\u3063\u3066\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''It will be fine tomorrow, I heard.''\"\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| \u660e\u65e5 || \u6674\u308c\u308b || -\u3063\u3066/\u3068 || \u8a00\u3063\u3066\u305f\u3000||\u3000\u3088\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''/''to'' || itteta || yo.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP || said || FP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''(X) said that it would be fine tomorrow.''\"\n|}\n\nVerbs of saying are highly restricted in Australian languages and almost always immediately proceed the complement verb. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  [[Ngarinyin language|Ngarinyin]] example <ref name=\"DarcyA Review/> !!!!\n|-\n| wurlan || wurr-u-miyangga || bud-ma-ra-ngarrugu\n|-\n| word || 3PL-FUT-know || 3PL-say-PST-1PL.OBL.IRR\n|-\n| colspan=7|''\"They will know this word\" they said to us.''\n|}\n\n=====Quotative evidentials=====\nQuotative evidentials provide knowledge of who or where information originated from in speech. Languages indicate this in various ways such as through additional words and phrases, prosody, gestures, or required endings of verbs. For example, English can express evidentials with an optional adverb, \"''Allegedly'', Annie pulled the trigger.\" The interlocutor then knows where the source of the quotation is from. <ref name=\"SRL Ev>{{cite journal |last1=San Roque |first1=Lila |title=Evidentiality |journal=Annual Review of Anthropology |date=2019 |volume=48 |issue= |pages=353\u2013370 |doi=10.1146/annurev-anthro-102218-011243 }}</ref> Similar to quotative particles, quotative evidentials are usually [[grammaticalization|grammaticalized]] from full lexical verbs. <ref name=\"Chojnicka Latvian\">{{cite journal |last1=Chojnicka |first1=Joanna |title=Latvian verbs of speaking and their relations to evidentiality |journal=Kalbotyra |issue=69 |page=59-81}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource portal|Quotations}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adage]]\n*[[Aphorism]]\n*[[Block quotation]]\n*[[Epigram]]\n*[[Fallacy of quoting out of context]]\n*[[Saying|Maxim (saying)]]\n*[[Musical quotation]]\n*[[Nested quotation]]\n*[[Proverb]]\n*[[Scare quotes]]\n*[[Sic]]\n*[[Use\u2013mention distinction]]\n*[[Quotation mark]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\">Florian Coulmas (Ed.). ''Direct and Indirect Speech (Trends in Linguistics: Studies and Monographs)'', p.164. {{ISBN|978-3110105995}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Appropriation in the arts|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Quotations| ]]\n[[Category:Communication]]\n", "name_user": "FUNG F", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSyntax of quotation:added year to citation source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotation"}
{"title_page": "Joe Biden", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Redirect|Biden|other members of his family|Biden family|other uses|Biden (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2019}}\n{{short description|47th vice president of the United States}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Joe Biden\n| image               = Joe Biden official portrait 2013 cropped.jpg <!--Do not change until a final consensus has been established in the talk page-->\n| caption             = \n| office              = 47th [[Vice President of the United States]]\n| president           = [[Barack Obama]]\n| term_start          = January 20, 2009\n| term_end            = January 20, 2017\n| predecessor         = [[Dick Cheney]]\n| successor           = [[Mike Pence]]\n| jr/sr1              = United States Senator\n| state1              = [[Delaware]]\n| term_start1         = January 3, 1973\n| term_end1           = January 15, 2009\n| predecessor1        = [[J. Caleb Boggs]]\n| successor1          = [[Ted Kaufman]]\n| office2             = Chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]]\n| term_start2         = January 3, 2007\n| term_end2           = January 3, 2009\n| predecessor2        = [[Richard Lugar]]\n| successor2          = [[John Kerry]]\n| term_start3         = June 6, 2001\n| term_end3           = January 3, 2003\n| predecessor3        = [[Jesse Helms]]\n| successor3          = [[Richard Lugar]]\n| term_start4         = January 3, 2001\n| term_end4           = January 20, 2001\n| predecessor4        = [[Jesse Helms]]\n| successor4          = [[Jesse Helms]]\n| office5             = Chair of the [[International Narcotics Control Caucus]]\n| term_start5         = January 3, 2007\n| term_end5           = January 3, 2009\n| predecessor5        = [[Chuck Grassley]]\n| successor5          = [[Dianne Feinstein]]\n| office6             = Chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]\n| term_start6         = January 3, 1987\n| term_end6           = January 3, 1995\n| predecessor6        = [[Strom Thurmond]]\n| successor6          = [[Orrin Hatch]]\n| office7             = Member of the [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County Council]]<br>from the 4th district\n| term_start7         = November 4, 1970\n| term_end7           = November 8, 1972\n| predecessor7        = Henry Folsom\n| successor7          = Francis Swift\n| birth_name          = Joseph Robinette Biden Jr.\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1942|11|20}}\n| birth_place         = [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (1969\u2013present)\n| otherparty          = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (1968\u20131969)\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Neilia Hunter|August 27, 1966|December 18, 1972|end=died}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Jill Biden|Jill Jacobs]]|June 17, 1977}}\n| children            = {{hlist|[[Beau Biden|Beau]]|[[Hunter Biden|Hunter]]|Naomi|Ashley}}\n| education           = [[University of Delaware]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Syracuse University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| awards              = [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] with distinction (2017)\n| signature           = Joe Biden Signature.svg\n| website             = {{url|joebiden.com|Campaign website}}\n| relations           = [[Edward Francis Blewitt]] (great-grandfather)\n}}\n{{JoeBidenseries}}\n'''Joseph Robinette Biden Jr.''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|r|\u0252|b|\u1d7b|\u02c8|n|\u025b|t|_|\u02c8|b|a\u026a|d|\u0259n}};<ref>{{YouTube|time=58s|olQT5g6UJJA|\"Joe Biden takes the oath of Office of Vice President\"}}</ref> born November 20, 1942) is an American politician who served as the 47th [[Vice President of the United States|vice president of the United States]]<!--This is lower case per MOS:JOBTITLES.--> from 2009 to 2017 and represented [[Delaware]] in the [[U.S. Senate]] from 1973 to 2009. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Biden is the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|presumptive Democratic nominee]] for [[President of the United States|president]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 election]]. He unsuccessfully sought the Democratic presidential nomination in [[Joe Biden 1988 presidential campaign|1988]] and in [[Joe Biden 2008 presidential campaign|2008]]. \n\nBiden was raised in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], and [[New Castle County, Delaware]]. He studied at the [[University of Delaware]] before receiving his law degree from [[Syracuse University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Joe-Biden|title=Joe Biden &#124; Biography & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> He became a lawyer in 1969 and was elected to the [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle]] [[County Council]] in 1970. He was [[1972 United States Senate election in Delaware|elected]] to the [[List of United States senators from Delaware|U.S. Senate from Delaware]] in 1972 when he became the sixth-youngest senator in American history. Biden was reelected six times and was the [[Seniority in the United States Senate|fourth-most senior senator]] when he resigned to assume the vice presidency in 2009.\n\nAs a senator, Biden was a longtime member and eventually chairman of the [[Foreign Relations Committee]]. He opposed the [[Gulf War]] in 1991 but advocated for U.S. and [[NATO]] intervention in the [[Bosnian War]] in 1994 and 1995, expanding NATO in the 1990s, and the 1999 bombing of [[Serbia]] during the [[Kosovo War]]. He argued and voted for the [[Iraq War Resolution|resolution authorizing the Iraq War]] in 2002 but opposed the [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|surge of U.S. troops]] in 2007. He has also served as chairman of the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]], dealing with issues related to drug policy, crime prevention, and civil liberties, as well as the contentious [[U.S. Supreme Court]] nominations of [[Robert Bork]] and [[Clarence Thomas]]. Biden led the efforts to pass the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]] and the [[Violence Against Women Act]].\n\nIn [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]], Biden was the [[running mate]] of Democratic presidential nominee [[Barack Obama]]. As vice president, he oversaw [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009#Infrastructure Investment|infrastructure spending]] to counteract the [[Great Recession]] and helped formulate U.S. policy toward [[Iraq]] through the [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)#Full withdrawal (2011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops in 2011]]. His negotiations with congressional [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] helped the Obama administration pass legislation including the [[Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010]], which resolved a taxation deadlock; the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]], which resolved that year's [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2011|debt ceiling crisis]]; and the [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012]], which addressed the impending [[United States fiscal cliff|fiscal cliff]]. Obama and Biden were [[2012 United States presidential election|reelected in 2012]].\n\nIn October 2015, after months of speculation, Biden announced he would not seek the presidency in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]]. In January 2017, Obama awarded Biden the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] with distinction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/12/us/politics/joe-biden-presidential-medal-freedom.html|title=Obama Surprises Joe Biden With Presidential Medal of Freedom|last=Shear|first=Michael D.|date=January 12, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref> After completing his second term as vice president, Biden joined the faculty of the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he was named the [[Benjamin Franklin]] Professor of Presidential Practice.<ref name=\"BidenUPenn\">{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/joe-biden-has-a-new-job-2017-2 |title=Here's what Joe Biden will do after 8 years as vice president |last=Berke |first=Jeremy |date=February 7, 2017 |website=Business Insider |access-date=February 8, 2017 |quote=}}</ref> He announced his [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|2020 candidacy for president]] on April 25, 2019, joining a large [[2020 Democratic Party presidential candidates|field of Democratic candidates]] pursuing the party nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/07/us/politics/biden-2020.html|title=Joe Biden's 2020 Plan Is Almost Complete. Democrats Are Impatient.|first1=Jonathan|last1=Martin|first2=Alexander|last2=Burns|date=March 7, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Despite poor showings in the first three state contests, Biden won the [[2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|South Carolina primary]] decisively, and several [[Centre-left politics|center-left]] candidates dropped out of the race and endorsed him before [[Super Tuesday]]. Biden went on to win [[Results of the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|18 of the next 26 contests]]. With the suspension of the campaign of [[Bernie Sanders]] on April 8, 2020, Biden became the Democratic Party's [[presumptive nominee]] for the presidential election.<ref name=\"NYT4-8-2020\">{{Cite news |last=Ember |first=Sydney |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/politics/bernie-sanders-drops-out.html |title=Bernie Sanders Drops Out of 2020 Democratic Race for President |date=April 8, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Early life (1942\u20131965) ==\n\nBiden was born on November 20, 1942, at St. Mary's Hospital in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"witcover\">{{cite book|last=Witcover|first=Jules|authorlink=Jules Witcover|title=Joe Biden: A Life of Trial and Redemption|year=2010|publisher=William Morrow|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-06-179198-7|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061791987}}</ref>{{rp|5}} to Catherine Eugenia \"Jean\" Biden (''n\u00e9e'' Finnegan) and Joseph Robinette Biden Sr.<ref name=\"ap010810\">{{cite news |url=https://www.witn.com/home/headlines/81062772.html |title=Vice President Biden's mother, Jean, dies at 92 |last=Chase |first=Randall |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[WITN-TV]] |date=January 9, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-2002-09-03-0209030023-story.html |title=Joseph Biden Sr., 86, father of the senator |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=September 3, 2002 |accessdate=April 15, 2020 }}</ref> The first of four siblings in a [[Catholic]] family, he had a sister and two brothers.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|9}} Jean was of [[Irish people|Irish]] descent, with roots variously attributed to [[County Louth]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-bidens-irish-roots_b_1641678 |title=Joe Biden's Irish Roots |last=Smolenyak |first=Megan |authorlink=Megan Smolenyak|work=Huffington Post|date=July 2, 2012|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref> and [[County Londonderry]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sunday-life/number-two-biden-has-a-history-over-irish-debate-28454443.html |title=Number two Biden has a history over Irish debate |work=[[The Belfast Telegraph]] |date=November 9, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|8}} Joseph Sr.'s parents, Mary Elizabeth (''n\u00e9e'' Robinette) and Joseph H. Biden, an oil businessman from [[Baltimore, Maryland]], were of [[English people|English]], [[French people|French]], and Irish descent.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://irishamerica.com/2013/03/joey-from-scranton-vice-president-bidens-irish-roots/ |title=Joey From Scranton\u2014Vice President Biden's Irish Roots |magazine=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] |date=April\u2013May 2013 |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |last=Smolenyak|first=Megan|authorlink=Megan Smolenyak}}</ref><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|8}} Biden's paternal third great-grandfather, William Biden, was born in [[Sussex]], England, and immigrated to the United States. His maternal great-grandfather, [[Edward Francis Blewitt]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.lafayette.edu/2012/05/03/vice-president-joe-biden-discusses-american-innovation/ |title=Vice President Joe Biden Discusses American Innovation |last=Gehman |first=Geoff |publisher=[[Lafayette College]] |date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> the child of Irish emigrants from Rappagh, [[Ballina, County Mayo]], was a member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt |title=Remembering his roots |last=Krawczeniuk |first=Borys |newspaper=[[The Times-Tribune (Scranton)|The Times-Tribune]] |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=January 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406014842/http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt |archivedate=April 6, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.con-telegraph.ie/news/roundup/articles/2016/05/11/4119572-us-vice-president-to-visit-mayo-in-june/|title=US vice president to visit Mayo in June|date=May 11, 2016|newspaper=The Connaught Telegraph|access-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBiden's father was wealthy but had suffered several financial setbacks by the time his son was born. For several years, the family had to live with Biden's maternal grandparents, the Finnegans.<ref name=\"nyt-father\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/24/us/politics/24biden.html |title=Father's Tough Life an Inspiration for Biden |last=Broder |first=John M. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=October 24, 2008}}</ref> When the Scranton area fell into economic decline during the 1950s, Biden's father could not find sustained work.<ref name=\"ap-scranton\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/wires/2008Aug27/0,4670,CVNBidenapossScrantonRoots,00.html |title=Biden's Scranton childhood left lasting impression |last=Rubinkam |first=Michael |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]] |date=August 27, 2008 |accessdate=September 7, 2008}}</ref> In 1953, the Bidens moved into an apartment in [[Claymont, Delaware]], where they lived for several years before again moving to a house in [[Wilmington, Delaware]].<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/> Joe Biden Sr. later became a successful [[used car salesman]], maintaining the family's middle-class lifestyle.<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/><ref name=\"ap-scranton\"/><ref name=\"aap08-bio\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 364.</ref>\n[[File:Joe Biden at Archmere Academy.jpg|thumb|300px|Biden (second from left) studied at [[Archmere Academy]] in the 1950s.|alt=]]\n\nBiden attended the [[Archmere Academy]] in Claymont,<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|27, 32}} where he was a standout [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] and [[wide receiver]] on the [[high school football]] team; he helped lead a perennially losing team to an undefeated season in his senior year.<ref name=nyt-father/><ref name=tnj092808>{{cite news |title=Biden was the stuttering kid who wanted the ball |last=Frank |first=Martin |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |date=September 28, 2008 |page=D.1 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1742718581.html?FMT=ABS |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601081204/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1742718581.html?FMT=ABS |archivedate=June 1, 2013 }}</ref> He played on the baseball team as well.<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/> Academically, he was a poor student but was considered a natural leader among the students and elected class president during his junior and senior years.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|40\u201341}}<ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|99}} He graduated in 1961.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|40\u201341}}\n\nHe earned his bachelor's degree in 1965 from the [[University of Delaware]], with a [[double major]] in history and political science,<ref name=\"ap-timeline\" /> graduating with a [[class rank]] of 506 out of 688.<ref name=\"See How They Run\">{{cite book |last=Taylor |first=Paul |title=See How They Run: Electing the President in an Age of Mediaocracy |publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf]] |year=1990 |isbn=0-394-57059-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JMxWRDTR_sMC }}</ref>{{rp|98}} He impressed his classmates with his [[Cramming (education)|cramming]] abilities,<ref name=\"cby-43\">''Current Biography Yearbook 1987'', p. 43.</ref> and played halfback for the [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football|Blue Hens freshman football team]].<ref name=\"tnj092808\" /> In 1964, while on [[spring break]] in [[the Bahamas]],<ref name=\"coxns-jill\" /> he met and began dating Neilia Hunter, who was from an affluent background in [[Skaneateles (village), New York|Skaneateles, New York]], and attended [[Syracuse University]].<ref name=\"nyt-father\" /><ref name=\"nyt-ease\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/14/us/politics/14biden.html |title=Biden Campaigning With Ease After Hardships |last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 14, 2007 |accessdate=September 13, 2008 |authorlink=Elisabeth Bumiller }}</ref> He told her he aimed to become a senator by the age of 30 and then president.<ref name=\"dmn-87\">{{cite news|last=Leubsdorf|first=Carl P.|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_text_direct-0=0ED3CF5858543A33&p_field_direct-0=document_id|title=Biden Keeps Sights Set On White House|date=September 6, 1987|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]}} Reprinted in {{cite news|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/news/washington/cleubsdorf/stories/082308dnpolbiden87profile.4d6e19b.html|title=Lifelong ambition led Joe Biden to Senate, White House aspirations|date=August 23, 2008|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919060037/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/news/washington/cleubsdorf/stories/082308dnpolbiden87profile.4d6e19b.html|archivedate=September 19, 2008}}</ref> He dropped a junior-year plan to play for the varsity football team as a [[defensive back]], enabling him to spend more time visiting her.<ref name=\"tnj092808\" /><ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', pp. 27, 32\u201333.</ref>\n\nHe then entered [[Syracuse University College of Law]], later saying he found law school \"the biggest bore in the world\" and that he pulled many [[sleep deprivation#School|all-nighters]] to get by.<ref name=\"nyt092287\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/22/us/biden-admits-errors-and-criticizes-latest-report.html |title= Biden Admits Errors and Criticizes Latest Report |last=Dionne |first=E. J., Jr. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 22, 1987 |authorlink=E. J. Dionne}}</ref><ref name=\"cby-43\" /><ref name=\"nyt091887\" /> During his first year there, Biden was accused of having plagiarized five of 15 pages of a law review article. He said it was inadvertent, because he did not know the proper rules of citation. He was given an F and required to retake a course. This incident was cited in 1987, when plagiarism accusations arose during his first run for president.<ref name=\"nyt091887\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/18/us/biden-admits-plagiarism-in-school-but-says-it-was-not-malevolent.html |title=Biden Admits Plagiarism in School But Says It Was Not 'Malevolent' |last=Dionne |first==E. J., Jr. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 18, 1987 |authorlink= E. J. Dionne}}</ref><ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite news |last=Greenberg |first=David |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2008/08/why-biden-s-plagiarims-shouldn-t-be-forgotten.html |title=The Write Stuff? Why Biden's plagiarism shouldn't be forgotten |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=August 25, 2008 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref> Biden received his [[Juris Doctor]] in 1968,<ref name=\"cong-bio\" /> graduating 76th of 85 in his class.<ref name=\"nyt092287\" /> He was admitted to the [[Delaware State Bar Association|Delaware bar]] in 1969.<ref name=\"cong-bio\">{{cite dictionary |dictionary=[[Biographical Directory of the United States Congress]]| url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000444 |title=Biden, Joseph Robinette, Jr.|accessdate=August 19, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBiden received [[Conscription in the United States|student draft deferments]] during this period.<ref name=\"ap-draft\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsday.com/news/nation/biden-got-5-draft-deferments-during-nam-as-did-cheney-1.884250 |title=Biden got 5 draft deferments during Nam, as did Cheney |last=Chase |first=Randall |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=Newsday |date=September 1, 2008 }}</ref> After completing his studies, the [[Selective Service System]] classified him as unavailable for service due to a history of [[asthma]].<ref name=\"ap-draft\"/><ref name=\"wapo-romano87\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/06/09/joe-biden-the-politics-of-belief/c19fd9f1-3c4a-44c2-97e2-fd30cbdb22bc/ |title=Joe Biden & the Politics of Belief |last=Romano |first=Lois |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=June 9, 1987}}</ref>\n\nHe has had a problem with [[stuttering]] throughout his life, especially in his childhood and his early twenties,<ref>{{cite web |last=Biden |first=Joseph R., Jr. |url=http://www.westutter.org/pdfs/Joe_Biden-PublicGreeting_NationalStutteringAssoc_7.1.09.pdf |title=Letter to National Stuttering Association chairman |publisher=National Stuttering Association |date=July 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728173845/http://www.westutter.org/pdfs/Joe_Biden-PublicGreeting_NationalStutteringAssoc_7.1.09.pdf |archivedate=July 28, 2011 }}</ref> and says he has helped reduce the problem by spending many hours reciting poetry in front of a mirror.<ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|99}} But he continues to have problems with stuttering, and it has been suggested that this has affected his performance in Democratic debates during his 2020 campaign for the presidency.<ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Hendrickson |work=[[The Atlantic]] |title=What Joe Biden Can't Bring Himself to Say |date=January\u2013February 2020 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2020/01/joe-biden-stutter-profile/602401/ |access-date=November 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nNegative impressions of drinking alcohol in the Biden and Finnegan families and in the neighborhood led Biden to be a [[Teetotalism|non-drinker]].<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/09/16/riding-the-rails-with-amtrak-joe/ |title=Riding the Rails With Amtrak Joe |last=Leibovich |first=Mark |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Early political career and family life (1966\u20131972) ==\n\nOn August 27, 1966, while still a law student, Biden married Neilia Hunter.<ref name=\"ap-timeline\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2008/08/22/politics/p222636D16.DTL |title=A timeline of U.S. Sen. Joe Biden's life and career |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=September 6, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925021142/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fn%2Fa%2F2008%2F08%2F22%2Fpolitics%2Fp222636D16.DTL |archivedate=September 25, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They overcame her parents' initial reluctance for her to wed a Roman Catholic, and the ceremony was held in a Catholic church in [[Skaneateles, New York (village)|Skaneateles, New York]].<ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', pp. 32, 36\u201337.</ref> They had three children, [[Beau Biden|Joseph R. \"Beau\" Biden III]] in 1969, [[Hunter Biden|Robert Hunter]] in 1970, and Naomi Christina in 1971.<ref name=\"ap-timeline\"/>\n\nIn 1968, Biden clerked for six months at a [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]] law firm headed by prominent local [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] William Prickett and, as he later said, \"thought of myself as a Republican\".<ref name=\"dmn-87\"/><ref name=\"time-barrett\">{{cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964716,00.html |title=Campaign Portrait, Joe Biden: Orator for the Next Generation |last=Barrett |first=Laurence I. |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=June 22, 1987 }}</ref> He disliked incumbent Democratic Delaware Governor [[Charles L. Terry]]'s conservative racial politics and supported a more liberal Republican, [[Russell W. Peterson]], who defeated Terry in 1968.<ref name=\"dmn-87\"/> The local Republicans tried to recruit him, but he resisted due to his distaste for Republican presidential candidate [[Richard Nixon]], and registered as an [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] instead.<ref name=\"dmn-87\"/>\n\nIn 1969, Biden resumed practicing law in Wilmington, first as a [[public defender]] and then at a firm headed by Sid Balick, a locally active Democrat.<ref name=\"cby-43\"/><ref name=\"dmn-87\"/> Balick named him to the Democratic Forum, a group trying to reform and revitalize the state party,<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|86}} and Biden registered as a Democrat.<ref name=\"dmn-87\"/> He also started his own firm, Biden and Walsh.<ref name=\"cby-43\"/> [[Corporate law]], however, did not appeal to him and [[criminal law]] did not pay well.<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/> He supplemented his income by managing properties.<ref name=\"watn020109\">{{cite news|author=Doyle, Nancy Palmer|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2009/02/01/joe-biden-everyone-calls-me-joe/ |accessdate=February 4, 2009|title=Joe Biden: 'Everyone Calls Me Joe'|magazine=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|date=February 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLater in 1969, Biden ran to represent the 4th district on the [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle]] [[County council#United States|County Council]] with a liberal platform that included support for public housing in the suburban area.<ref name=\"cby-43\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Harriman|first=Jane|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=8326887|title=Joe Biden: Hope for Democratic Party in '72?|date=December 31, 1969|access-date=May 1, 2019|publisher=The News Journal|page=3|language=en|website=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He won by 2,000 votes in the usually Republican district and a bad year for Democrats in the state.<ref name=\"cby-43\"/><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|59}} Even before taking his seat, he was already talking about running for the U.S. Senate in a couple of years.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|59}} He served on the County Council from 1970 to 1972<ref name=\"cong-bio\"/> while continuing his private law practice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/2008-presidential-candidates/joe-biden |title=2008 Presidential Candidates: Joe Biden |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=October 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022055510/http://projects.washingtonpost.com/2008-presidential-candidates/joe-biden/ |archivedate=October 22, 2008 }}</ref> Among issues he addressed on the council was his opposition to large highway projects that might disrupt Wilmington neighborhoods, including those related to [[Interstate 95]].<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|62}}\n\n=== 1972 U.S. Senate campaign ===\n\n[[File:Delaware Senate Election Results by County, 1972.svg|thumb|right|115px|Results of the 1972 U.S. Senate election in [[Delaware]]]]\n\nBiden's candidacy in the [[1972 United States Senate election in Delaware|1972 U.S. Senate election in Delaware]] presented an unusual circumstance\u2014longtime Delaware political figure and Republican incumbent senator [[J. Caleb Boggs]] was considering retirement, which would likely have left [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Pierre S. du Pont, IV|Pete du Pont]] and Wilmington Mayor [[Harry G. Haskell Jr.]] in a divisive [[primary election|primary]] fight. To avoid that, President Nixon helped convince Boggs to run again with full party support. No other Democrat wanted to run against Boggs.<ref name=\"cby-43\"/> Biden's campaign had almost no money and was given no chance of winning.<ref name=\"nyt-father\"/> His sister Valerie Biden Owens managed his campaign (as she would his future campaigns) and other family members staffed it. The campaign relied upon handed-out newsprint position papers and meeting voters face-to-face;<ref name=\"npr-72\">{{cite news |author=Naylor, Brian |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14999603 |title=Biden's Road to Senate Took Tragic Turn |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |date=October 8, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref> the state's smallness and lack of a major media market made that approach feasible.<ref name=\"watn020109\"/> He did receive some help from the [[AFL\u2013CIO]] and Democratic pollster [[Patrick Caddell]].<ref name=\"cby-43\"/> His campaign focused on withdrawal from Vietnam; the environment; civil rights; mass transit; more equitable taxation; health care; the public's dissatisfaction with politics as usual,; and \"change\".<ref name=\"cby-43\"/><ref name=\"npr-72\"/> During the summer, he trailed by almost 30&nbsp;percentage points,<ref name=\"cby-43\"/> but his energy level, his attractive young family, and his ability to connect with voters' emotions gave him an advantage over the ready-to-retire Boggs.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\"/><!--Teamsters Union leader [[Frank Sheeran]] wrote in 2004 that in the week before the election, he organized a strike to prevent delivery of a newspaper which had Republican attack ads against Biden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2012/08/17/henry-miller-bidens-unhinged-and-worse-history/|title=Henry Miller: Biden's unhinged, and worse, history|author=Henry I. Miller|date=August 17, 2012|website=[[Orange County Register]]|quote=In the fascinating biography of Teamsters and Mafia hit-man Frank Sheeran, \"I Heard You Paint Houses,\" the lifelong thug describes a favor he performed while he was president of Teamsters Local 326 in Wilmington, Delaware. In 1972 Sheeran received a visit from \"a very prominent lawyer\" he knew who was \"very big in the Democratic Party\" in Delaware. The November general election was approaching, and the race for the U.S. Senate seat held by a Republican was expected to be close. The lawyer wanted help in preventing the distribution of a paid Republican political ad (an insert in Delaware-wide newspapers) that would run for a week and expose the Democratic challenger's misrepresentations. Sheeran promised the operative he \"would hire some people and put them on the picket line\". He added, \"People nobody would mess with\". The picket line went up, the papers were not delivered all week, and, as Sheeran said, \"The day after the election the informational picket line came down, and the newspaper went back to normal and Delaware had a new United States Senator.\" His name was Joe Biden. Thereafter, said admitted extortionist, thief and murderer Sheeran, of Biden, \"You could reach out for him, and he would listen.\"}}</ref>--> Biden won the November{{nbsp}}7 election by 3,162 votes.<ref name=\"npr-72\"/>\n\n=== Family deaths ===\n\nOn December 18, 1972, a few weeks after the election, Biden's wife and one-year-old daughter Naomi were killed in an automobile accident while Christmas shopping in [[Hockessin, Delaware]].<ref name=\"ap-timeline\"/> Neilia Biden's station wagon was hit by a [[Semi-trailer truck|tractor-trailer truck]] as she pulled out from an intersection. Biden's sons Beau and Hunter survived the accident and were taken to the hospital in fair condition, Beau with a broken leg and other wounds, and Hunter with a minor skull fracture and other head injuries.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|93, 98}} Doctors soon said both would make full recoveries.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|96}} Biden considered resigning to care for them,<ref name=\"aap08-bio\"/> but [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mike Mansfield]] persuaded him not to.<ref name=\"lat-joe\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-aug-24-na-biden24-story.html | title=In his home state, Biden is a regular Joe |last=Levey |first=Noam M. |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=September 7, 2008}}</ref> In later years, Biden often said the truck driver had drunk alcohol before the collision, but the driver's family has denied that claim and the police never substantiated it.<ref name=\"dj-no-dui2\">{{cite news |title=No DUI in crash that killed Biden's 1st wife, but he's implied otherwise |last=Kipp |first=Rachel |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |date=September 4, 2008 |page=A.1 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1743377101.html?FMT=ABS |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601102455/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1743377101.html?FMT=ABS |archivedate=June 1, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://insideedition.com/storyprint.aspx?SpecialReportID=2048 |title=A Senator's Past: The Biden Car Crash|date=August 27, 2008|accessdate=May 28, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601072408/http://insideedition.com/storyprint.aspx?SpecialReportID=2048|archivedate=June 1, 2009|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Inside Edition]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Orr |first=Bob |title=Driver In Biden Crash Wanted Name Cleared |date=March 24, 2009 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/driver-in-biden-crash-wanted-name-cleared/ |accessdate=March 13, 2017 |agency=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hamilton |first=Carl |title=Daughter of man in '72 Biden crash seeks apology from widowed Senator |url=https://www.newarkpostonline.com/news/local/article_6c9a477e-63be-561b-b771-1330b4cda02d.html |date=October 30, 2008 |accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=Newark Post}}</ref>\n\n== United States Senate (1973\u20132009) ==\n=== Recovery and remarriage ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden first official photo.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Biden in 1973]]\nBiden was sworn into office on January 5, 1973, by [[Secretary of the United States Senate|secretary of the Senate]] [[Francis R. Valeo]] in a small chapel at the [[Delaware Division of the Wilmington Medical Center]].<ref name=\"ap-sworn\"/><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|93, 98}} Beau was wheeled in with his leg still in traction; Hunter, who had already been released, was also there, as were other members of the extended family.<ref name=\"ap-sworn\"/><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|93, 98}} Witnesses and television cameras were also present and the event received national attention.<ref name=\"ap-sworn\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yadYAAAAIBAJ&pg=5556,1874966 |title=Oath Solemn |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Spokane Daily Chronicle]] |date=January 6, 1973 |page=11}}</ref><ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|93, 98}}\n\nAt age 30 (the minimum age required to hold the office), Biden became the [[List of youngest members of the United States Congress#List of youngest U.S. senators|sixth-youngest senator in U.S. history]], and one of only 18 who took office before turning 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Youngest_Senator.htm |title=Youngest Senator |publisher=[[United States Senate]] |accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>Byrd, Robert and Wolff, Wendy. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=PeHByMYxVm8C&pg=PA285 Senate, 1789\u20131989: Historical Statistics, 1789\u20131992, Volume 4]'', p. 285 (Government Printing Office 1993).</ref> But the accident that killed his wife and daughter left him filled with both anger and religious doubt: \"I liked to [walk around seedy neighborhoods] at night when I thought there was a better chance of finding a fight{{nbsp}}... I had not known I was capable of such rage{{nbsp}}... I felt God had played a horrible trick on me.\"<ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', p. 81.</ref> To be at home every day for his young sons,<ref name=\"family values\">{{cite news |author=Pride, Mike |url=http://concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071201/OPINION/712010307 |title=Biden a smart guy who has lived his family values |newspaper=[[Concord Monitor]] |date=December 1, 2007 |accessdate=October 4, 2008 |archivedate=December 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203001952/http://concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20071201%2FOPINION%2F712010307 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Biden began commuting every day by [[Amtrak]] train 90 minutes each way from his home in the Wilmington suburbs to Washington, D.C., which he continued to do throughout his Senate career.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\"/> In the accident's aftermath, he had trouble focusing on work and appeared to just go through the motions of being a senator. In his memoirs, Biden notes that staffers were taking bets on how long he would last.<ref name=\"nyt-ease\"/><ref name=\"npr-int\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12389154 |title=On Becoming Joe Biden |work=[[Morning Edition]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=August 1, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2008}}</ref> A single father for five years, he left standing orders that he be interrupted in the Senate at any time if his sons called.<ref name=\"lat-joe\"/> In remembrance of his wife and daughter, Biden does not work on December 18, the anniversary of the accident.<ref name=\"ap-aug22\"/>\n\n[[File:Joe and Jilly Biden early photo.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Biden met his second wife, [[Jill Biden|Jill]], in 1975. They married in 1977.]]\nIn 1975, Biden met [[Jill Biden|Jill Tracy Jacobs]], who had grown up in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]], and would become a teacher in Delaware.<ref name=\"nyt082508\"/> They met on a blind date arranged by Biden's brother, although Biden had already noticed a photograph of her in an advertisement for a park in Wilmington.<ref name=\"nyt082508\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html |title=Jill Biden Heads Toward Life in the Spotlight |last=Seelye |first=Katharine Q. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref> Biden credits her with renewing his interest in both politics and life.<ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', p. 113.</ref> On June 17, 1977, Biden and Jacobs were married by a Catholic priest at the Chapel at the United Nations in New York.<ref name=\"coxns-jill\">{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2008-10-24-a3bidenwife24-story.html |title=Bidens met, forged life together after tragedy |last=Dart |first=Bob |agency=[[Cox News Service]] |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=October 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', p. 117.</ref> Jill Biden has a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Delaware]]; two master's degrees, one from [[West Chester University]] and the other from [[Villanova University]]; and a doctorate in education from the University of Delaware.<ref name=\"nyt082508\"/> They have one daughter together, Ashley Blazer (born 1981),<ref name=\"ap-timeline\"/> who became a social worker and staffer at the [[Delaware Department of Services for Children, Youth, and Their Families]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/03/fashion/weddings/ashley-biden-howard-krein-wedding.html |title=Ashley Biden and Howard Krein |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2012 |page=ST15}}</ref> Biden and his wife are Roman Catholics and regularly attend Mass at [[St. Joseph's on the Brandywine]] in [[Greenville, Delaware]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Parishioners not surprised to see Biden at usual Mass |author=Gibson, Ginger |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |date=August 25, 2008 |page=A.12 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1742751081.html?FMT=ABS |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601093036/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/delawareonline/access/1742751081.html?FMT=ABS |archivedate=June 1, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBiden's elder son [[Beau Biden|Beau]] became [[Delaware Attorney General]] and an Army [[Judge Advocate]] who served in Iraq;<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=August 23, 2008|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121919956426355701 |title=Biden's Foreign Policy Background Carries Growing Cachet|author=Cooper, Christopher|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 20, 2008|page=A4}}</ref> he died at age 46 after a two-year battle with brain cancer on May 30, 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/vice-president-joe-bidens-son-beau-dies-n367171 |first=Phil |last=Helsel |title=Beau Biden, Son of Vice President Joe Biden, Dies After Battle With Brain Cancer |publisher=NBC News |date=May 31, 2015 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Kane |date=May 31, 2015 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |title=Family losses frame Vice President Biden's career |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/beau-biden-vice-presidents-son-dies-of-brain-cancer-at-46/2015/05/31/4198da78-07c6-11e5-9e39-0db921c47b93_story.html |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> His younger son, [[Hunter Biden|Hunter]], became a Washington attorney and lobbyist.<ref name=\"nydn122808\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2008/12/27/2008-12-27_from_a_blind_date_to_second_lady_jill_bi.html |title=From a blind date to second lady, Jill Biden's coming into her own |last=Evans |first=Heidi |newspaper=Daily News |location=New York |date=December 28, 2008 |accessdate=January 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Early Senate activities ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden and Jimmy Carter.jpg|thumb|right|Biden with President [[Jimmy Carter]] in the [[Oval Office]]]]\n[[File:Biden-Church-Sadat.jpg|thumb|right|Senators Joe Biden (left) and [[Frank Church]] (middle) with [[president of Egypt]] [[Anwar Sadat|Anwar el-Sadat]] after signing the [[Egypt\u2013Israel Peace Treaty]], 1979]]\n[[File:Reagan Contact Sheet C20355 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Biden greets [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1984]]\n\nDuring his first years in the Senate, Biden focused on consumer protection and environmental issues and called for greater government accountability.<ref name=\"time-200-fut\"/> In mid-1974, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named him one of the ''200 Faces for the Future'' in a profile that mentioned what had happened to his family, calling him \"self-confident\" and \"compulsively ambitious\".<ref name=\"time-200-fut\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,879402-6,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813045404/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,879402-6,00.html |archivedate=August 13, 2013 |title=200 Faces for the Future |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=July 15, 1974 |accessdate=August 23, 2008 }}</ref> In a June 1, 1974, interview with the ''[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]'', Biden described himself as liberal on civil rights and liberties, senior citizens' concerns and healthcare, but conservative on other issues, including abortion and the draft.<ref name=\"The Washingtonian-June-1974\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/1974/06/01/joe-biden-kitty-kelley-1974-profile-death-and-the-all-american-boy/|title=Death and the All-American Boy|last=Kelley|first=Kitty|date=June 1, 1974|work=The Washingtonian|access-date=March 8, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBiden became [[ranking member|ranking minority member]] of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|U.S. Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] in 1981. In 1984, he was a Democratic floor manager for the successful passage of the [[Comprehensive Crime Control Act]]. Over time, the law's tough-on-crime provisions became controversial on the left and among [[Criminal justice reform in the United States|criminal justice reform]] proponents, and in 2019 Biden called his role in passing the legislation a \"big mistake\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Herndon|first=Astead W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/21/us/politics/biden-crime-bill-regrets.html|title=Biden Expresses Regret for Support of Crime Legislation in the 1990s|date=January 21, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 21, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/06/us/politics/joe-biden-2020-president.html \"Biden in 2020? Allies Say He Sees Himself as Democrats' Best Hope\"], By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns. ''New York Times''. January 6, 2019</ref> His supporters praised him for modifying some of the law's worst provisions, and it was his most important legislative accomplishment at that time.<ref name=\"cby-44\" /> He first considered running for president that year, after gaining notice for speeches he gave to party audiences that simultaneously scolded and encouraged Democrats.<ref name=\"Whose Broad Stripes\">{{cite book|last=Germond|first=Jack|url=https://archive.org/details/whosebroadstripe00germ|title=Whose Broad Stripes and Bright Stars? The Trivial Pursuit of the Presidency 1988|last2=Witcover|first2=Jules|publisher=[[Warner Books]]|year=1989|isbn=0-446-51424-1|authorlink=Jack Germond|authorlink2=Jules Witcover}}</ref>{{rp|216}}\n\nIn 1993, Biden voted in favor of 10 U.S.C. \u00a7654, a section of a broader federally mandated policy that deemed homosexuality incompatible with military life thereby banning gay Americans from serving in the United States armed forces in any capacity without exception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/app/details/USCODE-2010-title10/USCODE-2010-title10-subtitleA-partII-chap37-sec654|title=govinfo|website=govinfo.gov|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Epstein|first=Reid J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/lgbt-forum-2020.html|title=Joe Biden Has Tense Exchange Over L.G.B.T.Q. Record|date=2019-09-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|last2=Lerer|first2=Lisa|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sanders-calls-biden-my-friend-then-he-goes-on-the-attack/2020/03/08/20a23f86-60d0-11ea-9055-5fa12981bbbf_story.html|title=Sanders attacks Biden's record on gay rights and women's issues|last=A. Del|first=Jose|last2=|first2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The law was subsequently modified by President Clinton through the issuance of DOD Directive 1304.26 (subsequently nicknamed \"[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]\" or DADT) which accommodated \"closeted\" service to the extent that a servicemember's homosexual sexual orientation was neither discovered nor disclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biotech.law.lsu.edu/blaw/dodd/corres/pdf/d130426wch1_122193/d130426p.pdf|title=DOD Directive 1304.26|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The ban was held unconstitutional in ''[[Log Cabin Republicans v. United States]]'' for violation of [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First]] and [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] rights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/10/us/10gays.html|title=Judge Rules That Military Policy Violates Rights of Gays|last=Schwartz|first=John|date=2010-09-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Biden voted in favor of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (1 U.S.C. \u00a77), which prohibited the federal government from recognizing any same-sex marriage, barring individuals in such marriages from equal protection under federal law, and allowing states to do the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=104&session=2&vote=00280|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 104th Congress\u20142nd Session|website=senate.gov|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> In 2013, Section{{nbsp}}3 of DOMA was ruled unconstitutional and partially struck down in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]''. The Obama Administration did not defend the law and congratulated Windsor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court/2013/06/26/f0039814-d9ab-11e2-a016-92547bf094cc_story.html|title=Supreme Court strikes down key part of Defense of Marriage Act|last=Barnes|first=Robert|date=June 26, 2013|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}{{paywall}}</ref> In 2015, DOMA was ruled unconstitutional in totality in [[Obergefell v. Hodges|''Obergefell v. Hodges.'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/06/26/politics/supreme-court-same-sex-marriage-ruling/index.html|title=Supreme Court rules states must allow same-sex marriage |author1=Ariane de Vogue |author2=Jeremy Diamond|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nRegarding foreign policy, during his first decade in the Senate, Biden focused on [[arms control]] issues.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/><ref name=\"cby-45\">''Current Biography Yearbook 1987'', p. 45.</ref> In response to [[U.S. Congress|Congress]]'s refusal to ratify the [[SALT II]] Treaty signed in 1979 by Soviet leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]] and President [[Jimmy Carter]], Biden took the initiative to meet with Soviet foreign minister [[Andrei Gromyko]], educate him about American concerns and interests, and secure several changes to address the Foreign Relations Committee's objections.<ref>{{cite book|last=Salacuse|first=Jeswald W.|url=https://archive.org/details/leadingleaders00jesw|title=Leading Leaders: How to Manage Smart, Talented, Rich and Powerful People|publisher=American Management Association|year=2005|isbn=0-8144-0855-9}} p. 144.</ref> When the [[Reagan administration]] wanted to interpret the 1972 [[SALT I]] Treaty loosely to allow the [[Strategic Defense Initiative]] to proceed, Biden argued for strict adherence to the treaty's terms.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/> He clashed again with the Reagan administration in 1986 over [[economic sanctions against South Africa]],<ref name=\"cby-45\" /> receiving considerable attention when he excoriated Secretary of State [[George P. Shultz]] at a Senate hearing because of the administration's support of that country, which continued to practice [[apartheid]].<ref name=\"dmn-87\" />\n\n=== Opposition to desegregation busing ===\n\nIn the mid-1970s, Biden was one of the Senate's leading opponents of [[desegregation busing]]. His white Delaware constituents strongly opposed it, and such opposition nationwide later led his party to mostly abandon school desegregation policies.<ref name=\"Gadsen\">{{cite news|last1=Gadsden|first1=Brett|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/05/05/joe-biden-busing-problem-226791|title=Here's How Deep Biden's Busing Problem Runs|date=May 5, 2019|work=POLITICO Magazine|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his first Senate campaign, Biden expressed support for the Supreme Court's 1971 ''[[Swann v. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Board of Education|Swann]]'' decision, which supported busing programs to integrate school districts to remedy ''[[de jure]]'' [[Racial segregation|segregation]], but opposed it to remedy ''[[de facto]]'' segregation, as in Delaware. He said Republicans were using busing as a scare tactic to court Southern white votes, and along with Boggs voiced opposition to a [[House of Representatives]] constitutional amendment banning busing.{{sfn|Gadsen|2012|page=214}} In 1974, Biden voted to table an amendment to an omnibus education bill promoted by [[Edward Gurney]] (R-FL) that contained anti-busing measures and anti-school desegregation clauses. In May, Senator [[Robert P. Griffin|Robert Griffin]] (R-MI) attempted to revive an amended version of the amendment. Minority Leader [[Hugh Scott]] (R-PA) and Majority Leader [[Mike Mansfield]] (D-MT) offered to leave the text of Griffin's amendment intact but add the qualifier that such legislation was not intended to weaken the judiciary's power to enforce the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|5th]] and [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|14th Amendments]] of the U.S. Constitution. Biden voted for this compromise, angering his local voters.<ref name=\"Sokol\">{{cite news |last1=Sokol |first1=Jason |title=How a Young Joe Biden Turned Liberals Against Integration |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/08/04/joe-biden-integration-school-busing-120968 |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |work=[[POLITICO Magazine]] |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, some Delaware residents met at the Krebs School in Newport to protest integration. Biden spoke to the auditorium and said his position on school busing was evolving, emphasizing that busing in Delaware was in his opinion beyond court restrictions. The crowd was unconvinced, and heckled him until he yielded the microphone.{{sfn|Gadsen|2012|pages=2\u20133}} This, along with the prospect of a busing plan in Wilmington, led Biden to align himself with civil rights opponent Senator [[Jesse Helms]] (R-NC) in opposing busing. Biden and anti-busing senators wanted to limit the scope of [[Civil Rights Act of 1964#Title VI\u2014nondiscrimination in federally assisted programs|Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]] with respect to the federal government's power to enforce school integration policies.<ref name=\"Gadsen\" /> After 1975, Biden took a harsher line on further legislative action to limit busing.<ref name=\"cby-44\" /> That year, Helms proposed an anti-integration amendment to an education bill that would stop the [[Department of Health, Education, and Welfare]] (HEW) from collecting data about students' or teachers' races and thereby prevent it from defunding districts that refused to integrate. Biden supported this amendment, saying: \"I am sure it comes as a surprise to some of my colleagues{{nbsp}}... that a senator with a voting record such as mine stands up and supports\" it.{{sfn|Gadsen|2012|pages=220\u2013221}} He said busing was a \"bankrupt idea [that violated] the cardinal rule of common sense\", and that his opposition would make it easier for other liberals to follow suit.<ref name=\"cby-44\" /> But he had also supported integrationist Senator [[Edward Brooke]]'s (R-MA) initiatives on housing, job opportunities and voting rights.<ref name=\"Sokol\" /> Civil rights lawyer and NAACP Legal Defense Fund director [[Jack Greenberg]] criticized Biden's support for the bill, saying it \"heave[d] a brick through the window of school integration\", with Biden's hand on the brick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ross |first1=Janell |title=Joe Biden didn't just compromise with segregationists. He fought for their cause in schools, experts say. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/joe-biden-didn-t-just-compromise-segregationists-he-fought-their-n1021626 |accessdate=August 28, 2019 |work=NBC News |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBiden supported a measure Senator [[Robert Byrd]] (D-WV) sponsored that forbade the use of federal funds to transport students beyond their closest school. This was adopted as part of the Labor-HEW Appropriations Act of 1976. In 1977, Biden co-sponsored an amendment with [[Thomas Eagleton]] (D-MO) to close loopholes in Byrd's amendment. A 1977 status report on school desegregation by the federal [[Civil Rights Commission]] in Washington, D.C., said, \"the enactment of Eagleton-Biden would be an actual violation, on the part of the Federal Government, of the fifth amendment and Title VI\" of the Civil Rights Act.<ref name=\"Bartning\">Bartning, Delores de la Torre; and others (February 1979). [https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED167688.pdf \"Desegregation of the Nation's Public Schools: A Status Report\"]. (PDF) Commission on Civil Rights, Washington, D.C. Accessed August 28, 2019.</ref> President Carter signed the amendment into law in 1978.<ref name=\"Raffel1998\">{{cite book|author=Jeffrey A. Raffel|title=Historical Dictionary of School Segregation and Desegregation: The American Experience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gA1JljCpxzEC&pg=PA90|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-29502-7|page=90}}</ref> Biden repeatedly asked for, and received, the support of Senator [[James Eastland]] (D-MS) on anti-busing measures.<ref name=\"Zeleny\">{{cite news |last1=Zeleny |first1=Jeff |title=Letters from Joe Biden reveal how he sought support of segregationists in fight against busing |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/11/politics/joe-biden-busing-letters-2020/index.html |accessdate=August 28, 2019 |work=CNN |date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 1988 presidential campaign ===\n\n{{Main|Joe Biden 1988 presidential campaign}}\n[[File:Joe Biden in 1987 at White House.png|thumb|right|200px|Biden in 1987]]\n\nBiden ran for the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1988|1988 Democratic presidential nomination]], formally declaring his candidacy at the [[Wilmington station (Delaware)|Wilmington train station]] on June 9, 1987.<ref name=\"nyt-1987-ann\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/10/us/biden-joins-campaign-for-the-presidency.html |title= Biden Joins Campaign for the Presidency |author1=Dionne Jr. |author2=E. J. | newspaper=The New York Times | date=June 10, 1987 | authorlink= E. J. Dionne}}</ref> He was attempting to become the youngest president since [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref name=\"dmn-87\"/> When the campaign began, he was considered a potentially strong candidate because of his moderate image, his speaking ability on the stump, his appeal to [[Baby Boomer]]s, his high-profile position as chair of the Senate Judiciary Committee at the upcoming [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination]] hearings, and his fundraising appeal.<ref name=\"nyt083187\"/><ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|83}} He raised $1.7 million in the first quarter of 1987, more than any other candidate.<ref name=\"nyt083187\"/><ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|83}}\n\nBy August 1987, Biden's campaign, whose messaging was confused due to staff rivalries,<ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|108\u2013109}} had begun to lag behind those of [[Michael Dukakis]] and [[Dick Gephardt]],<ref name=\"nyt083187\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/31/us/biden-once-the-field-s-hot-democrat-is-being-overtaken-by-cooler-rivals.html |title= Biden, Once the Field's Hot Democrat, Is Being Overtaken by Cooler Rivals | author=Toner, Robin | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 31, 1987}}</ref> though he had still raised more funds than any candidate but Dukakis, and was seeing an upturn in Iowa polls.<ref name=\"cook\">{{cite book | last=Cook | first=Rhodes | chapter=The Nominating Process | title=The Elections of 1988 | editor=Nelson, Michael | publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly]] | year=1989 | isbn=0-87187-494-6 | chapter-url-access=registration | chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/electionsof19880000unse | page=[https://archive.org/details/electionsof19880000unse/page/46 46] | url=https://archive.org/details/electionsof19880000unse/page/46 }}</ref><ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|83}} In September 1987, the campaign ran into trouble when he was accused of [[plagiarism|plagiarizing]] a speech that had been made earlier that year by British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Neil Kinnock]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/12/us/biden-s-debate-finale-an-echo-from-abroad.html |title=Biden's Debate Finale: An Echo From Abroad |last=Dowd |first=Maureen |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 12, 1987 |authorlink= Maureen Dowd }}</ref> Kinnock's speech included the lines:\n\n<blockquote>Why am I the first Kinnock in a thousand generations to be able to get to university? [Then pointing to his wife in the audience] Why is Glenys the first woman in her family in a thousand generations to be able to get to university? Was it because all our predecessors were thick?</blockquote>\n\nWhile Biden's speech included the lines:\n\n<blockquote>I started thinking as I was coming over here, why is it that Joe Biden is the first in his family ever to go to a university? [Then pointing to his wife in the audience] Why is it that my wife who is sitting out there in the audience is the first in her family to ever go to college? Is it because our fathers and mothers were not bright? Is it because I'm the first Biden in a thousand generations to get a college and a graduate degree that I was smarter than the rest?</blockquote>\n\nBiden had in fact cited Kinnock as the source for the formulation on previous occasions.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1987/09/13/plagiarism-suggestion-angers-bidens-aides/912bfcf1-b3f3-4850-a14d-e8b0bee1ed63/ |title=Plagiarism Suggestion Angers Biden's Aides |first=Eleanor |last=Randolph |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 13, 1987 |page=A6}}</ref><ref name=\"lat-speech\"/> But he made no reference to the original source at the August 23 Democratic debate at the [[Iowa State Fair]] being reported on,<ref name=\"Whose Broad Stripes\"/>{{rp|230\u2013232}} or in an August 26 interview with the [[National Education Association]].<ref name=\"lat-speech\">{{cite news | newspaper=Los Angeles Times | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-09-16-mn-5412-story.html |title=Differing Versions Cited on Source of Passages: Biden Facing New Flap Over Speeches |date= September 16, 1987 |first=James |last=Risen |authorlink=James Risen |first2=Robert |last2=Shogan }}</ref> Moreover, while political speeches often appropriate ideas and language from each other, Biden's use came under more scrutiny because he changed aspects of his own family's background to match Kinnock's.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/18/us/biden-admits-plagiarism-in-school-but-says-it-was-not-malevolent.html |title=Biden Admits Plagiarism in School But Says It Was Not 'Malevolent' |date= September 18, 1987 |first=E. J. |last=Dionne, Jr. |authorlink=E. J. Dionne}}</ref> Biden was soon found to have lifted passages from a 1967 speech by [[Robert F. Kennedy]] earlier that year (for which his aides took the blame), and a short phrase from the 1961 [[inaugural address of John F. Kennedy]]; and to have done the same with a 1976 passage from [[Hubert H. Humphrey]] two years earlier.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/16/us/biden-is-facing-growing-debate-on-his-speeches.html | title=Biden Is Facing Growing Debate On His Speeches | first=Maureen | last=Dowd | newspaper=The New York Times | date=September 16, 1987 | authorlink= Maureen Dowd}}</ref>\n\nA few days later, Biden's plagiarism incident in law school came to public light.<ref name=\"nyt091887\"/> Video was also released showing that when earlier questioned by a [[New Hampshire]] resident about his grades in law school, he had said he graduated in the \"top half\" of his class, that he had attended law school on a full scholarship, and that he had received three degrees in college,<ref name=\"nyt092287\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1j0FS0Z6ho |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] via YouTube |title=1988 Road to the White House with Sen. Biden |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=October 3, 2012}}{{better source|date=May 2019}}</ref> each of which was untrue or an exaggeration.<ref name=\"nyt092287\"/> Advisers and reporters pointed out that he falsely claimed to have marched in the [[civil rights movement]].<ref>{{cite news | newspaper=New York Times | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/03/us/politics/biden-1988-presidential-campaign.html | title=Biden's First Run for President Was a Calamity. Some Missteps Still Resonate. | date=June 3, 2019 | first=Matt | last = Flegenheimer | access-date=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe limited amount of other news about the race amplified these revelations,<ref>{{cite book | last=Pomper | first=Gerald M. | chapter=The Presidential Nominations | title=The Election of 1988 | publisher=Chatham House Publishers | year=1989 | isbn=0-934540-77-2 | chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/electionof1988re00pomp | page=[https://archive.org/details/electionof1988re00pomp/page/37 37] | url=https://archive.org/details/electionof1988re00pomp/page/37 }}</ref> when most of the public was not yet paying attention to the campaigns; Biden thus fell into what ''[[The Washington Post]]'' writer Paul Taylor called that year's trend, a \"trial by media ordeal\".<ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|86, 88}} Lacking a strong group of supporters to help him survive the crisis,<ref name=\"cook\"/><ref name=\"See How They Run\"/>{{rp|88\u201389}} he withdrew from the race on September 23, 1987, saying his candidacy had been overrun by \"the exaggerated shadow\" of his past mistakes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/24/us/biden-withdraws-bid-for-president-in-wake-of-furor.html | title= Biden Withdraws Bid for President in Wake of Furor |author1=Dionne Jr. |author2=E. J. | newspaper=The New York Times | date=September 24, 1987 | authorlink= E. J. Dionne}}</ref>\n\nAfter Biden withdrew, it was revealed that the Dukakis campaign had secretly made a video highlighting the Biden\u2013Kinnock comparison and distributed it to news outlets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Offers Briton His Talks 'Without Attribution' Biden Meets Kinnock, but He's Not Speechless|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=January 12, 1988}} See also: {{cite news | title=Joseph Biden's Plagiarism; Michael Dukakis's 'Attack Video'\u20141988 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/frenzy/biden.htm | newspaper=The Washington Post | accessdate=August 19, 2008 | date=July 21, 1998}}</ref> Later in 1987, the [[Delaware Supreme Court]]'s Board of Professional Responsibility cleared Biden of the law school plagiarism charges regarding his standing as a lawyer, saying Biden had \"not violated any rules\".<ref name=\"nyt-cleared\">{{cite news | title=Professional Board Clears Biden In Two Allegations of Plagiarism | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/29/us/professional-board-clears-biden-in-two-allegations-of-plagiarism.html |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 29, 1989}}</ref>\n\n=== Brain surgeries ===\n\nIn 1988, Biden suffered two brain aneurysms, one on the right side and one on the left. Each required surgery with high risk of long-term impact on brain functionality. In February 1988, after suffering from several episodes of increasingly severe neck pain, Biden was taken by long-distance ambulance to [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center]] and given lifesaving surgery to correct an [[intracranial berry aneurysm]] that had begun leaking.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/23/science/the-doctors-world-subtle-clues-are-often-the-only-warnings-of-perilous-aneurysms.html |title=The Doctor's World; Subtle Clues Are Often The Only Warnings Of Perilous Aneurysms |author1=Altman, Lawrence M.D. |newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 23, 1998| accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-4cmed\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/20/us/politics/20health.html | title=Many Holes in Disclosure of Nominees' Health |author=Altman, Lawrence M.D. | newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 19, 2008|accessdate=October 26, 2008}}</ref> While recuperating, he suffered a [[pulmonary embolism]], a major complication.<ref name=\"nyt-4cmed\"/>\n\nAnother operation to repair a second aneurysm, which had caused no symptoms but was at risk of bursting, was performed in May 1988.<ref name=\"nyt-4cmed\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/04/us/biden-resting-after-surgery-for-second-brain-aneurysm.html |title=Biden Resting After Surgery For Second Brain Aneurysm | agency=[[Associated Press]] | newspaper=The New York Times | date=May 4, 1988}}</ref> The hospitalization and recovery kept Biden from his duties in the Senate for seven months.<ref name=\"ap-aug22\">{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/vp-candidate-profile-sen-joe-biden/ |title=V.P. candidate profile: Sen. Joe Biden |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=August 22, 2008 |accessdate=September 7, 2008 |first=Calvin |last=Woodward |url-status=live }}</ref> Biden has had no recurrences or effects from the aneurysms since then.<ref name=\"nyt-4cmed\"/>\n\nIn retrospect, Biden's family came to believe the early end to his presidential campaign had been a blessing in disguise, for had he still been campaigning in 1988, he might well not have stopped to seek medical attention and the condition might have become unsurvivable.<ref>Biden, ''Promises to Keep'', p. 225</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/04/us/biden-resting-after-surgery-for-second-brain-aneurysm.html|title=Biden Resting After Surgery For Second Brain Aneurysm|date=May 4, 1988|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In 2013, Biden said, \"they take a saw and they cut your head off\" and \"they literally had to take the top of my head off.\" He also said he was told he would have less than a 50% chance of full recovery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/campaigns/surgeon-who-operated-on-joe-biden-hes-better-now-than-before-brain-surgery|title=Surgeon who operated on Biden: He's better now than before brain surgery|date=April 26, 2019|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the neurosurgeon who operated on Biden in 1988 said he felt Biden was fit to run for president, and joked, \"...{{nbsp}}he's the only politician in Washington I'm sure has a brain, because I've seen it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/article/washington/terence-p-jeffrey/flashback-brain-surgeon-told-biden-he-had-less-50-chance-being|title=FLASHBACK: Brain Surgeon Told Biden He Had Less Than 50% Chance of 'Being Completely Normal'|date=June 5, 2013|website=CNSNews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/joe-bidens-mind-totally-in-clear-despite-suffering-near-death-experience-in-1988|title=Joe Biden's mind 'totally in the clear' despite 1988 aneurysm, his brain surgeon says|first=Lukas|last=Mikelionis|date=April 26, 2019|website=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate Judiciary Committee ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden, official photo.jpg|thumb|upright|Biden, [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] photo]]\n\nBiden was a longtime member of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|U.S. Senate Committee on the Judiciary]]. He chaired it from 1987 to 1995 and served as [[ranking member|ranking minority member]] from 1981 to 1987 and from 1995 to 1997.\n\nWhile chairman, Biden presided over two of the most contentious [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] confirmation hearings in history, [[Robert Bork]]'s in 1987 and [[Clarence Thomas]]'s in 1991.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> In the [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination|Bork hearings]], he stated his opposition to Bork soon after the nomination, reversing his approval in an interview of a hypothetical Bork nomination he had made the previous year and angering conservatives who thought he could not conduct the hearings fairly.<ref name=\"bronner\">Bronner, ''Battle for Justice'', pp. 138\u2013139, 214, 305.</ref> At the close, he won praise for conducting the proceedings fairly and with good humor and courage, despite his presidential campaign's collapse in the middle of them.<ref name=\"bronner\"/><ref name=\"nyt-lg-87\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/08/us/washington-talk-the-bork-hearings-for-biden-epoch-of-belief-epoch-of-incredulity.html | title= Washington Talk: The Bork Hearings; For Biden: Epoch of Belief, Epoch of Incredulity | author=Greenhouse, Linda | newspaper=The New York Times | date=October 8, 1987 | authorlink= Linda Greenhouse}}</ref> Rejecting some of the less intellectually honest arguments that other Bork opponents were making,<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> Biden framed his discussion around the belief that the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]] provides rights to liberty and privacy that extend beyond those explicitly enumerated in the text, and that Bork's strong [[originalism]] was ideologically incompatible with that view.<ref name=\"nyt-lg-87\"/> Bork's nomination was rejected in the committee by a 9\u20135 vote,<ref name=\"nyt-lg-87\"/> and then rejected in the full Senate, 58\u201342.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/24/us/senate-s-roll-call-on-the-bork-vote.html|title=Senate's Roll-Call On the Bork Vote|date=October 24, 1987 |newspaper=The New York Times |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|Thomas hearings]], Biden's questions on constitutional issues were often long and convoluted, to the point that Thomas sometimes forgot the question being asked.<ref name=\"mayer-abramson\">Mayer; Abramson, ''Strange Justice'', p. 213, 218, 336.</ref> Biden's style annoyed many viewers.<ref name=\"time-be-joe\"/> Thomas later wrote that despite Biden's earlier private assurances, his questions had been akin to [[beanball]]s.<ref name=\"thomas-vi\">{{cite news |title=Clarence Thomas: A Silent Justice Speaks Out: Part VI: Becoming a Judge\u2014and perhaps a Justice |last=Greenburg |first=Jan Crawford |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=September 30, 2007 |url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Story?id=3664944&page=4 |accessdate=October 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622121644/http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Story?id=3664944&page=4 |archive-date=June 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The nomination came out of the committee without a recommendation, with Biden opposed.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> In part due to his own bad experiences with his presidential campaign, Biden was reluctant to let personal matters into the hearings.<ref name=\"mayer-abramson\"/> He initially shared with the committee, but not the public, [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment charges, on the grounds she was not yet willing to testify.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> After she did, Biden did not permit other witnesses to testify further on her behalf, such as Angela Wright (who was present, waiting to testify, and who had made a similar charge) and experts on harassment.<ref name=\"nyt-hill\">{{cite news | url=https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/23/biden-and-anita-hill-revisited/ |title=Biden and Anita Hill, Revisited |last=Phillips |first=Kate | newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 23, 2008 | accessdate=September 12, 2008}}</ref> Biden said he was striving to preserve Thomas's [[right to privacy]] and the hearings' decency.<ref name=\"mayer-abramson\"/><ref name=\"nyt-hill\"/> The full Senate confirmed Thomas by a 52\u201348 vote, with Biden again opposed.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> During and afterward, liberal legal groups and women's groups strongly criticized Biden for mishandling the hearings and not doing enough to support Hill.<ref name=\"nyt-hill\"/> Biden later sought out women to serve on the Judiciary Committee and emphasized women's issues in the committee's legislative agenda.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> In April 2019, he called Hill to express regret over how he treated her; after the conversation, Hill said she remained deeply unsatisfied.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/us/politics/joe-biden-anita-hill.html|title=Joe Biden Expresses Regret to Anita Hill, but She Says 'I'm Sorry' Is Not Enough|last=Stolberg|first=Sheryl Gay|date=April 25, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 25, 2019|last2=Martin|first2=Jonathan|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n[[File:Biden Crime Bill.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Biden spoke at the signing of the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]] in 1994.]]\nBiden was involved in crafting many federal crime laws. He spearheaded the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]] of 1994, also known as the Biden Crime Law, which included the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]], which expired in 2004 after its ten-year sunset period and was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.ft.com/content/412f47b0-5694-11e2-aad0-00144feab49a |title=Biden faces key role in second term |last=Fifield |first=Anna |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=January 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"time-cov-0113\"/> It also included the [[Violence Against Women Act]] (VAWA), which contains a broad array of measures to combat [[domestic violence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2014/09/19/biden-men-who-dont-stop-violence-against-women-are-cowards/ |title=Biden: Men who don't stop violence against women are \"cowards\" |author=Finley, Bruce |newspaper=The Denver Post |date=September 19, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013133013/http://www.denverpost.com/environment/ci_26568257/vice-president-biden-denver-discuss-domestic-violence-issues |archivedate=October 13, 2015 }}</ref> In 2000, the Supreme Court ruled in ''[[United States v. Morrison]]'' that the VAWA section allowing a federal civil remedy for victims of [[gender]]-motivated violence exceeded Congress's authority and was therefore unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|title=''United States v. Morrison'', 529 U.S. 598 (2000)|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/99-5.ZS.html|publisher=[[Cornell University]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref> Congress reauthorized VAWA in 2000 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bash |first=Dana |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/10/11/congress.terror/index.html |title=Senate votes to allow compensation for terror victims, re-authorizes Violence Against Women Act |work=CNN |date=October 11, 2000|accessdate=August 24, 2008}} See also: {{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/story/deal-reached-on-violence-against-women-act |title=Deal Reached on Violence Against Women Act |work=Fox News|date=December 16, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517064449/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,179001,00.html |archive-date=May 17, 2009 |url-status=live |agency=Associated Press }}</ref> Biden has said, \"I consider the Violence Against Women Act the single most significant legislation that I've crafted during my 35-year tenure in the Senate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618 | title=Domestic Violence | publisher=[[United States Senate|Biden senate website]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822144642/http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618|archivedate=August 22, 2008|accessdate=September 9, 2008}}</ref> In 2004 and 2005, he enlisted major American technology companies in diagnosing the problems of the [[Austin, Texas]]-based [[National Domestic Violence Hotline]], and to donate equipment and expertise to it in a successful effort to improve its services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making connections to end Domestic Violence|url=http://www.microsoft.com/issues/essays/2004/05-05violence.mspx|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|author=Cates, Sheryl|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430104855/http://www.microsoft.com/issues/essays/2004/05-05violence.mspx|archivedate=April 30, 2008|date=May 5, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndvh.org/tenth/history.html |title=History |publisher=[[National Domestic Violence Hotline]] |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705193830/http://www.ndvh.org/tenth/history.html |archivedate=July 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBiden was critical of the actions of [[United States Office of the Independent Counsel|Independent Counsel]] [[Kenneth Starr]] during the 1990s [[Whitewater controversy]] and [[Lewinsky scandal]] investigations, and said, \"it's going to be a cold day in hell\" before another Independent Counsel would be granted the same powers.<ref>''Almanac of American Politics'' 2000, p. 372.</ref> He voted to acquit on both charges during the [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|impeachment of President Clinton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/02/12/senate.vote/ |title=How the senators voted on impeachment |work=CNN |date=February 12, 1999 }}</ref>\n\nAs chairman of the [[International Narcotics Control Caucus]], Biden wrote the laws that created the U.S. \"[[Drug Czar]]\", who oversees and coordinates national drug control policy. In April 2003, he introduced the Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to Ecstasy ([[RAVE Act|RAVE]]) Act. He continued to work to stop the spread of \"[[date rape]] drugs\" such as [[flunitrazepam]], and party drugs such as [[MDMA|ecstasy]] and [[ketamine]]. In 2004, he worked to pass a bill outlawing [[steroid]]s like [[androstenedione]], the drug many baseball players used.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" />\n\nBiden's \"Kids 2000\" legislation established a public-private partnership to provide computer centers, teachers, Internet access, and technical training to young people, particularly low-income and at-risk youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biden.senate.gov/newsroom/details.cfm?id=229820&&|title=Kids 2000 Program|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223064751/http://biden.senate.gov/newsroom/details.cfm?id=229820&& |archivedate=December 23, 2007|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Senate Foreign Relations Committee ===\n\n[[File:Bill Clinton and officials on Air Force One.jpg|thumb|right|Senator Biden accompanied [[Bill Clinton|President Clinton]] and other officials to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]] in December 1997.]]\n\nBiden was a longtime member of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|U.S. Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]]. In 1997, he became the [[ranking member|ranking minority member]] and chaired the committee in January 2001 and from June 2001 to 2003. When Democrats retook control of the Senate after the [[United States Senate elections, 2006|2006 elections]], Biden again assumed the top spot on the committee.<ref name=\"aap08-365\"/> He was generally a [[liberal internationalist]] in foreign policy.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/world/americas/24iht-policy.4.15591832.html | title=In Biden, Obama chooses a foreign policy adherent of diplomacy before force | author=Gordon, Michael R. | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 24, 2008 | accessdate=November 5, 2009 | authorlink=Michael R. Gordon}}</ref><ref name=\"lat-foreign\"/> He collaborated effectively with important Republican senators such as [[Richard Lugar]] and [[Jesse Helms]] and sometimes went against elements of his own party.<ref name=\"aap08-365\"/><ref name=\"lat-foreign\"/> Biden was also co-chairman of the [[NATO]] Observer Group in the Senate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nato.int/docu/review/1997/9705-05.htm |title=Transatlantic relations: Stormy weather on the way to enlargement? |last=Sloan |first=Stanley |work=NATO Review |date=October 1997 |accessdate=August 29, 2008 }}</ref> A partial list covering this time showed Biden meeting with 150 leaders from nearly 60 countries and international organizations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2008/09/23/meetings_with_foreign_leaders.html |title=Meetings with Foreign Leaders? Biden's Been There, Done That | author=Kessler, Glenn | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=September 23, 2008 | accessdate=November 5, 2009 | authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist)}}</ref> He held frequent hearings as chairman of the committee, as well as many subcommittee hearings during the three times he chaired the [[United States Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee on European Affairs|Subcommittee on European Affairs]].<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/>\n[[File:Bidenpetraeus.jpg|thumb|right|Biden gives an opening statement and takes questions at a [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] hearing on [[Iraq]] in 2007]]\n\nBiden voted against authorization for the [[Gulf War]] in 1991,<ref name=\"lat-foreign\">{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-aug-24-na-foreignpol24-story.html |title=Joe Biden respected\u2014if not always popular\u2014for foreign policy record |last=Richter |first=Paul |last2=Levey |first2=Noam N. |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=November 5, 2009 }}</ref> siding with 45 of the 55 Democratic senators; he said the U.S. was bearing almost all the burden in the [[Coalition of the Gulf War|anti-Iraq coalition]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/01/13/world/confrontation-gulf-congress-acts-authorize-war-gulf-margins-are-5-votes-senate.html |title=Congress Acts to Authorize War in Gulf |last=Clymer |first=Adam |newspaper=The New York Times | date=January 13, 1991 | authorlink=Adam Clymer}}</ref>\n\nBiden became interested in the [[Yugoslav Wars]] after hearing about [[Serbs|Serbian]] abuses during the [[Croatian War of Independence]] in 1991.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/> Once the [[Bosnian War]] broke out, Biden was among the first to call for the \"[[Lift and strike (Bosnia)|lift and strike]]\" policy of lifting the arms embargo, training [[Bosniaks|Bosnian Muslims]] and supporting them with [[NATO]] air strikes, and investigating [[war crimes]].<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/><ref name=\"aap08-365\"/> The [[George H. W. Bush administration]] and [[Clinton administration]] were both reluctant to implement the policy, fearing Balkan entanglement.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/><ref name=\"lat-foreign\"/> In April 1993, Biden spent a week in the Balkans and held a tense three-hour meeting with Serbian leader [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]].<ref name=\"wapo-bosnia\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/10/06/AR2008100602681.html | title=Biden Played Less Than Key Role in Bosnia Legislation | author=Kessler, Glenn | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=October 7, 2008 | accessdate=November 5, 2009 | authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist)}}</ref> Biden related that he had told Milo\u0161evi\u0107, \"I think you're a damn war criminal and you should be tried as one.\"<ref name=\"wapo-bosnia\"/> Biden wrote an amendment in 1992 to compel the Bush administration to arm the Bosnians, but deferred in 1994 to a somewhat softer stance the Clinton administration preferred, before signing on the following year to a stronger measure sponsored by [[Bob Dole]] and [[Joe Lieberman]].<ref name=\"wapo-bosnia\"/> The engagement led to a successful NATO peacekeeping effort.<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/> Biden has called his role in affecting Balkans policy in the mid-1990s his \"proudest moment in public life\" related to foreign policy.<ref name=\"lat-foreign\"/>\n\nIn 1998, ''[[Congressional Quarterly]]'' named Biden one of \"Twelve Who Made a Difference\" for playing a lead role in several foreign policy matters, including [[NATO enlargement]] and the successful passage of bills to streamline foreign affairs agencies and punish religious persecution overseas.<ref name=\"state-10k\"/>\n\nIn 1999, during the [[Kosovo War]], Biden supported the [[1999 NATO bombing of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|NATO bombing campaign against Serbia and Montenegro]],<ref name=\"nyt-foreign\"/> and co-sponsored with [[John McCain]] the McCain-Biden Kosovo Resolution, which called on President Clinton to use all necessary force, including ground troops, to confront Milo\u0161evi\u0107 over Serbian actions in [[Kosovo]].<ref name=\"lat-foreign\"/><ref name=\"wsj082508\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121954185485266719 | title=Biden, McCain Have a Friendship\u2014and More\u2014in Common | author=Holmes, Elizabeth | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=August 25, 2008 | accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBiden was a strong supporter of the 2001 [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]], saying, \"Whatever it takes, we should do it.\"<ref name=TNR.hawk>{{cite magazine|last1=Crowley|first1=Michael|title=HawkDown|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/hawk-down|magazine=The New Republic|quote=Even before Obama announced his run for president, Biden was warning that Afghanistan, not Iraq, was the \"central front\" in the war against Al Qaeda, requiring a major U.S. commitment. \"Whatever it takes, we should do it,\" Biden said in February 2002. \"}}</ref>\n\nAs head of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Biden said in 2002 that [[Saddam Hussein]] was a threat to national security and there was no option but to \"eliminate\" that threat.<ref name=\"MTP04292007\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/18381961 |work=[[Meet the Press]] |title=MTP Transcript for April 29, 2007 |author=Tim Russert |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 29, 2007 |page=2 |author-link=Tim Russert }}</ref> In October 2002, he voted in favor of the [[Iraq Resolution|Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq]], approving the U.S. invasion of [[Iraq War|Iraq]].<ref name=\"lat-foreign\" /> More significantly, as chair of the committee, he assembled a series of witnesses to testify in favor of the authorization. They gave testimony grossly misrepresenting the intent, history of and status of Saddam and his Sunni government, which was an openly avowed enemy of [[al Qaida|al-Qaida]], and touting Iraq's fictional possession of [[Weapons of Mass Destruction|weapons of mass destruction]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/feb/17/joe-biden-role-iraq-war Joe Biden championed the Iraq war. Will that come back to haunt him now?], ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Mark Weisbrot]], February 17, 2020. Retrieved February 19, 2020.</ref>\n\nWhile he eventually became a critic of the war and viewed his vote and role as a \"mistake\", he did not push for U.S. withdrawal.<ref name=\"lat-foreign\" /><ref name=\"wapo-bosnia\" /> He supported the appropriations to pay for the occupation, but argued repeatedly that the war should be internationalized, that more soldiers were needed, and that the Bush administration should \"level with the American people\" about the cost and length of the conflict.<ref name=\"aap08-365\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 365.</ref><ref name=\"wsj082508\" /> By late 2006, Biden's stance had shifted considerably, and he opposed the [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|troop surge of 2007]],<ref name=\"lat-foreign\" /><ref name=\"wapo-bosnia\" /> saying General [[David Petraeus]] was \"dead, flat wrong\" in believing the surge could work.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\" /> Biden instead advocated dividing Iraq into a loose [[federalism|federation]] of three [[ethnic group|ethnic]] states.<ref name=\"Divided\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/19/weekinreview/19shanker.html | title=Divided They Stand, but on Graves | author=Thom Shanker | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 19, 2007}}</ref> In November 2006, Biden and [[Leslie H. Gelb]], President Emeritus of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], released a comprehensive strategy to end [[Civil war in Iraq (2006-07)|sectarian violence in Iraq]].<ref name=\"LAT20071001\">{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-oct-01-fg-iraq1-story.html |first=Ned |last=Parker |first2=Raheem |last2=Salman |title=U.S. vote unites Iraqis in anger |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=October 1, 2007 }}</ref> Rather than continuing the present approach or withdrawing, the plan called for \"a third way\": federalizing Iraq and giving [[Kurd]]s, [[Shiite]]s, and [[Sunni Islam|Sunnis]] \"breathing room\" in their own regions.<ref name=\"witcover\" />{{rp|572\u2013573}} In September 2007, a non-binding resolution endorsing such a scheme passed the Senate,<ref name=\"LAT20071001\" /> but the idea was unfamiliar, had no political constituency, and failed to gain traction.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\" /> Iraq's political leadership denounced the resolution as ''de facto'' partitioning of the country, and the [[Embassy of the United States in Baghdad|U.S. Embassy in Baghdad]] issued a statement distancing itself from it.<ref name=\"LAT20071001\" />\n\nIn March 2004, Biden secured the brief release of Libyan democracy activist and [[political prisoner]] [[Fathi Eljahmi]], after meeting with leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] in [[Tripoli]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/27/international/africa/27libya.html | title=For a Critic, Libya's Nascent Openness Doesn't Apply | author=Smith, Craig S. | newspaper=The New York Times | date=December 27, 2004 | accessdate=November 5, 2009 | authorlink=Craig S. Smith}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/15/AR2006111501576_pf.html | title=Support Builds for Libyan Dissident | author=Boustany, Nora | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=November 16, 2006 | accessdate=November 5, 2009}}</ref> In May 2008, Biden sharply criticized President [[George W. Bush]] for his speech to [[Israel]]'s [[Knesset]], where he suggested some Democrats were acting the way some Western leaders did when they appeased Hitler in the run-up to World War{{nbsp}}II. Biden said, \"This is bullshit. This is malarkey. This is outrageous. Outrageous for the president of the United States to go to a foreign country, sit in the Knesset{{nbsp}}... and make this kind of ridiculous statement{{nbsp}}... Since when does this administration think that if you sit down, you have to eliminate the word 'no' from your vocabulary?\" He later apologized for using the expletive.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/05/15/bush.dems/index.html |title=Dems fire back at Bush on 'appeasement' statement |last=Henry |first=Ed |work=CNN |date=May 16, 2008 |accessdate=September 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Delaware matters ===\n\n[[File:BidenDoverAFB1997.jpg|thumb|right|Biden toured a new facility at [[Delaware]]'s [[Dover Air Force Base]] in October 2007.]]\n\nBiden was a familiar figure to his Delaware constituency, by virtue of his daily train commute from there,<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> and generally sought to attend to state needs.<ref name=\"aap08-366\"/> He strongly supported increased [[Amtrak]] funding and rail security;<ref name=\"aap08-366\"/> he hosted barbecues and an annual Christmas dinner for the Amtrak crews, who sometimes held the last train of the night a few minutes so he could catch it.<ref name=\"watn020109\"/><ref name=\"aap08-366\"/> He earned the nickname \"Amtrak Joe\" as a result (and in 2011, Amtrak's [[Wilmington station (Delaware)|Wilmington Station]] was named the Joseph R. Biden Jr. Railroad Station, in honor of the 7,000-plus trips he made from there).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2011/03/amtrak-joe-biden-gets-his-own-train-station.html | title='Amtrak Joe' Biden Gets His Own Train Station |last=Travers |first=Karen |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=March 16, 2011 |accessdate=March 16, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319050955/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2011/03/amtrak-joe-biden-gets-his-own-train-station.html | archivedate=March 19, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/19/vice-president-biden-gets_n_837999.html |title=Vice President Biden Gets Wilmington Amtrak Station Named For Him |work=The Huffington Post |date=March 19, 2011 |accessdate=July 27, 2016 }}</ref> He was an advocate for Delaware military installations, including [[Dover Air Force Base]] and [[New Castle Air National Guard Base]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.carper.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/pressreleases?ID=A0D1424D-120B-4BCA-8F4C-12253EEE97C8 |title=Senate Approves $24.4 Million for Guard, Dover Air Force Bases |publisher=[[United States Senate]] for [[Thomas R. Carper]] |date=September 23, 2005 |accessdate=July 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, when Biden was seeking reelection to the Senate, [[Desegregation busing in the United States#Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington's federally mandated cross-district busing plan]] generated much turmoil. Biden's compromise solution between his white constituents and African-American leaders was to introduce legislation to outlaw the court's power to enforce certain types of busing, while allowing it to end segregation school districts had deliberately imposed. White anti-integrationists seized on a comment Biden made that he would support the use of federal helicopters if Wilmington's schools could not be voluntarily integrated, and Delaware [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] head Littleton P. Mitchell later said Biden \"adequately represented our community for many years, but he quivered that one time on busing.\" The compromise nearly alienated him from both working-class whites and African-Americans, but tensions ended after the end of a teachers' strike that began over pay issues raised by the busing plan.<ref name=\"Broder\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/18/us/politics/18biden.html | title=Biden's record on race is scuffed by 3 episodes | author=Broder, John M. | newspaper=The New York Times | date=September 17, 2008 | accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1991, Biden served as an [[adjunct professor]] at the [[Widener University School of Law]], Delaware's only law school, teaching a seminar on [[constitutional law]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.widener.edu/Academics/Faculty/ProfilesDeAdj/BidenJosephR.aspx |title=Faculty: Joseph R. Biden, Jr. | publisher=[[Widener University School of Law]] |accessdate=September 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006123224/http://law.widener.edu/Academics/Faculty/ProfilesDeAdj/BidenJosephR.aspx | archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"wid-veep-elect\"/> The seminar was one of Widener's most popular, often with a waiting list for enrollment.<ref name=\"wid-veep-elect\"/> Biden typically co-taught the course with another professor, taking on at least half the course minutes and sometimes flying back from overseas to make one of the classes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://philly.metro.us/metro/local/article/For_Widener_Law_students_a_teacher_aims_high/13457.html |title=For Widener Law students, a teacher aims high |author=Purchla, Matt |publisher=[[Metro International|Metro Philadelphia]] |date=August 26, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004214751/http://philly.metro.us/metro/local/article/For_Widener_Law_students_a_teacher_aims_high/13457.html |archivedate=October 4, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.delcotimes.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=20094884&BRD=1675&PAG=461&dept_id=18171&rfi=6 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919152356/http://www.delcotimes.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=20094884&BRD=1675&PAG=461&dept_id=18171&rfi=6 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 19, 2008 |title=For Widener Law students, a teacher aims high |author=Carey, Kathleen E. |publisher=[[Delaware County Daily and Sunday Times]] |date=August 27, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2000s, Biden sponsored bankruptcy legislation that was sought by [[MBNA]], one of Delaware's largest companies, and other credit card issuers.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> He allowed an amendment to the bill to increase the homestead exemption for homeowners declaring bankruptcy and fought for an amendment to forbid anti-abortion felons from using bankruptcy to discharge fines; President Clinton vetoed the bill in 2000 but it finally passed in 2005 as the [[Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act]], with Biden supporting it.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> A vociferous supporter, Biden was one of only 18 Democratic senators to vote with the Republicans in favor of the legislation, while leading Democrats and consumer rights organizations came out in opposition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/dec/02/joe-biden-student-loan-debt-2005-act-2020 |title=How Biden Helped Create the Student Debt Problem He Now Promises to Fix |date=December 2, 2019 |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |last=Pilkington |first=Ed }}</ref>\n\nBiden held up trade agreements with Russia when that country stopped importing U.S. chickens. The downstate [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex County]] region is the nation's top chicken-producing area.<ref name=\"aap08-366\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Biden requested and gained $67 million worth of projects for his constituents through [[Earmark (politics)|congressional earmarks]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/13614-clinton-tops-2008-rivals-gets-530m-in-earmarks |title=Clinton tops 2008 rivals, gets $530M in earmarks |date=November 9, 2007 |accessdate=August 24, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |last=Bolton |first=Alexander }}</ref>\n\n=== Reputation ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden, official photo portrait 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Biden's official [[United States Senate|Senate]] photo (2005)]]\n\nFollowing his first election in 1972, Biden was reelected to six more Senate terms, in [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 1978|1978]], [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 1984|1984]], [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 1990|1990]], [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 1996|1996]], [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 2002|2002]], and [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 2008|2008]], usually getting about 60% of the vote.<ref name=\"aap08-366\"/> He did not face strong opposition; Pete du Pont, then governor, chose not to run against him in 1984.<ref name=\"cby-44\">''Current Biography Yearbook 1987'', p. 44.</ref> Biden spent 28 years as a junior senator due to the two-year seniority of his Republican colleague [[William Roth]]. After [[Tom Carper]] defeated Roth in 2000, Biden became Delaware's senior senator. He then became the longest-serving senator in Delaware history<ref>{{cite news | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/08/23/biden.democrat.vp.candidate/ |title= Obama introduces Biden as running mate |work=CNN |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=September 18, 2008}}</ref> and, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, was the 18th-longest-serving senator in U.S. history.<ref name=\"26 Aug 2018\">{{cite web |title=Longest Serving Senators|url=https://www.senate.gov/senators/longest_serving_senators.htm |website=United States Senate |publisher=United States Senate|accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref> In May 1999, Biden became the youngest senator to cast 10,000 votes.<ref name=\"state-10k\">{{cite web | url=http://usinfo.state.gov/journals/itps/0301/ijpe/pj61bios.htm | title=Senator Joseph Biden (Democrat, Delaware) | publisher=[[U.S. State Department]] |date=March 2001 | accessdate=November 26, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080712124319/http://usinfo.state.gov/journals/itps/0301/ijpe/pj61bios.htm |archivedate = July 12, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWith a [[net worth]] between $59,000 and $366,000, and almost no outside income or investment income, Biden was consistently ranked one of the least wealthy members of the Senate.<ref name=\"lat082408nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-aug-24-na-assess24-story.html | title=Demographics part of calculation: Biden adds experience, yes, but he could also help with Catholics, blue-collar whites and women |last=Wallsten |first=Peter |newspaper=Los Angeles Times | date=August 24, 2008 | accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2008/08/24/a_look_at_bidens_net_worth/ |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=Boston Globe |title=A look at Biden's net worth |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=February 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725145844/http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2008/08/24/a_look_at_bidens_net_worth/ |archivedate=July 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/13/us/politics/13biden.html | title=Biden Releases Tax Returns, in Part to Pressure Rivals |last=Broder |first=John M. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 13, 2008 |accessdate=September 13, 2008}}</ref> Biden said he was listed as the second-poorest member in Congress; he was not proud of the distinction, but attributed it to having been elected early in his career.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/09/12/biden-tax-returns-revealed/ |title=Biden tax returns revealed |last=Mooney |first=Alexander |work=CNN | date=September 12, 2008 | accessdate=September 13, 2008}}</ref> He has said he realized early in his senatorial career how vulnerable poorer public officials are to offers of financial contributions in exchange for policy support, and pushed [[campaign finance reform]] measures during his first term.<ref name=\"cby-44\"/> Biden earned $15.6 million in 2017\u201318.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Viser|first1=Matt|last2=Narayanswamy|first2=Anu|title=Joe Biden earned $15.6 million in the two years after leaving the vice presidency|work=The Washington Post|date=July 9, 2019|url=https://beta.washingtonpost.com/politics/joe-biden-earned-156-million-in-the-two-years-after-leaving-the-vice-presidency/2019/07/09/55aad492-a27e-11e9-b8c8-75dae2607e60_story.html?outputType=amp|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref> By 2019, Biden called his middle-class status a \"state of mind\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=HOLLY OTTERBEIN |last2=MARC CAPUTO |title='Middle-Class Joe' rakes in millions |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/03/18/joe-biden-2020-money-wealth-1221934 |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 18, 2019 |language=en |quote=For Biden and his supporters, \"middle class\" isn't so much a financial status as it is a state of mind, a sensibility that's ingrained in his political DNA.}}</ref> His assets increased to between $2.2 million and $8{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eder|first1=Steve|last2=Glueck|first2=Katie|title=Joe Biden's Tax Returns Show More Than $15 Million in Income After 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 9, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/us/politics/joe-biden-net-worth.html|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe political writer [[Howard Fineman]] has said, \"Biden is not an academic, he's not a theoretical thinker, he's a great street pol. He comes from a long line of working people in Scranton\u2014auto salesmen, car dealers, people who know how to make a sale. He has that great Irish gift.\"<ref name=\"watn020109\"/> Political columnist [[David S. Broder]] has viewed Biden as having grown since he came to Washington and since his failed 1988 presidential bid: \"He responds to real people\u2014that's been consistent throughout. And his ability to understand himself and deal with other politicians has gotten much much better.\"<ref name=\"watn020109\"/> Traub concludes that \"Biden is the kind of fundamentally happy person who can be as generous toward others as he is to himself.\"<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/>\n\n=== Gaffes ===\n\nDuring his years as a senator, Biden acquired a reputation for loquaciousness<ref>{{cite news | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0601/12/sitroom.01.html |title=Transcripts |work=[[The Situation Room with Wolf Blitzer|The Situation Room]] |publisher=CNN |date=January 12, 2006 |accessdate=September 21, 2008}}</ref> and \"putting his foot in his mouth\".<ref name=\"abc-loq\">{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Story?id=2838420 | title=A Biden Problem: Foot in Mouth | author=Tapper, Jake | publisher=[[ABC News]] | date=January 31, 2007 | accessdate=September 21, 2008 | authorlink=Jake Tapper}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-no2\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/19/world/senate-struggles-to-pay-attention-to-the-remapping-of-nato.html |title= Senate Struggles to Pay Attention to the Remapping of NATO |last=Seelye |first=Katharine Q. |newspaper=The New York Times | date=March 19, 1998 | accessdate=September 21, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"time-pcs\">{{cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1835480,00.html |title=Halperin on Biden: Pros and Cons |last=Halperin |first=Mark |magazine=Time |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=September 21, 2008 |authorlink=Mark Halperin }}</ref> He has been a strong speaker and debater and a frequent and effective guest on [[Sunday morning talk shows]].<ref name=\"time-pcs\"/> In public appearances, he is known to deviate from prepared remarks.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/ben-smith/2008/12/biden-enemy-of-the-prepared-remarks-014500 |title=Biden, enemy of the prepared remarks |last=Smith |first=Ben |work=[[Politico]] |date=December 2, 2008 |accessdate=December 2, 2008}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Biden's \"weak filters make him capable of blurting out pretty much anything\".<ref name=\"nyt-no2\"/>\n\n=== 2008 presidential campaign ===\n\n{{Main|Joe Biden 2008 presidential campaign}}\n[[File:Joe Biden Presidential Campaign Logo 08.svg|thumb|Biden's 2008 campaign logo]]\n\nBiden thought about running for president again ever since his failed 1988 bid.{{refn|group=nb| Biden chose not to run for president in 1992 in part because he had voted against the resolution authorizing the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"aap08-366\"/> He considered joining the Democratic field of candidates for the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential race]] but in August 2003 decided otherwise, saying he did not have enough time and any attempt would be too much of a long shot.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2003/ALLPOLITICS/08/11/biden/index.html |title=Sen. Biden not running for president |work=CNN |date=August 12, 2003 |accessdate=September 18, 2008}}</ref> Around 2004, Biden was also widely discussed as a possible Secretary of State in a Democratic administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/kerry-to-opt-for-the-senator-who-copied-kinnock-8k0k0b22sq9 |accessdate=August 24, 2008|newspaper=The Times |location=London |title=Kerry to opt for the senator who copied Kinnock |last=Baker |first=Gerard |date=October 29, 2004 }}</ref> }} He declared [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2008|his candidacy for president]] on January 31, 2007, after having discussed running for months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/31/AR2007013100404.html |title=Biden Stumbles at the Starting Gate|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=August 23, 2008|date=January 1, 2007|author=Balz, Dan|authorlink=Dan Balz}}</ref> Biden made a formal announcement to [[Tim Russert]] on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', saying he would \"be the best Biden I can be\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2007/01/08/biden_27/ |title=The 'Best Biden' for President?|work=[[Salon.com|Salon]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008 |last=Koppelman |first=Alex |date=January 8, 2007|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724011704/http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2007/01/08/biden/ |archivedate=July 24, 2008}}</ref> In January 2006, Delaware newspaper columnist Harry F. Themal wrote that Biden \"occupies the sensible center of the Democratic Party\".<ref name=\"themal\">{{cite news | title=Biden says he's on track for 2008 run | author=Themal, Harry F. | work=[[The News Journal]] | date=January 23, 2006}}</ref> Themal concluded that that was the position Biden desired, and that in a campaign \"he plans to stress the dangers to the security of the average American, not just from the terrorist threat, but from the lack of health assistance, crime, and energy dependence on unstable parts of the world.\"<ref name=\"themal\" />[[File:Sen. Joe Biden attends a Creston house party.jpg|thumb|right|Biden campaigning at a [[Political house party|house party]] in [[Creston, Iowa]], July 2007]]\n\nDuring his campaign, Biden focused on the [[Iraq War|war in Iraq]] and his support for implementing the Biden-Gelb plan to achieve political success. He touted his record in the Senate as the head of major congressional committees and his experience in foreign policy. Despite speculation to the contrary,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.observer.com/2007/candidate-secretary-state|title=A Candidate For Secretary Of State|newspaper=[[The New York Observer]]|date=June 12, 2007|accessdate=August 23, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919053641/http://www.observer.com/2007/candidate-secretary-state|archivedate=September 19, 2008}}</ref> Biden rejected the notion of becoming Secretary of State, focusing on only the presidency. At a 2007 campaign event, Biden said, \"I know a lot of my opponents out there say I'd be a great secretary of state. Seriously, every one of them. Do you watch any of the debates? 'Joe's right, Joe's right, Joe's right.{{'\"}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ReMqAAAAIBAJ&pg=6332,4673219 |newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Biden says he wouldn't be secretary of state|date = November 30, 2007 |page=12A}}</ref> Other candidates' comments that \"Joe is right\" in the [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential debates, 2008|Democratic debates]] were converted into a Biden campaign theme and ad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wbOa989IRYw |publisher=YouTube |title=Joe is Right |accessdate=August 23, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080702201709/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wbOa989IRYw |archivedate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-2007, Biden stressed his foreign policy expertise compared to Obama's, saying of the latter, \"I think he can be ready, but right now I don't believe he is. The presidency is not something that lends itself to on-the-job training.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Decision2008/Story?id=3498294&page=1 |title=Transcript: The Democratic Debate | publisher=[[ABC News]] | date=August 19, 2007 | accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> Biden also said Obama was copying some of his foreign policy ideas.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/29/magazine/29Biden-t.html | title=After Cheney | author=Traub, James | magazine=[[The New York Times Magazine]] | date=November 24, 2009 | page=MM34 | authorlink=James Traub}}</ref> Biden was noted for his one-liners on the campaign trail, saying of Republican then-frontrunner [[Rudy Giuliani]] at the debate on October 30, 2007, in Philadelphia, \"There's only three things he mentions in a sentence: a noun, and a verb and 9/11.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071101/NEWS01/711010358/1043/NEWS01|newspaper=[[Concord Monitor]]|title=A noun, a verb and 9/11|author=Farrell, Joelle|accessdate=August 23, 2008|date=November 1, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828010554/http://www.concordmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20071101%2FNEWS01%2F711010358%2F1043%2FNEWS01|archivedate=August 28, 2008}}</ref> Overall, Biden's debate performances were an effective mixture of humor, and sharp and surprisingly disciplined comments.<ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|336}}\n\nBiden made controversial remarks during the campaign. On the day of his January 2007 announcement, he spoke of fellow Democratic candidate and Senator [[Barack Obama]]: \"I mean, you got the first mainstream African-American who is articulate and bright and clean and a nice-looking guy\u2014I mean, that's a storybook, man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2007/02/biden-unbound-lays-into-clinton-obama-edwards/ |title=Biden Unbound: Lays Into Clinton, Obama, Edwards |author=Horowitz, Jason|work=[[The New York Observer]]|date=February 4, 2007}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb| Several [[linguistics|linguists]] and political analysts said the correct transcription includes a comma after the word \"African-American\", which one said \"would significantly change the meaning (and the degree of offensiveness) of Biden's comment\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itre.cis.upenn.edu/~myl/languagelog/archives/004131.html |title=Language Log: Biden's Comma |last=Liberman |first=Mark |date=February 1, 2007 |publisher=[[Language Log]] |authorlink=Mark Liberman}}</ref>}} This comment undermined his campaign as soon as it began and significantly damaged his fund-raising capabilities;<ref name=\"gamechange\">{{Cite book | first=John | last=Heilemann |authorlink=John Heilemann | first2=Mark | last2=Halperin | authorlink2=Mark Halperin | title=Game Change: Obama and the Clintons, McCain and Palin, and the Race of a Lifetime | publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=New York | year= 2010 | isbn=978-0-06-173363-5| title-link=Game Change }}</ref>{{rp|336}} it later took second place on ''Time'' magazine's list of Top 10 Campaign Gaffes for 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1686204_1690170_1690790,00.html |title=Top 10 Campaign Gaffes |last=Lim |first=Christine |first2=M. J. |last2=Stephey |work=Time |accessdate=August 20, 2008 |date=December 9, 2007 }}</ref> Biden had also been criticized in July 2006 for a remark he made about his support among [[Indian Americans]]: \"I've had a great relationship. In Delaware, the largest growth in population is Indian-Americans moving from India. You cannot go to a 7-Eleven or a Dunkin' Donuts unless you have a slight Indian accent. I'm not joking.\"<ref name=\"cbs070706\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bidens-comments-ruffle-feathers/ |title=Biden's Comments Ruffle Feathers, Senator Forced To Explain His Remarks About Indian-Americans |date=July 7, 2006 |accessdate=August 24, 2008 |publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> Biden later said the remark was not intended to be derogatory.<ref name=\"cbs070706\"/>{{refn|group=nb|The Indian-American activist who was on the receiving end of Biden's comment stated that he was \"100 percent behind [Biden] because he did nothing wrong.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Distaso |title=Indian-American activist defends Sen. Biden |url=http://www.unionleader.com/article.aspx?headline=Indian-American+activist+defends+Sen.+Biden&articleId=0108a2f4-0530-4860-b010-5b076007bff6 | newspaper = [[New Hampshire Union Leader]] | date = July 10, 2006 | accessdate = February 1, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228073804/http://www.unionleader.com/article.aspx?headline=Indian-American+activist+defends+Sen.+Biden&articleId=0108a2f4-0530-4860-b010-5b076007bff6 |archive-date=February 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nIn an unusual move, Biden shared campaign planes with one of his rivals for the nomination, Senator [[Chris Dodd]] of [[Connecticut]]. Dodd and Biden were friends and seeking to save funds during somewhat long-shot efforts at the nomination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/16/us/politics/biden-obama-history.html|title=Obama and Biden's Relationship Looks Rosy. It Wasn't Always That Simple.|last=Thrush|first=Glenn|date=August 16, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOverall, Biden had difficulty raising funds, struggled to draw people to his [[Demonstration (political)|rallies]], and failed to gain traction against the high-profile candidacies of Obama and Senator [[Hillary Clinton]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/conventions/co_20080825_3122.php |title=Conventions 2008: Sen. Joseph Biden (D) |work=[[National Journal]] |date=August 25, 2008 |accessdate=September 16, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906210353/http://www.nationaljournal.com/conventions/co_20080825_3122.php |archivedate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> he never rose above single digits in [[Nationwide opinion polling for the Democratic Party 2008 presidential candidates|national polls of the Democratic candidates]]. In the first contest on January 3, 2008, Biden placed fifth in the [[Iowa Democratic caucuses, 2008|Iowa caucuses]], garnering slightly less than one percent of the state delegates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.iowacaucusresults.com/ | title=Iowa Democratic Party Caucus Results | publisher=[[Iowa Democratic Party]] | accessdate=August 29, 2008}}</ref> He withdrew from the race that evening, saying, \"There is nothing sad about tonight.{{nbsp}}... I feel no regret.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/04/AR2008010400260.html |title=Biden, Dodd Withdraw From Race |last=Murray |first=Shailagh |work=The Washington Post |date=January 4, 2008 |accessdate=August 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDespite its lack of success, Biden's stature in the political world rose as the result of his 2008 campaign.<ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|336}} In particular, it changed the relationship between Biden and Obama. Although the two had served together on the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], they had not been close, with Biden resenting Obama's quick rise to political stardom<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/><ref name=\"wolffe-218\">Wolffe, ''Renegade'', p. 218.</ref> and Obama viewing Biden as garrulous and patronizing.<ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|28, 337\u2013338}} Having gotten to know each other during 2007, Obama appreciated Biden's campaigning style and appeal to working-class voters, and Biden said he became convinced Obama was \"the real deal\".<ref name=\"wolffe-218\"/><ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|28, 337\u2013338}}\n\n== 2008 vice-presidential campaign ==\n\n{{Main|Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|2008 Democratic Party vice presidential candidate selection}}\n[[File:Biden Obama 3b.jpg|thumb|right|Biden speaks at the August 23, 2008, vice presidential announcement in [[Springfield, Illinois]]]]\n\nShortly following Biden's withdrawal from the presidential race, Obama privately told him he was interested in finding an important place for Biden in his administration.<ref name=\"ny-lizza\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/10/20/bidens-brief |title=Biden's Brief |last=Lizza |first=Ryan |work=The New Yorker |date=October 20, 2008 |accessdate=November 24, 2008 |authorlink=Ryan Lizza}}</ref> Biden declined Obama's first request to vet him for the vice-presidential slot, fearing the vice presidency would represent a loss in status and voice from his Senate position, but later changed his mind.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/><ref name=\"pol091609\"/> In a June 22, 2008, interview on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'', Biden confirmed that, although he was not actively seeking a spot on the ticket, he would accept the offer if it came.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/06/23/biden-id-say-yes-to-being-vp/ |first=Alexander |last=Mooney |title=Biden: I'd say yes to being VP |work=CNN |accessdate=August 23, 2008 |date=June 23, 2008}}</ref> In early August, Obama and Biden met in secret to discuss the possibility,<ref name=\"ny-lizza\"/> and developed a strong personal [[rapport]].<ref name=\"wolffe-218\"/> On August 22, 2008, Obama announced that Biden would be his [[running mate]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Obama's veep message to supporters |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/23/AR2008082300455.html |first=Jose Antonio |last=Vargas |work=The Washington Post |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 23, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the strategy behind the choice reflected a desire to fill out the ticket with someone with [[foreign policy]] and [[national security]] experience\u2014and not to help the ticket win a [[swing state]] or to emphasize Obama's \"change\" message.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Nagourney |authorlink=Adam Nagourney |author2=Jeff Zeleny |title=Obama Chooses Biden as Running Mate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/us/politics/24biden.html |work=The New York Times |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 23, 2008 }}</ref> Others pointed out Biden's appeal to middle-class and [[blue-collar]] voters, as well as his willingness to aggressively challenge Republican nominee [[John McCain]] in a way that Obama seemed uncomfortable doing at times.<ref>{{cite news|first=E.J. |last=Dionne |title=Tramps Like Us: How Joe Biden will reassure working class voters and change the tenor of this week's convention |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/62212/tramps-us |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=August 25, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828210626/http://tnr.com/politics/story.html?id=2ecbd0b9-c2c4-44d7-824a-603b4a418c74 |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref><ref>Wolffe, ''Renegade'', p. 217.</ref> In accepting Obama's offer, Biden ruled out running for president again in 2016,<ref name=\"ny-lizza\"/> but his comments in later years seemed to back off that stance, as he did not want to diminish his political power by appearing uninterested in advancement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/06/vp-biden-keeping-the-door-open-for-2016-.html|title= VP Biden Keeping the Door Open for 2016? |last=Travers |first=Karen |date= June 25, 2009|work= [[Political Punch]]|publisher= [[ABC News]]|accessdate= October 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101017172435/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/06/vp-biden-keeping-the-door-open-for-2016-.html|archivedate= October 17, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2011/10/21/biden-in-2016/ |title=Biden in 2016? |work=CNN |date=October 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt050812\"/> Biden was officially nominated for vice president on August 27 by voice vote at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newsblaze.com/usnews/politics/democrats-formally-nominate-barack-obama-for-u-s-presidency_60148/ |title=Democrats Formally Nominate Barack Obama for U.S. Presidency |first=Alan |last=Gray |publisher=NewsBlaze|date=August 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter his selection as the vice-presidential candidate, Biden's [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Wilmington]] confirmed that even if elected vice president, he would not be allowed to speak at Catholic schools.<ref name=\"ce082808\">{{cite news |url=https://catholicexchange.com/bidens-bishop-will-not-permit-him-even-if-elected-vp-to-speak-at-catholic-schools |title=Biden's Bishop Will not Permit Him, Even if Elected VP, to Speak at Catholic Schools |last=Westen |first=John-Henry |publisher=[[Catholic Exchange]] |date=August 28, 2008 |accessdate=October 2, 2008}}</ref> The bishop of his original hometown of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Scranton|Scranton, Pennsylvania]], soon barred Biden from receiving [[Holy Communion]] because of his support for abortion rights,<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Kirkpatrick |title=Abortion Issue Again Dividing Catholic Votes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/17/us/politics/17catholics.html |work=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2008 |accessdate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref> but Biden continued to receive Communion at his local Delaware parish.<ref name=\"ce082808\"/> Scranton became a flashpoint in the competition for swing-state Catholic voters between the Democratic campaign and liberal Catholic groups, who stressed that other social issues should be considered as much as or more than abortion, and many bishops and conservative Catholics, who maintained abortion was paramount.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/05/us/politics/05catholic.html |title=A Fight Among Catholics Over Which Party Best Reflects Church Teachings |last=Kirkpatrick |first=David D. |work=The New York Times |date=October 4, 2008 |accessdate=October 5, 2008}}</ref> Biden said he believed life begins at conception but would not impose his religious views on others.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kate |last=Phillips |title=As a Matter of Faith, Biden Says Life Begins at Conception |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/08/us/politics/08campaign.html |work=The New York Times |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=August 7, 2008 }}</ref> Bishop Saltarelli had previously said of stances like Biden's, \"No one today would accept this statement from any public servant: 'I am personally opposed to human slavery and racism but will not impose my personal conviction in the legislative arena.' Likewise, none of us should accept this statement from any public servant: 'I am personally opposed to abortion but will not impose my personal conviction in the legislative arena.'\"<ref name=\"ce082808\"/>\n[[File:Joe Biden nomination DNC 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Biden was nominated as the Democratic vice presidential candidate during the third night of the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]].]]\n\nBiden's vice-presidential campaigning gained little media visibility, as far greater press attention was focused on the Republican running mate, [[List of Governors of Alaska|Alaska Governor]] [[Sarah Palin]].<ref name=\"nyt-no2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/20/us/politics/20biden.html |title=Meanwhile, the Other No. 2 Keeps On Punching |last=Leibovich |first=Mark |work=The New York Times |date=September 19, 2008 |accessdate=September 20, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2008/09/joe-who.html |title=Joe Who? |last=Tapper |first=Jake |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=September 14, 2008 |accessdate=September 15, 2008 |authorlink=Jake Tapper |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915055913/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2008/09/joe-who.html |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}</ref> During one week in September 2008, for instance, the [[Pew Research Center]]'s [[Project for Excellence in Journalism]] found that Biden was included in only five percent of coverage of the race, far less than the other three candidates on the tickets received.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.journalism.org/2008/09/15/pej-campaign-coverage-index-september-8-14-2008/ |title=Northern Exposure Still Dominates the News |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |last=Jurkowitz |first=Mark |date=September 14, 2008 |accessdate=November 24, 2008}}</ref> Biden nevertheless focused on campaigning in economically challenged areas of [[swing state]]s and trying to win over blue-collar Democrats, especially those who had supported [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/><ref name=\"nyt-no2\"/> Biden attacked McCain heavily despite a long-standing personal friendship;{{refn|group=nb| Biden admired McCain politically as well as personally; in May 2004, he had urged McCain to run as vice president with presumptive Democratic presidential nominee [[John Kerry]], saying the cross-party ticket would help heal the \"vicious rift\" in U.S. politics.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/4961694 |title=McCain Urged to Join Kerry Ticket |agency=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=May 16, 2004}}</ref>}} he said, \"That guy I used to know, he's gone. It literally saddens me.\"<ref name=\"nyt-no2\"/> As the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]] reached a peak with the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010|liquidity crisis of September 2008]] and the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008|proposed bailout of the United States financial system]] became a major factor in the campaign, Biden voted in favor of the $700 billion [[HR1424|Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]], which went on to pass in the Senate 74\u201325.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ny1.com/content/features/86538/senate-passes-economic-rescue-package/Default.aspx |title=Senate Passes Economic Rescue Package |publisher=[[NY1]] |date=October 1, 2008 |accessdate=October 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005022401/http://www.ny1.com/content/features/86538/senate-passes-economic-rescue-package/Default.aspx |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2008, Biden participated in the [[United States vice-presidential debate, 2008|vice-presidential debate]] with Palin at [[Washington University in St. Louis]]. Post-debate polls found that while Palin exceeded many voters' expectations, Biden had won the debate overall.<ref name=\"witcover\"/>{{rp|655\u2013661}} On October 5, Biden suspended campaign events for a few days after the death of his mother-in-law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/10/05/bidens-mother-in-law-dies/ |title=Biden's mother-in-law dies |last=Marquardt |first=Alexander |work=CNN |date=October 5, 2008}}</ref> During the campaign's final days, he focused on less populated, older, less well-off areas of battleground states, especially Florida, Ohio, and Pennsylvania, where polling indicated he was popular and where Obama had not campaigned or performed well in the Democratic primaries.<ref name=\"nyt103008\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/31/us/politics/31biden.html |title=Hitting the Backroads, and Having Less to Say |last=Broder |first=John M. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 30, 2008 |accessdate=October 31, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"time102908\"/><ref name=\"pol110308\">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2008/11/where-have-you-gone-joe-biden-015205 |title=Where have you gone, Joe Biden? |last=McGrane |first=Victoria |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=November 3, 2008 |accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> He also campaigned in some normally Republican states, as well as in areas with large Catholic populations.<ref name=\"pol110308\"/>\n\nUnder instructions from the Obama campaign, Biden kept his speeches succinct and tried to avoid offhand remarks, such as one about Obama's being tested by a foreign power soon after taking office, which had attracted negative attention.<ref name=\"nyt103008\"/><ref name=\"time102908\">{{cite news |url=https://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1855355,00.html |title=Hidin' Biden: Reining In a Voluble No. 2 |last=Tumulty |first=Karen |magazine=Time |date=October 29, 2008 |accessdate=November 1, 2008}}</ref> Privately, Biden's remarks frustrated Obama. \"How many times is Biden gonna say something stupid?\" he asked.<ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|411\u2013414, 419}} Obama campaign staffers referred to Biden blunders as \"Joe bombs\" and kept Biden uninformed about strategy discussions, which in turn irked Biden.<ref name=\"nyt050812\"/> Relations between the two campaigns became strained for a month, until Biden apologized on a call to Obama and the two built a stronger partnership.<ref name=\"gamechange\"/>{{rp|411\u2013414}} Publicly, Obama strategist [[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]] said Biden's high popularity ratings had outweighed any unexpected comments.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden reliable running mate despite gaffes |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/144631311/ |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Asbury Park Press]] |date=October 26, 2008}}</ref> Nationally, Biden had a 60% favorability rating in a [[Pew Research Center]] poll, compared to Palin's 44%.<ref name=\"nyt103008\"/>\n\nOn November 4, 2008, Obama was elected president and Biden was elected vice president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/11/04/election.president/index.html |title=Barack Obama wins presidential election |work=CNN |accessdate=November 5, 2008|date=November 4, 2008}}</ref> The Obama\u2013Biden ticket won 365 [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral votes]] to McCain\u2013Palin's 173,<ref>{{cite news |last=Franke-Ruta |first=Garance |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/11/19/mccain_takes_missouri.html |title=McCain Takes Missouri |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=November 19, 2008 |accessdate=November 19, 2008}}</ref> and won 53% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/president/ |title=President\u2014Election Center 2008 |work=CNN |accessdate=November 19, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBiden had continued to run for his Senate seat as well as for vice president,<ref name=\"ap082408\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/wires/2008Aug24/0,4670,CVNBidenTwoCampaigns,00.html |title=Biden Wages 2 Campaigns At Once |agency=Associated Press |date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=August 29, 2008 |first=Randall |last=Chase |publisher=Fox News}}</ref> as permitted by Delaware law.<ref name=\"aap08-366\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 366.</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Biden was the fourth person to run for Vice President and reelection to the Senate simultaneously after [[Lyndon Johnson]], [[Lloyd Bentsen]], and [[Joe Lieberman]], and the second to have won both elections after Johnson.}} On November{{nbsp}}4 he was also [[United States Senate election in Delaware, 2008|reelected]] to the Senate, defeating Republican [[Christine O'Donnell]].<ref name=\"ap110408\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-11-04-420465768_x.htm |title=Biden wins 7th Senate term but may not serve |last=Nuckols |first=Ben |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=USA Today |date=November 4, 2008 |accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> Having won both races, Biden made a point of holding off his resignation from the Senate so he could be sworn in for his seventh term on January 6, 2009.<ref name=\"dnj010709\">{{cite news|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2009901070333 |title=A bittersweet oath for Biden |last=Gaudiano |first=Nicole |work=[[The News Journal]] |date=January 7, 2009 |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212100305/http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2009901070333 |archivedate=February 12, 2009 }}</ref> He became the youngest senator ever to start a seventh full term, and said, \"In all my life, the greatest honor bestowed upon me has been serving the people of Delaware as their United States senator.\"<ref name=\"dnj010709\"/> Biden cast his last Senate vote on January 15, supporting the release of the second $350 billion for the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Trish |last=Turner |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/senate-releases-350-billion-in-bailout-funds-to-obama |title=Senate Releases $350 Billion in Bailout Funds to Obama |work=Fox News |date=January 15, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2009 }}</ref> Biden [[resignation from the United States Senate|resigned from the Senate]] later that day;{{refn|group=nb| Delaware's Democratic governor, [[Ruth Ann Minner]], announced on November 24, 2008, that she would appoint Biden's longtime senior adviser [[Ted Kaufman]] to succeed Biden in the Senate.<ref name=\"bloom112408\"/> Kaufman said he would serve only two years, until [[United States Senate special election in Delaware, 2010|Delaware's special Senate election in 2010]].<ref name=\"bloom112408\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=apZPaTS_UmpM |title=Kaufman Picked by Governor to Fill Biden Senate Seat (Update 3) |last=Milford |first=Phil |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=November 24, 2008 |accessdate=November 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081116003829/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087 |archivedate=November 16, 2008 }}</ref> Biden's son [[Beau Biden|Beau]] ruled himself out of the 2008 selection process due to his impending tour in Iraq with the [[Delaware Army National Guard]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/scorecard/1108/Minner_appoints_Ted_Kaufman_to_Biden_seat.html |title=Ted Kaufman to succeed Biden in Senate |last=Kraushaar |first=Josh |publisher=[[Politico]] |date=November 24, 2008 |accessdate=November 24, 2008}}</ref> He was a possible candidate for the 2010 special election, but in early 2010 said he would not run for the seat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/25/bidens-son-will-not-run-for-delaware-senate-seat/ |title=Biden's Son Will Not Run for Delaware's Open Senate Seat |last=Hulse |first=Carl |newspaper=The New York Times |date=January 25, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> }} in emotional farewell remarks on the Senate floor, where he had spent most of his adult life, Biden said, \"Every good thing I have seen happen here, every bold step taken in the 36-plus years I have been here, came not from the application of pressure by interest groups, but through the maturation of personal relationships.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/15/biden-and-clinton-say-goodbye-to-senate |title=Biden and Clinton Say Goodbye to Senate |last=Becker |first=Bernie |newspaper=The New York Times |date=January 15, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDelaware Governor [[Ruth Ann Minner]] appointed longtime Biden adviser [[Ted Kaufman]] to complete his term. Kaufman chose not to run for a full term, allowing Democrat [[Chris Coons]] to succeed him after a special election in 2010.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Vice presidency (2009\u20132017) ==\n=== Post-election transition ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden and Dick Cheney at VP residence.jpg|thumb|right|Vice President-elect Biden meets with Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] at [[Number One Observatory Circle]] on November 13, 2008]]\n<!--For convenience, includes material between election and inauguration, although not strictly part of first term-->\n\nOn November 4, 2008, Biden [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama|was elected]] Vice President of the United States as Obama's running mate.\n\nSoon after the election, he was appointed chairman of president-elect Obama's transition team. During the transition phase of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]], Biden said he was in daily meetings with Obama and that McCain was still his friend.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/11/06/biden-talks-transition-says-mccains-still-my-friend/ | title=Biden talks transition, says McCain's 'still my friend' |last=Marquardt |first=Alexander |work=CNN | date=November 6, 2008 | accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref> The [[U.S. Secret Service]] gave Biden the code name \"Celtic\", referring to his Irish roots.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/us_elections_2008/7726453.stm | title='Secret' Obama code name revealed |work=BBC News | date=November 13, 2008 | accessdate=November 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBiden chose veteran Democratic lawyer and aide [[Ron Klain]] as his chief of staff,<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden picks former Gore aide as chief of staff |agency=Reuters |date=November 13, 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE4AC5EA20081113| accessdate =November 13, 2008 | first=Steve | last=Holland}}</ref> and ''Time'' Washington bureau chief [[Jay Carney]] as his director of communications.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/1208/Report_Carney_joins_Biden_team.html |title=Report: Carney joins Biden team |last=Calderone |first=Michael |work=[[Politico]] | date=December 15, 2008 | accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref> He intended to eliminate some of the explicit roles assumed by his predecessor, [[Dick Cheney]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2008/12/biden-to-shrink-vp-role-big-time-016558 |title=Biden to shrink VP role\u2014big time |last=Lee |first=Carol E. |work=[[Politico]] | date=December 14, 2008 | accessdate=December 23, 2008}}</ref> who had established himself as an autonomous power center.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/> Otherwise, Biden said he would not emulate any previous vice presidency, but would instead seek to provide advice and counsel on every critical decision Obama would make.<ref name=\"lkl122208\">{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/22/biden.lkl/index.html |title= Biden says he'll be different vice president |work=CNN | date=December 22, 2008 | accessdate=December 22, 2008}}</ref> He said he was closely involved in all the cabinet appointments made during the transition.<ref name=\"lkl122208\"/> Biden was also named to head the new White House Task Force on Working Families, an initiative to improve the middle class's economic well-being.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/21/transition.wrap/index.html |title=What Obama promised Biden |last=Hornick |first=Ed |last2=Levs |first2=Josh |work=CNN | date=December 21, 2008 | accessdate=December 23, 2008}}</ref> In his last act as Chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, Biden went on a trip to [[Iraq]], Afghanistan and [[Pakistan]] during the second week of January 2009, meeting with the leadership of those countries.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/01/senator-bidens-trip-raises-concerns-017136 | title='Senator' Biden's trip raises concerns |last=Lee |first=Carol E. |work=[[Politico]] |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=January 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== First term (2009\u20132013) ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden sworn in 1-20-09 hires 090120-N-0696M-204a.jpg|thumb|right|Biden was sworn into office by [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice]] [[John Paul Stevens]] on January 20, 2009]]\n\nAt noon on January 20, 2009, Biden became the 47th [[vice president of the United States]], sworn into the office by Supreme Court Justice [[John Paul Stevens]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.oregonlive.com/politics/2009/01/in_culminating_moment_biden_is.html |title=In culminating moment, Biden is vice president |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[OregonLive.com]] |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=July 27, 2016 }}</ref> He is the first U.S. vice president from Delaware<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/11/03/election.trivia/index.html |title=Think you know your election trivia? |work=CNN |date=November 3, 2008 |accessdate=November 9, 2008}}</ref> and the first [[Roman Catholic]] to attain that office.<ref name=\"npr2008\">{{cite news |title=The First Catholic Vice President? |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/politicaljunkie/2009/01/the_first_catholic_vice_presid.html |accessdate=September 25, 2019 |agency=[[NPR]] |date=January 9, 2009 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20081106/NEWS02/811060379 |title=VP's home awaits if Biden chooses |last=Gaudiano |first=Nicole |work=[[The News Journal]] |date=November 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081109060406/http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20081106/NEWS02/811060379 |archivedate=November 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n[[File:Barack Obama Walking With Joe Biden.jpg|thumb|right|President Obama with Vice President Biden at the [[White House]], February 2009]]\n\nIn the early months of the Obama administration, Biden assumed the role of a behind-the-scenes counselor,<ref name=\"nyt032809\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/us/politics/29biden.html | title=Speaking Freely, Biden Finds Influential Role | author=Leibovich, Mark | work=The New York Times | date=March 28, 2009 | accessdate=March 31, 2009}}</ref> often adjudicating disputes among Obama's \"team of rivals\".<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/> Obama compared Biden's efforts to a basketball player \"who does a bunch of things that don't show up in the stat sheet\".<ref name=\"nyt032809\"/> Biden played a key role in gaining Senate support for several major pieces of legislation, and was a main factor in convincing Senator [[Arlen Specter]] to switch from a Republican to a Democrat.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Carol|title=Biden worked on Specter '100 days'|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/04/biden-worked-on-specter-100-days-021824 |accessdate=June 23, 2012|date=April 29, 2009}}</ref> Biden lost an internal debate to Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] regarding his opposition to sending 21,000 new troops to the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20090611/1aclinton11_cv.art.htm | title=In a supporting role, Clinton takes a low-key approach at State Dept. |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |work=USA Today | date=June 11, 2009 | accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/06/clinton-toils-in-the-shadows-024067 |title=Hillary Clinton toils in the shadows |last=Smith |first=Ben |work=[[Politico]] | date=June 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref> but his skepticism was still considered valuable in the administration,<ref name=\"pol091609\"/> and in 2009 Biden's views gained more influence as Obama reconsidered his Afghanistan strategy.<ref name=\"nw-cov-101009\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/joe-biden-white-house-truth-teller-81181 |title=An Inconvenient Truth Teller|author=Bailey, Holly|date=October 10, 2009|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|accessdate=November 6, 2009|author2=Thomas, Evan|authorlink2=Evan Thomas}}</ref>\n\nBiden visited Iraq about every two months,<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/> becoming the administration's point man in delivering messages to Iraqi leadership about expected progress in the country.<ref name=\"pol091609\"/> More generally, overseeing Iraq policy became Biden's responsibility: Obama was said to have said, \"Joe, you do Iraq.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/breaking-maliki-biden |title=Breaking Up: Maliki and Biden |last=Osnos |first=Evan |work=The New Yorker |date=August 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Biden said Iraq \"could be one of the great achievements of this administration\".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2010/02/vice-president-biden-iraq-could-be-one-of-the-great-achievements-of-this-administration/ |title=Vice President Biden: Iraq \"Could Be One of the Great Achievements of This Administration\" |work=[[ABC News]] | date= February 11, 2010}}</ref> His January 2010 visit to Iraq in the midst of turmoil over banned candidates from the [[Iraqi parliamentary election, 2010|upcoming Iraqi parliamentary election]] resulted in 59 of the several hundred candidates being reinstated by the Iraqi government two days later.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iJGz55dJrnOzzejqmBj6QTolyydg |title=Iraq reinstates 59 election candidates | agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=January 25, 2010}}</ref> By 2012, Biden had made eight trips there, but his oversight of U.S. policy in Iraq receded with the exit of U.S. troops in 2011.<ref name=\"time-mo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/11/president-obama-war-iraq-112730 |title=The war over President Obama's new war in Iraq |last=Crowley |first=Michael |work=[[Politico]] |date=November 9, 2014 |accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBiden was also in charge of the oversight role for [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009#Infrastructure Investment|infrastructure spending from the Obama stimulus package]] intended to help counteract the [[late-2000s recession|ongoing recession]], and stressed that only worthy projects should get funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1908417,00.html |title=What Happened to the Stimulus? |last=Scherer |first=Michael |work=Time |date=July 1, 2009 |accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> He talked with hundreds of governors, mayors, and other local officials in this role.<ref name=\"time-mo\"/> During this period, Biden was satisfied that no major instances of waste or corruption had occurred,<ref name=\"pol091609\"/> and when he completed that role in February 2011, he said the number of fraud incidents with stimulus monies had been less than one percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2011/02/sheriff-joe-biden-touts-recovery-act-success-and-hands-over-his-badge.html |title='Sheriff Joe' Biden Touts Recovery Act Success\u2014and Hands Over His Badge |last=Travers |first=Karen |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=February 17, 2011 |accessdate=March 19, 2011 | url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221153327/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2011/02/sheriff-joe-biden-touts-recovery-act-success-and-hands-over-his-badge.html |archivedate=February 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n[[File:US Navy 090514-N-4451V-548 Vice President Joe Biden meets with Basic Underwater Demolition-SEAL (BUDS) students at Naval Amphibious Base Coronado.jpg|thumb|Biden speaks to [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] trainees at [[Naval Amphibious Base Coronado|NAB Coronado]], [[California]], May 2009]]\n[[File:President Barack Obama and Vice President Joe Biden shake hands in the Oval Office following a phone call with House Speaker John Boehner securing a bipartisan deal to reduce the nation's deficit and avoid default.jpg|thumb|right|President Obama congratulates Biden for his role in shaping the [[United States debt ceiling|debt ceiling]] deal that led to the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]]]]\n[[File:Obama and Biden await updates on bin Laden.jpg|thumb|right|Biden, Obama and the national security team gathered in the [[White House Situation Room]] to monitor the progress of the May 2011 [[Death of Osama bin Laden|mission to kill Osama bin Laden]].]]\n\nIt took some time for the cautious Obama and the blunt, rambling Biden to work out ways of dealing with each other.<ref name=\"nyt050812\"/> In late April 2009, Biden's off-message response to a question during the beginning of the [[2009 flu pandemic|swine flu outbreak]], that he would advise family members against traveling on airplanes or subways, led to a swift retraction by the White House.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-may-01-na-biden1-story.html |title=White House adjusts Biden's swine flu advice |last=Silva |first=Mark |last2==Parsons |first2=Christi |work=Los Angeles Times | date=May 1, 2009 |accessdate=May 28, 2009}}</ref> The remark revived Biden's [[Political gaffe|reputation for gaffes]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/health/articles/2009/05/01/white_house_tempers_bidens_swine_flu_advice/ |title=White House tempers Biden's swine flu advice |work=Boston Globe |date=May 1, 2009 |accessdate=May 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505114058/http://www.boston.com/news/health/articles/2009/05/01/white_house_tempers_bidens_swine_flu_advice/ |archivedate=May 5, 2009 }}</ref> and led to a spate of late-night television jokes based on his being a loose-talking buffoon.<ref name=\"nw-cov-101009\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.liveabout.com/late-night-political-jokes-2733896 |title=The Week's Best Late-Night Jokes |last=Kurtzman |first=Daniel |publisher=[[About.com]] |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=May 28, 2009}}</ref> In the face of persistently rising unemployment through July 2009, Biden acknowledged that the administration had \"misread how bad the economy was\" but maintained confidence the stimulus package would create many more jobs once the pace of expenditures picked up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31745563 |title=Biden: 'We misread how bad the economy was' |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=July 5, 2009 |accessdate=July 9, 2009}}</ref> The same month, Secretary of State Clinton quickly disavowed Biden's remarks disparaging Russia as a power, but despite any missteps, Biden still retained Obama's confidence and was increasingly influential within the administration.<ref name=\"lat081909\">{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-aug-18-na-biden18-story.html |title=Despite fumbles, Biden's a player |last=Nicholas |first=Peter |last2=Richter |first2=Paul |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 19, 2009 |accessdate=August 22, 2009 }}</ref> On March 23, 2010, a microphone picked up Biden telling the president that his signing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] was \"a big fucking deal\" during live national news telecasts. White House press secretary [[Robert Gibbs]] replied via Twitter \"And yes Mr. Vice President, you're right{{nbsp}}...\"<ref name=\"bigdeal\">{{cite news | url=https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/23/at-white-house-bidens-expletive-caught-on-open-mic/ |title=At White House, Biden's Expletive Caught on Open Mic | author=Herszenhorn, David M. | magazine=[[The New York Times]] | date=March 23, 2010 | accessdate=March 23, 2010}}</ref> Despite their different personalities, Obama and Biden formed a friendship, partly based around Obama's daughter Sasha and Biden's granddaughter Maisy, who attended [[Sidwell Friends School]] together.<ref name=\"nyt050812\"/>\n\nBiden's most important role in the administration was as a contrarian who questioned assumptions.<ref name=\"nytm-traub\"/><ref name=\"nw-cov-101009\"/> Obama said, \"The best thing about Joe is that when we get everybody together, he really forces people to think and defend their positions, to look at things from every angle, and that is very valuable for me.\"<ref name=\"pol091609\">{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/09/the-skunk-at-the-family-picnic-027211 | title=Joe Biden, 'the skunk at the family picnic' | author=Cummings, Jeanne | publisher=[[The Politico]] | date=September 16, 2009 | accessdate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Another senior Obama advisor said Biden \"is always prepared to be the skunk at the family picnic to make sure we are as intellectually honest as possible.\"<ref name=\"pol091609\"/> On June 11, 2010, Biden represented the United States at the opening ceremony of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], attended the [[England v United States (2010)|England v. U.S. game]], and visited Egypt, Kenya, and South Africa.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/06/12/south.africa.biden/index.html |title=Biden visits South Africa as World Cup begins |work=CNN |accessdate=June 13, 2010 |date=June 12, 2010}}</ref> The Bidens maintained a relaxed atmosphere at their official residence in Washington, often entertaining some of their grandchildren, and regularly returned to their home in Delaware.<ref name=\"pol-regular\">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2011/06/the-bidens-regular-lives-057887 |title=Joe and Jill Biden's 'regular' lives |last=Parnes |first=Amie |newspaper=[[Politico]] | date=June 28, 2011 | accessdate=June 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBiden campaigned heavily for Democrats in the [[United States elections, 2010|2010 midterm elections]], maintaining an attitude of optimism in the face of predictions of large-scale losses for the party.<ref name=\"nyt101310\"/> Following big Republican gains in the elections and the departure of White House chief of staff [[Rahm Emanuel]], Biden's past relationships with Republicans in Congress became more important.<ref name=\"pol120910\">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2010/12/biden-steps-into-rahms-shoes-046173 |title=Joe Biden expands role as White House link to Congress |last=Lee |first=Carol E. |last2==Bresnahan |first2=John |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=December 9, 2010 | accessdate=December 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt121110\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/12/us/politics/12biden.html | title=As the Ground Shifts, Biden Plays a Bigger Role | author=Cooper, Helene | newspaper=The New York Times | date=December 11, 2010 | accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> He led the successful administration effort to gain Senate approval for the [[New START treaty]].<ref name=\"pol120910\"/><ref name=\"nyt121110\"/> In December 2010, Biden's advocacy for a middle ground, followed by his negotiations with Senate minority leader [[Mitch McConnell]], were instrumental in producing the administration's compromise tax package that revolved around a temporary [[extension of the Bush tax cuts]].<ref name=\"nyt121110\"/><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/08/us/politics/08deal.html | title=Biden and G.O.P. Leader Helped Hammer Out Bipartisan Tax Accord | author=Hulse, Carl | author2=Calmes, Jackie | newspaper=The New York Times | date=December 7, 2010 | accessdate=December 8, 2010}}</ref> Biden then took the lead in trying to sell the agreement to a reluctant Democratic caucus in Congress.<ref name=\"nyt121110\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/08/us/politics/08cong.html | title=Democrats Skeptical of Obama on New Tax Plan |author=Herszenhorn, David M. | author2=Stolberg, Sheryl Gay |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 7, 2010 |accessdate=December 8, 2010}}</ref> The package passed as the [[Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010]].\n\nIn foreign policy, Biden supported the NATO-led [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-xpm-2011-oct-20-la-pn-santorum-kadafi-20111020-story.html |title=Kadafi death: Joe Biden says 'NATO got it right' in Libya |first=Michael A. |last=Memoli |date=October 20, 2011 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> He has supported closer economic ties with [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden backs Russia WTO bid, praises Medvedev |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-usa-biden-idUSTRE72826320110309 |agency=Reuters |date=March 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, Obama delegated Biden to lead negotiations between Congress and the White House in resolving federal spending levels for the rest of the year, and avoiding a government shutdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/41870549 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729195403/http://www.cnbc.com/id/41870549 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |title=Obama Welcomes Budget Deal; Biden to Lead Talks |agency=Reuters |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=March 2, 2011 |accessdate=March 9, 2011 }}</ref> By May 2011, a \"Biden panel\" with six congressional members was trying to reach a bipartisan deal on raising the [[United States public debt|U.S. debt ceiling]] as part of an overall [[Government budget deficit|deficit reduction]] plan.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/16/us-usa-debt-talks-idUSTRE74F26V20110516 | title=Q+A: Debt and deficit talks in early stages |last=Reid |first=Tim |agency=[[Reuters]] | date=May 16, 2011 | accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110505/NEWS02/105050326/Biden-tasked-achieving-consensus-cutting-deficit?odyssey=tab%7Ctopnews%7Ctext%7CHome |title=Biden tasked with achieving consensus on cutting deficit |last=Gaudiano |first=Nicole |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |date=May 4, 2011 |accessdate=May 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2011|U.S. debt ceiling crisis]] developed over the next couple months, but it was again Biden's relationship with McConnell that proved a key factor in breaking a deadlock and finally bringing about a deal to resolve it, in the form of the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]], signed on August 2, 2011, the same day an unprecedented [[Sovereign default|U.S. default]] had loomed.<ref name=\"pol-bca\">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2011/08/biden-mcconnell-and-the-making-of-a-deal-060463 |title=Joe Biden, Mitch McConnell and the making of a debt deal |last=Thrush |first=Glenn |last2=Brown |first2=Carrie Budoff |last3=Raju |first3=Manu |last4=Bresnahan |first4=John |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=August 2, 2011 | accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-bca\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/the-real-drama-was-in-private-as-debt-deal-hatched |title=The real drama was in private as debt deal hatched |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[Fox News]] |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/03/us-usa-debt-brink-idUSTRE77271R20110803?feedType=RSS&feedName=topNews | title=Special report: How Washington took the U.S. to the brink | agency=[[Reuters]] | author=Bohan, Caren Bohan | author2=Sullivan, Andy | author3= Ferraro, Thomas | date=August 3, 2011 | accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref> Biden had spent the most time bargaining with Congress on the debt question of anyone in the administration,<ref name=\"ap-bca\"/> and one Republican staffer said, \"Biden's the only guy with real negotiating authority, and [McConnell] knows that his word is good. He was a key to the deal.\"<ref name=\"pol-bca\"/>\n\nSome reports suggest that Biden opposed to going forward with the May 2011 [[Death of Osama bin Laden|U.S. mission to kill Osama bin Laden]],<ref name=\"time-mo\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2014/01/robert-gates-duty-hillary-told-the-president-that-her-opposition-to-the-surge-in-iraq-had-been-political.html |title=Hillary Told the President That Her Opposition to the Surge in Iraq Had Been Political |last=Weigel |first=David |authorlink=David Weigel |date=January 10, 2014|work=Slate}}</ref> lest failure adversely affect Obama's chances for a second term.<ref>{{cite news |first=Marc A. |last=Thiessen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/marc-thiessen-bidens-bin-laden-hypocrisy/2012/10/08/990aca7c-114d-11e2-be82-c3411b7680a9_story.html |title=Biden's Bin Laden Hypocrisy |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 8, 2012 |accessdate=August 29, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/390144-hillary-clintons-ass-covering-on-bin-laden-raid-rattled-biden |title=Hillary Clinton's 'ass-covering' on bin Laden raid 'rattled' Biden |last=Perks |first=Ashley |date=June 1, 2018 |website=TheHill |access-date=April 29, 2019}}</ref> He took the lead in notifying Congressional leaders of the successful outcome.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110501/NEWS/110509984 |title=Osama Bin Laden dead; President Obama addresses nation | agency=[[NewsCore]] | newspaper=[[Times Herald-Record]] | date=May 2, 2011 | accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 reelection campaign ===\n\n{{main|Barack Obama 2012 presidential campaign}}\n\nIn October 2010, Biden said Obama had asked him to remain as his running mate for the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref name=\"nyt101310\">{{cite news |title= Vice President Tries to Energize Democrats|author= Stolberg, Sheryl Gay |newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|date= October 12, 2010|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/13/us/politics/13biden.html|accessdate=October 14, 2010}}</ref> But with Obama's popularity on the decline, White House chief of staff [[William M. Daley]] conducted some secret polling and focus group research in late 2011 on the idea of replacing Biden on the ticket with Hillary Clinton.<ref name=\"nyt-dd-replace\"/> The notion was dropped when the results showed no appreciable improvement for Obama,<ref name=\"nyt-dd-replace\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/01/us/politics/book-details-consideration-of-replacing-biden-on-2012-ticket.html |title=Book Details Obama Aides' Talks About Replacing Biden on 2012 Ticket | author=Martin, Jonathan | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 31, 2013}}</ref> and White House officials later said Obama had never entertained the idea.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/politico44/2013/11/wh-obama-never-considered-dropping-joe-biden-176520 |title=W.H.: Obama never considered dropping Joe Biden |last=Allen |first=Jonathan |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=November 1, 2013 |access-date=November 3, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104143531/http://www.politico.com/politico44/2013/11/wh-obama-never-considered-dropping-biden-176520.html |archive-date=November 4, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBiden's May 2012 statement that he was \"absolutely comfortable\" with [[same-sex marriage]] gained considerable public attention in comparison to Obama's position, which had been described as \"evolving\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-xpm-2012-may-06-la-na-biden-gay-marriage-20120507-story.html |title= Biden 'comfortable' with equal rights for gays who wed |date=May 6, 2012 |first=Christi |last=Parsons |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref> Biden made his statement without administration consent, and Obama and his aides were quite irked, since Obama had planned to shift position several months later, in the build-up to the party convention, and since Biden had previously counseled the president to avoid the issue lest key Catholic voters be offended.<ref name=\"nyt050812\"/><ref name=\"ap051012\"/><ref name=\"pol-ebook\">{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2012/08/politico-e-book-obama-campaign-roiled-by-conflict-079867 | title=Politico e-book: Obama campaign roiled by conflict | author=Thrush, Glenn | newspaper=[[Politico]] | date=August 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2012/08/6-hidden-obama-campaign-fault-lines-080028 |title=6 hidden fault lines in President Obama's campaign |last=Thursh |first=Glenn |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=August 23, 2012 }}</ref> Gay rights advocates seized upon Biden's statement,<ref name=\"ap051012\"/> and within days, Obama announced that he too supported same-sex marriage, an action in part forced by Biden's unexpected remarks.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/10/us/politics/obama-says-same-sex-marriage-should-be-legal.html | title=Obama Says Same-Sex Marriage Should Be Legal | first=Jackie | last=Calmes | first2=Peter | last2=Baker | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 9, 2012 | accessdate=May 10, 2012}}</ref> Biden apologized to Obama in private for having spoken out,<ref name=\"pol-ebook\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/10/joe-biden-gay-marriage-apology_n_1507939.html |title=Joe Biden Reportedly Apologized To Obama Over Gay Marriage Comments |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=Huffington Post |date=May 10, 2012 |accessdate=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528233546/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/10/joe-biden-gay-marriage-apology_n_1507939.html |archive-date=May 28, 2013 }}</ref> while Obama acknowledged publicly it had been done from the heart.<ref name=\"ap051012\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/ap-source-biden-apologizes-to-obama-over-comments | title=AP source: Biden apologizes to Obama over comments | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[Fox News]] | date=May 10, 2012 | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref> The incident showed that Biden still struggled at times with [[message discipline]];<ref name=\"nyt050812\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/08/us/politics/for-a-blunt-biden-an-uneasy-supporting-role.html | title=For a Blunt Biden, an Uneasy Supporting Role | author=Leibovich, Mark | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 8, 2012 | page=1}}</ref> as ''Time'' wrote, \"everyone knows [that] Biden's greatest strength is also his greatest weakness.\"<ref name=\"time-mo\"/> Relations were also strained between the campaigns when Biden appeared to use his position to bolster fundraising contacts for a possible run for president in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]], and he ended up being excluded from Obama campaign strategy meetings.<ref name=\"nyt-dd-replace\"/>\n[[File:Official portrait of President Obama and Vice President Biden 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Biden with President [[Barack Obama]], July 2012]]\n\nThe Obama campaign nevertheless still valued Biden as a retail-level politician who could connect with disaffected, blue-collar workers and rural residents, and he had a heavy schedule of appearances in swing states as the [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|Obama reelection campaign]] began in earnest in spring 2012.<ref name=\"time-be-joe\"/><ref name=\"time-mo\">{{cite news | title=Mo Joe | author=Scherer, Michael | magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=June 11, 2012 | pages=26\u201330}}</ref> An August 2012 remark before a mixed-race audience that Republican proposals to relax Wall Street regulations would \"put y'all back in chains\" led to a similar analysis of Biden's face-to-face campaigning abilities versus his tendency to go off track.<ref name=\"time-be-joe\"/><ref name=\"lat-offt\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2012/08/mission-impossible-managing-biden-079776 |title=Mission Impossible: Managing Joe Biden |last=Martin |first=Jonathan |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote, \"Most candidates give the same stump speech over and over, putting reporters if not the audience to sleep. But during any Biden speech, there might be a dozen moments to make press handlers cringe, and prompt reporters to turn to each other with amusement and confusion.\"<ref name=\"lat-offt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2012-aug-17-la-na-biden-20120817-story.html |title=Biden's unscripted moments keep campaign on its toes |last=Memoli |first=Michael A. |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 17, 2012}}</ref> [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] wrote that Biden often went too far and that \"Along with the familiar Washington mix of neediness and overconfidence, Biden's brain is wired for more than the usual amount of goofiness.\"<ref name=\"time-be-joe\">{{cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2123322,00.html |title=Let There Be Joe |last=Von Drehle |first=David |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=September 10, 2012 |pages=41\u201343 |author-link=David Von Drehle }}</ref>\n\nBiden was officially nominated for a second term as vice president on September{{nbsp}}6 by voice vote at the [[2012 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/beau-biden-speech-read-th_n_1862997 |title=Beau Biden Speech Kicks Of Motion To Nominate Father Joe Biden For Vice President |work=[[Huffington Post]] | date=September 6, 2012 | first=Elyse | last=Siegel}}</ref> He faced his Republican counterpart, Representative [[Paul Ryan]], in the [[United States vice-presidential debate, 2012|vice-presidential debate]] on October 11 in [[Danville, Kentucky]]. There he made a feisty, emotional defense of the Obama administration's record and energetically attacked the Republican ticket, attempting to regain the momentum lost by Obama's unfocused debate performance against Republican nominee [[Mitt Romney]] the week before.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/10/11/14376267-biden-plays-aggressor-in-debate-as-ryan-argues-gop-case |title=Biden plays aggressor in debate as Ryan makes GOP case | author=O'Brien, Michael | publisher=[[NBC News]] | date=October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/sparks-fly-as-biden-ryan-face-off-in-feisty-vice-presidential-debate | title=Sparks fly as Biden, Ryan face off in feisty vice presidential debate | publisher=[[Fox News]] | date=October 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Obama and Biden were elected to second terms.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/obama-defeats-romney-to-win-second-term-vows-he-has-more-work-to-do | title=Obama defeats Romney to win second term, vows he has 'more work to do' | publisher=[[Fox News]] | date=November 7, 2012}}</ref> The ticket won 332 [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College votes]] to Romney\u2013Ryan's 206 and 51% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-xpm-2013-jan-04-la-pn-obama-biden-officially-win-second-term-20130104-story.html |title=It's official: Obama, Biden win second term |last=Memoli |first=Michael A. |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Post-election ====\n\n[[File:Vice President Biden Delivers Remarks at the Joint Opening Session.jpg|thumb|Biden speaks during the [[U.S.\u2013China Strategic and Economic Dialogue]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], July 2013]]\n<!--For convenience, includes material between re-election and second inauguration, although strictly speaking part of first term-->\n\nIn December 2012, Obama named Biden to head the [[Gun Violence Task Force]], created to address the causes of [[gun violence in the United States]] in the aftermath of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama sets up gun violence task force |first=Leigh Ann |last=Caldwell |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/obama-sets-up-gun-violence-task-force/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=December 19, 2012}}</ref> Later that month, during the final days before the United States fell off the \"[[United States fiscal cliff|fiscal cliff]]\", Biden's relationship with McConnell once more proved important as the two negotiated a deal that led to the [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012]] being passed at the start of 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2013/jan/01/its-over-house-passes-fiscal-cliff-deal/ |title=It's over: House passes 'fiscal cliff' deal |last=Demirjian |first=Karoun |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=January 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-cliff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/185276422.html |title=Congress' OK of fiscal cliff deal gives Obama a win, prevents GOP blame for tax boosts |author=Fram, Alan |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |location=Minneapolis |date=January 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105020524/http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/185276422.html |archivedate=January 5, 2013 }}</ref> It made many of the Bush tax cuts permanent but raised rates on upper income levels.<ref name=\"ap-cliff\"/>\n\n=== Second term (2013\u20132017) ===\n\n[[File:Michel Temer recebe vice-presidente norte-americano.jpg|thumb|right|Biden visits [[Brazil]]ian [[Vice President of Brazil|vice president]] [[Michel Temer]], October 11, 2013]]\nBiden was [[Second inauguration of Barack Obama|inaugurated to a second term]] on January 20, 2013, at a small ceremony in his official residence with Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]] presiding (a public ceremony took place on January 21).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/20/us-usa-inauguration-biden-idUSBRE90J08B20130120 | title=Vice President Biden sworn into office for second term | author=Rampton, Roberta | agency=Reuters | date=January 20, 2013}}</ref> He continued to be in the forefront as, in the wake of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]], the Obama administration put forth executive orders and proposed new gun control measures<ref name=\"time-cov-0113\">{{cite news | url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/01/16/americas-new-gunfight-inside-the-campaign-to-avert-mass-shootings/ | title=The Next Gun Fight | author=Scherer, Michael | magazine=Time | date=January 28, 2013}} Cover story.</ref> (they failed to pass).<ref>{{cite news |author=Weisman, Jonathan |date=April 17, 2013 |title=Senate Blocks Drive for Gun Control |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/18/us/politics/senate-obama-gun-control.html |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nBiden played little part in discussions that led to the October 2013 passage of the [[Continuing Appropriations Act, 2014]], which resolved the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|federal government shutdown of 2013]] and the [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2013|debt-ceiling crisis of 2013]]. This was becaues Senate majority leader [[Harry Reid]] and other Democratic leaders cut him out of any direct talks with Congress, feeling Biden had given too much away during previous negotiations.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/10/anatomy-of-a-shutdown-098518 |title=Anatomy of a shutdown |last=Bresnahan |first=John |last2=Manu |first2=Raju |last3=Sherman |first3=Jake |last4=Brown |first4=Carrie Budoff |newspaper=Politico |date=October 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/10/13/biden-mostly-out-of-sight-during-shutdown-showdown/2968373/ | title=Biden mostly out of sight as shutdown drags on |last=Gaudiano |first=Nicole |newspaper=USA Today |date=October 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/2013/10/biden-takes-back-seat-in-budget-negotiations-during-shutdown.html | title=Biden takes a back seat during budget negotiations over shutdown | author=Bowman, Bridget | work=PBS NewsHour | publisher=PBS | date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Joe Biden & Ahmet Davuto\u011flu.jpg|thumb|right|Biden with [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Turkish prime minister]] [[Ahmet Davuto\u011flu]], December 31, 2014. Biden said the [[Kurds in Turkey|Kurdish]] [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]] is a \"terrorist group\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/biden-says-kurdish-pkk-is-a-terror-group-plain-and-simple/a-19000607 |title=Biden says Kurdish PKK is a 'terror group plain and simple' |date=January 23, 2016 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]]}}</ref>]]\n\nBiden's Violence Against Women Act was reauthorized again in 2013. The act led to related developments, such as the [[White House Council on Women and Girls]], begun in the first term, as well as the [[White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault]], begun in January 2014 with Biden and [[Valerie Jarrett]] as co-chairs.<ref name=\"Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/docs/sexual_assault_report_1-21-14.pdf |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160824035035/https://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/docs/sexual_assault_report_1-21-14.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 24, 2016 |title=Rape and sexual assault: A renewed call to action |publisher=The White House |date=January 2014 |accessdate=August 24, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2014/01/22/memorandum-establishing-white-house-task-force-protect-students-sexual-a | title=Memorandum: Establishing White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault | publisher=obamawhitehouse.archives.gov | date= January 22, 2014 | accessdate= June 10, 2014}}</ref> Biden discussed federal guidelines on sexual assault on university campuses while giving a speech at the University of New Hampshire. He said, \"No means no, if you're drunk or you're sober. No means no if you're in bed, in a dorm or on the street. No means no even if you said yes at first and you changed your mind. No means no.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayes|first=Dianne|year=2012|title=Looking The Other Way?|url=|journal=Diverse: Issues in Higher Education|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elaine Grant |title=Federal Effort Targets Sexual Assaults At Colleges |url=https://www.npr.org/2011/04/05/135135544/federal-effort-targets-sexual-assaults-at-colleges |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |work=National Public Radio NPR |date=April 5, 2011 |quote=BIDEN: Look, guys, no matter what a girl does, no matter how she's dressed, no matter how much she's had to drink, it's never, never, never, never, never OK to touch her without her consent.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ashe Schow |title=Biden Reaps the #MeToo Whirlwind |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-reaps-the-metoo-whirlwind-11554419738 |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=April 4, 2019 |quote=While speaking to students at the University of New Hampshire in 2011, then-Vice President Joe Biden told men in the audience that \"no matter what a girl does, no matter how she's dressed, no matter how much she's had to drink\u2014it's never, never, never, never, never OK to touch her without her consent.\"}}</ref>\n\nBiden favored arming [[Timber Sycamore|Syria's rebel fighters]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Who to Blame If Arming the Syrian Rebels Goes Wrong |first=Conor |last=Friedersdorf |authorlink=Conor Friedersdorf |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2014/09/who-to-blame-if-arming-syrian-rebels-goes-wrong/380411/ |work=The Atlantic |date=September 18, 2014}}</ref> As [[Timeline of the Iraqi insurgency (2014)|Iraq fell apart during 2014]], renewed attention was paid to the Biden-Gelb Iraqi federalization plan of 2006, with some observers suggesting Biden had been right all along.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/joe-biden-iraq-107858 | title=Was Joe Biden right? | author=Gerstein, Josh | newspaper=Politico | date=June 13, 2014 | accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/62830 |title=Turns Out, Joe Biden Was Right About Dividing Iraq |last=Kitfield |first=James |magazine=National Journal |date=January 30, 2014 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> Biden himself said the U.S. would follow [[ISIL]] \"to the gates of hell\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/Decoder/2014/0903/Joe-Biden-vows-to-chase-Islamic-State-to-gates-of-hell.-Does-he-mean-it |title=Joe Biden vows to chase Islamic State to 'gates of hell'. Does he mean it? | author=Grier, Peter | newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor | date=September 3, 2014 | accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, he said [[Turkey]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]] had \"poured hundreds of millions of dollars and tens of thousands of tons of weapons into anyone who would fight against Al-Assad, except that the people who were being supplied were [[Al-Nusra Front|al-Nusra]], and al Qaeda, and the extremist elements of [[Jihadism|jihadis]] coming from other parts of the world.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Biden Is the Only Honest Man in Washington |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/10/07/joe-biden-is-the-only-honest-man-in-washington/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vice President Joe Biden visit to Israel March 2016 (25554709411).jpg|thumb|Biden with [[Prime Minister of Israel|Israeli prime minister]] [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] in [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]], March 9, 2016]]\n\nBy 2015, a series of swearings-in and other events where Biden had placed his hands on women and girls and talked closely to them attracted attention both in the press and on social media.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2015/02/17/joe-biden-takes-being-biden-to-new-heights-or-lows/ | title=Joe Biden takes 'being Biden' to new heights (or depths) | author=Henderson, Nia-Malika | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=February 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/17/387035292/joe-biden-gets-a-bit-too-close-to-new-secretary-of-defenses-wife | title=Joe Biden Gets A Bit Too Close To New Secretary Of Defense's Wife | author=Peralta, Eyder | publisher=NPR | date=February 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/us-vicepresident-joe-biden-in-new-creepy-photo-with-wife-of-defence-secretary-ashton-carter-20150218-13hp6a.html |title=US Vice-President Joe Biden in new 'creepy' photo with wife of Defence Secretary Ashton Carter | author=Visentin, Lisa | newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=February 18, 2015}}</ref> In one case, a senator issued a statement afterward saying of his daughter, \"No, she doesn't think the vice president is creepy.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2015/01/11/coons-my-daughter-doesnt-think-joe-biden-is-creepy/ | title=Coons: My daughter doesn't think Joe Biden is 'creepy' | author=Henderson, Nia-Malika | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=January 11, 2015}}</ref> On January 17, 2015, Secret Service agents heard shots fired as a vehicle drove near Biden's Delaware residence at 8:28&nbsp;p.m. outside the security perimeter, but the Bidens were not home. An agent observed a vehicle speeding away.<ref>{{cite news|first=Angie|last=Yack|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/01/18/politics/joe-biden-delaware-shooting/ |title=Delaware shooting occurs near unoccupied Biden home|date=January 18, 2015|work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2015, Biden spoke in Ukraine's parliament in Kiev<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_x9mT9jfzvw|title=Joe Biden english speech in Ukraine's parliament in Kiev|via= [[YouTube]]|date=December 8, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/vice-president-joe-bidens-dec-8-speech-to-ukraines-parliament-403800.html |title=U.S. Vice President Joe Biden's Dec. 8 speech to Ukraine's parliament (VIDEO, TRANSCRIPT) |publisher= kyivpost.com|date=December 8, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref> in one of his many visits to set U.S. aid and policy stance on Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-01-25/how-ukraine-s-president-fooled-joe-biden|title=How Ukraine's President Fooled Joe Biden|last=Bershidsky|first=Leonid|date=January 25, 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=January 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>In March 2016 testimony to the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], former ambassador to Ukraine [[John E. Herbst]] stated, \"By late fall of 2015, the EU and the United States joined the chorus of those seeking Mr. Shokin's removal\" and that Joe Biden \"spoke publicly about this before and during his December visit to Kyiv.\" During the same hearing, assistant secretary of state [[Victoria Nuland]] stated, \"we have pegged our next $1{{nbsp}}billion loan guarantee, first and foremost, to having a rebooting of the reform coalition so that we know who we are working with, but secondarily, to ensuring that the prosecutor general's office gets cleaned up.\" https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/03%2015%2016%20Ukrainian%20Reforms%20Two%20Years%20After%20the%20Maidan%20Revolution%20and%20the%20Russian%20Invasion.pdf</ref> On February 28, 2016, he gave a speech on sexual assault awareness at the [[88th Academy Awards]]; he also introduced [[Lady Gaga]].\n\nIn 2015, [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]] and [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate majority leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] invited Israeli prime minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] to address a joint session of Congress without notifying the Obama administration. This defiance of protocol led Biden and more than 50 congressional [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] to skip Netanyahu's speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/02/26/politics/democrats-missing-netanyahu-whip-list/index.html|title=The list of Democrats skipping Netanyahu's speech |first=Alexandra |last=Jaffe|website=CNN|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> But in March 2016, Biden spoke at the [[American Israel Public Affairs Committee|American Israel Public Affairs Committee (AIPAC)]] Policy Conference in [[Washington, D.C.]], saying, \"We're all united by our unyielding\u2014I mean literally unyielding\u2014commitment to the survival, the security, and the success of the Jewish State of [[Israel]].\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lS71Kp17o68|title=Special Report: AIPAC Policy Conference strengthens American-Israel alliance|last=Reznik|first=Ethan|date=April 27, 2016|work=Webb Canyon Chronicle|access-date=July 23, 2019|location=Claremont, California}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2016, Biden went to [[Ottawa]] to meet with [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Chris|title=Joe Biden drops in for a visit without any gifts: Chris Hall|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/joe-biden-visit-ottawa-1.3886370 |website=cbcnews.ca|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBiden never [[List of tie-breaking votes cast by vice presidents of the United States|cast a tie-breaking vote in the Senate]], making him the longest-serving vice president with this distinction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/pence-has-already-done-something-biden-never-did-break-a-senate-tie/|title=Pence Has Already Done Something Biden Never Did: Break A Senate Tie|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=February 7, 2017|website=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|quote=Twelve vice presidents, including Biden, never broke a tie; Biden was the longest-serving vice president to never do so.}}</ref>\n\n==== Death of Beau Biden ====\n\nOn May 30, 2015, Biden's son [[Beau Biden]] died at age 46 after having battled [[Glioblastoma|brain cancer]] for several years. In a statement, the Vice President's office said, \"The entire Biden family is saddened beyond words.\"<ref name=Kane>{{cite news|last1=Kane|first1=Paul|title=Beau Biden, vice president's son, dies of brain cancer|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2015/05/30/e1ac5a2a-0731-11e5-a428-c984eb077d4e_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> The nature and seriousness of the illness had not been previously disclosed to the public, and Biden had quietly reduced his public schedule to spend more time with Beau. Before his death, Beau had been widely seen as the front-runner for the [[Delaware gubernatorial election, 2016|2016]] Democratic nomination for [[governor of Delaware]].<ref name=allabout>{{cite news|title=Delaware's 2016 speculation all about Biden |first=Jonathan |last=Starkey |url=https://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2014/11/08/delawares-speculation-biden/18727837/ |accessdate=November 9, 2014 |newspaper=Delaware Online |date=November 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Governor>{{cite news |url=https://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2015/01/25/beau-biden-governor/22326393/ |title=Beau Biden for governor?|newspaper=Delaware Online |date=January 26, 2015 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 |first=Jonathan |last=Starkey }}</ref>\n\n=== Role in the 2016 presidential campaign ===\n\nDuring much of his second term, Biden was said to be preparing for a possible bid for the [[2016 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2016 Democratic presidential nomination]].<ref name=Itkowitz1/> At age 74 on [[United States presidential inauguration|Inauguration Day]] in January 2017, he would have been the [[List of Presidents of the United States by age|oldest president on inauguration]] in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeanddate.com/date/durationresult.html?d1=20&m1=11&y1=1942&d2=20&m2=1&y2=2017|title=Calculate duration between two dates\u2014results|work=timeanddate.com}}</ref> With his family, many friends, and donors encouraging him in mid-2015 to enter the race, and with [[Hillary Clinton]]'s favorability ratings in decline at that time, Biden was reported to again be seriously considering the prospect and a \"Draft Biden 2016\" [[Political action committee|PAC]] was established.<ref name=Itkowitz1>{{cite news |first=Colby |last=Itkowitz |title=There is a 'Draft Joe Biden' Super PAC Now; It's Even Hiring a Fundraiser |newspaper=Washington Post |date=March 23, 2015 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/wp/2015/03/23/job-opening-raise-money-to-draft-joe-biden-to-run-in-2016/ |accessdate=August 2, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Dowd1>{{cite news |first=Maureen |last=Dowd |title=Joe Biden in 2016: What Would Beau Do? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/opinion/sunday/maureen-dowd-joe-biden-in-2016-what-would-beau-do.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 1, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Zeleny |first2=Kevin |last2=Liptak |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/31/politics/vice-president-joe-biden-presidential-elections/ |title=Joe Biden Keeps Watchful Eye on 2016 Race |work=CNN |date=August 1, 2015 |accessdate=August 2, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2015|September|11|df=US}}, Biden was still uncertain whether to run. He cited his son's recent death as a large drain on his emotional energy, and said, \"nobody has a right{{nbsp}}... to seek that office unless they're willing to give it 110% of who they are.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-34216117|title=Joe Biden still undecided on presidential run|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, speaking from a podium in the [[White House Rose Garden|Rose Garden]] with his wife and Obama by his side, Biden announced his decision not to run for president in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Mason |url=https://www.aol.com/article/2015/10/21/biden-announces-hes-not-running-for-president/21252056/ |title=Biden says he will not seek 2016 Democratic nomination |agency=Thomson Reuters |date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=October 21, 2015 |website=aol.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Comment Joe Biden Is Not Running For President In 2016|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-president-2016_n_55f1cefbe4b093be51be0d69 |work=Huffington Post|accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Joe Biden Decides Not to Enter Presidential Race|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-biden-decides-not-to-enter-presidential-race-1445444657|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> In January 2016, Biden affirmed that it was the right decision, but admitted to regretting not running for president \"every day\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fabian|first1=Jordan|title=Biden regrets not running for president 'every day'|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/265011-biden-regrets-not-running-but-calls-it-right-decision |accessdate=January 12, 2017|work=TheHill|date=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of the end of January 2016, neither Biden nor Obama had endorsed anyone in the 2016 presidential election. Biden missed his annual Thanksgiving tradition of going to [[Nantucket, MA|Nantucket]], opting instead to travel abroad and meet with several European leaders. He took time to meet with [[Martin O'Malley]], having previously met with [[Bernie Sanders]], both 2016 candidates. Neither of these meetings was considered an endorsement, as Biden had said he would meet with any candidate who asked.<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Baker |first2=Maggie |last2=Haberman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/11/24/a-grieving-joe-biden-skips-thanksgiving-in-nantucket/ |title=Joe Biden Skips Thanksgiving in Nantucket; Meets With Martin O'Malley |work=The New York Times |date=November 24, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n[[File:VP Biden with Pence.jpg|thumb|Biden with Vice President-elect [[Mike Pence]] on November 10, 2016]]\n\nAfter Obama endorsed Clinton on June 9, 2016, Biden endorsed her later the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/06/joe-biden-endorses-hillary-clinton-224162 |title=Joe Biden endorses Hillary Clinton|publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref> Though Biden and Clinton were scheduled to campaign together in Scranton on July 8, Clinton canceled the appearance in light of the [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|shooting of Dallas police officers]] the previous day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/08/politics/hillary-clinton-joe-biden/index.html |first=Eugene |last=Scott |first2=MJ |last2=Lee |first3=Dan |last3=Merica |title=Joe Biden-Hillary Clinton rally postponed after Dallas shooting |date=July 8, 2016 |work=CNN |accessdate=January 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign season, Biden publicly displayed his disagreements with the policies of Republican presidential nominee [[Donald Trump]]. On June 20, Biden critiqued Trump's proposal to temporarily ban Muslims from entering the United States as well as his stated intent to [[Trump's border wall|build a wall]] along the border with Mexico, adding that Trump's suggestion to either torture and or kill family members of terrorists was damaging both to American values and \"to our security\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/joe-biden-to-slam-donald-trump-in-speech-monday/ |title=Joe Biden slams Donald Trump on wall, Muslim entry ban|date=June 20, 2016|publisher=CBS News|first=Rebecca|last=Shabad}}</ref> During an interview with [[George Stephanopoulos]] at the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]] on July 26, Biden asserted that \"moral and centered\" voters would not vote for Trump.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/vice-president-joe-biden-moral-sanders-supporters-vote/story?id=40908315 |title=Vice President Joe Biden: 'Moral' Sanders Supporters 'Can't Vote for Trump'|date=July 27, 2016|first=Suzan|last=Clarke}}</ref> On October 21, the anniversary of his decision not to run, Biden said he wished he was still in high school so he could take Trump \"behind the gym\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/biden-wishes-trump-gym-groping-comments/story?id=42965866 |title=Biden Says He Wishes He Could Take Trump 'Behind the Gym' Over Groping Comments|date=October 21, 2016|publisher=ABC|first=Maryalice|last=Parks}}</ref> On October 24, Biden clarified he would have fought Trump only if he was still in high school,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/10/21/politics/joe-biden-fight-donald-trump-2016-election/ |first=Allie |last=Malloy |first2=Daniella |last2=Diaz |title=Biden: I would only take Trump behind the gym 'if I were in high school' |date=October 24, 2016 |work=CNN |accessdate=January 1, 2020 }}</ref> and the following day, October 25, Trump responded that he would \"love that\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/10/25/trump-fight-biden/92752556/ |title=Trump: I'd love to fight 'Mr. Tough Guy', Joe Biden|newspaper=USA Today|first=William|last=Cummings|date=October 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Post-vice presidency (2017\u2013present) ==\n\n[[File:Barack Obama, Donald Trump, Joe Biden at Inauguration 01-20-17 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Biden with [[Chuck Schumer]], [[Barack Obama]] and [[Donald Trump]], January 2017]]\n[[File:Vice President Joe Biden Doug Jones.jpg|thumb|Biden campaigned for [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] candidate [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]] in October 2017.]]\n\nIn 2017, Biden was named the Benjamin Franklin Presidential Practice professor at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he intended to focus on foreign policy, diplomacy, and national security while leading the Penn Biden Center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement.<ref name=\"BidenUPenn\"/> He also wanted to pursue his \"cancer moonshot\" agenda,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/09/biden-outlines-steps-to-pursue-post-obama-cancer-moonshot.html |title=Biden outlines steps to pursue post-Obama 'cancer moonshot' |date=January 9, 2017 |work=CNBC |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> calling the fight against cancer \"the only bipartisan thing left in America\" in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/03/12/technology/sxsw-joe-biden-cancer/index.html |title=Joe Biden: The fight against cancer is bipartisan |last=O'Brien |first=Sara Ashley |date=March 12, 2017 |website=CNNMoney |access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBiden had been close friends with Senator [[John McCain]] for over 30 years. In 2018, McCain died at the age of 81 of the same kind of cancer that [[Beau Biden]] died of. Biden gave the eulogy at McCain's funeral service in Phoenix, Arizona. He opened with \"My name's Joe Biden. I'm a Democrat. And I loved John McCain.\"<ref name=\"townandcountrymag\">{{cite news |url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/politics/a22877209/joe-biden-eulogy-john-mccain-memorial-full-transcript/|title=Joe Biden Just Gave an Incredibly Powerful Speech at John McCain's Memorial|first=Megan|last=Friedman|date=August 30, 2018|website=Town & Country}}</ref> He also called him a \"brother\".<ref name=\"townandcountrymag\"/> Biden also served as a pallbearer at McCain's memorial service at the [[Washington National Cathedral]] alongside [[Warren Beatty]] and [[Michael Bloomberg]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/28/john-mccain-pallbearer-russia-799061 |date=August 28, 2018 |title=McCain's choice of Russian dissident as pallbearer is final dig at Putin, Trump |first=Josh |last=Meyer |website=[[Politico]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Comments on President Trump ===\n\nWhile attending the launch of the Penn Biden Center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement on March 30, 2017, a student asked Biden what \"piece of advice\" he would give Trump. Biden responded that Trump should grow up and cease his tweeting so he could focus on the office.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/326608-joe-biden-to-trump-grow-up-and-stop-tweeting |title=Biden to Trump: 'Grow Up' and 'Stop tweeting'|date=March 30, 2017|first=Taylor |last=Lorenz |newspaper=The Hill }}</ref> During a speech at a May 29 gathering of [[Phil Murphy]] supporters at a community center gymnasium, Biden said, \"There are a lot of people out there who are frightened. Trump played on their fears. What we haven't done, in my view\u2014and this is a criticism of all us\u2014we haven't spoken enough to the fears and aspirations of the people we come from.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-jersey/story/2017/05/28/biden-backing-phil-murphy-says-nj-governors-race-single-most-important-112380 |title=Biden backs Phil Murphy, says N.J. governor's race 'most important' in nation|first=Ryan|last=Hutchins|date=May 28, 2017|publisher=Politico}}</ref> On June 17, 2017, Biden predicted the \"state the nation is today will not be sustained by the American people\" while speaking at a [[Florida Democratic Party]] fundraiser in [[Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article156812854.html |title='We are better than this', impassioned Biden tells Florida Democrats|date=June 17, 2017 |newspaper=Miami Herald |first=Patricia |last=Mazzei |first2=Martin |last2=Vassolo }}</ref> Biden told ''CBS This Morning'' that Trump's administration \"seems to feel the need to coddle autocrats and dictators\" like [[Saudi Arabia]]n leaders, Russian president [[Vladimir Putin|Putin]], North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-un]] and Philippine president [[Rodrigo Duterte]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden knocks Trump for 'coddling' Saudi leaders after Khashoggi's disappearance |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/biden-knocks-trump-for-coddling-saudi-leaders-after-khashoggis-disappearance/2018/10/18/d428c82a-d2c6-11e8-83d6-291fcead2ab1_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |first=John |last=Wagner |date=October 18, 2018 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref> In October 2018, Biden said if Democrats retook the House of Representatives, \"I hope they don't [impeach Trump]. I don't think there's a basis for doing that right now.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Biden hopes Democrats don't impeach Trump right away |first=Arlette |last=Saenz |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/17/politics/biden-dont-impeach-trump/index.html |work=CNN |date=October 18, 2018}}</ref> On June 11, 2019, Biden criticized Trump's \"damaging\" [[China\u2013United States trade war|trade war with China]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Democratic candidates on foreign policy |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020-election/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> He also criticized Trump's decision to [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|withdraw U.S. troops from Syria]], which critics say gave [[Turkey]] the green light to launch the [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|military offensive]] against [[Rojava|Syrian Kurds]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden warns Isis fighters will strike US over Syria withdrawal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/15/biden-isis-syria-attack-trump-withdrawal-warning |first=Tom |last=McCarthy |work=The Guardian |date=October 16, 2019 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Climate change ====\n\nDuring an appearance at the Brainstorm Health Conference in [[San Diego, California]] on May 2, 2017, Biden said the public \"has moved ahead of the administration [on science]\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://fortune.com/2017/05/03/joe-biden-trump-cancer-drug-prices/ |title=Joe Biden on His New Cancer Initiative, Drug Prices, and Donald Trump|magazine=Fortune|date=May 3, 2017|first=Sy|last=Mukherjee}}</ref> On May 31, Biden tweeted that climate change was an \"existential threat to our future\" and remaining in the [[Paris Agreement]] was the \"best way to protect our children and global leadership\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/335859-biden-paris-deal-best-way-to-protect-us-leadership |title=Biden: Paris deal 'best way to protect' US leadership|first=Max|last=Greenwood|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> The next day, after Trump announced U.S. withdrawal from the agreement, Biden tweeted that the choice \"imperils U.S. security and our ability to own the clean energy future\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/335995-biden-says-paris-climate-deal-exit-imperils-national-security |title=Biden: Paris climate deal exit 'imperils' national security|first=Morgan|last=Chalfant|date=June 1, 2017|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref> While appearing at the Concordia Europe Summit in [[Athens, Greece]] on June 7, Biden said, referring to the withdrawal, \"The vast majority of the American people do not agree with the decision the president made.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/897c487c1e3442d2aee733448de49034 |title=Biden: Trump at odds with most Americans on climate change |work=Associated Press |date=June 7, 2017 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Healthcare ====\n\nOn March 22, 2017, during his first appearance on Capitol Hill since Trump's inauguration, Biden called the Republican healthcare bill a \"tax bill\" meant to transfer nearly $1 trillion used for health benefits for the lower classes to wealthy Americans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/03/22/joe-biden-says-republican-health-care-giveaway-rich/99502082/|title=Joe Biden says Republican health care is a giveaway to the rich|first=Nicole|last=Gaudiano|newspaper=USA Today|date=March 22, 2017}}</ref> On May 4, after the House of Representatives narrowly voted for the [[American Health Care Act]], Biden tweeted that it was a \"Day of shame for Congress\", lamenting the loss of preexisting condition protections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/hillary-clinton-joe-biden-slam-house-republicans-for-passing-ahca-2017-5 |title='Day of shame': Hillary Clinton and Joe Biden slammed the GOP for passing health care bill |date=May 4, 2017 |first=Mark |last=Abadi |website=Business Insider }}</ref> On June 24, in response to Senate Republicans' revealing an American Health Care Act draft the previous day, Biden tweeted that the bill \"isn't about health care at all\u2014it's a wealth transfer: slashes care to fund tax cuts for the wealthy & corporations.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/339263-biden-rips-senate-gop-healthcare-bill-says-it-isnt-about-healthcare |title=Biden rips Senate GOP healthcare bill, says it 'isn't about healthcare'|date=June 23, 2017|first=Julia|last=Manchester|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref> On July 28, in response to the Republican Senate healthcare bill failing, Biden tweeted, \"Thank you to everyone who tirelessly worked to protect the healthcare of millions.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/344330-biden-thanks-gop-healthcare-bill-opponents-after-skinny |title=Biden thanks GOP healthcare bill opponents after skinny ObamaCare repeal failure|first=Max|last=Greenwood|newspaper=The Hill|date=July 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Immigration ====\n\nOn September 5, 2017, after Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]] announced that the Trump Administration would rescind [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]], Biden tweeted, \"Brought by parents, these children had no choice in coming here. Now they'll be sent to countries they've never known. Cruel. Not America.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/349235-biden-trumps-dreamer-decision-cruel |title=Biden: Trump's DACA decision 'cruel'|first=Rafael|last=Bernal|newspaper=The Hill|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== LGBTQ rights ====\n\nOn April 14, 2017, Biden released a statement denouncing [[Chechnya|Chechen]]<nowiki/> authorities for rounding up, torturing, and murdering \"individuals who are believed to be gay\", and stating his hope that the Trump administration would honor a prior pledge to advance human rights by confronting Chechen leader [[Ramzan Kadyrov]] and Russian leaders over \"these egregious violations of human rights\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/14/politics/joe-biden-lgbt-chechnya-russia |title=Biden calls on Trump to raise anti-LGBT violence in Chechnya with Russians|first=Dan|last=Merica|date=April 14, 2017 |work=CNN}}</ref> On June 21, during a speech at a Democratic National Committee [[LGBT]] gala in [[New York City]], Biden said, \"Hold President Trump accountable for his pledge to be your friend.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/joe-biden-to-lgbt-gala-hold-president-trump-accountable/ |title=Joe Biden to LGBT gala: 'Hold President Trump accountable'|date=June 21, 2017|first=Steve|last=Peoples|newspaper=Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, after Trump announced a ban of [[Transgender personnel in the United States military|transgender people serving in the military]], Biden tweeted, \"Every patriotic American who is qualified to serve in our military should be able to serve. Full stop.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/343883-biden-rips-trump-transgender-ban-every-qualified-american |title=Biden rips Trump transgender ban: Every qualified American should be allowed to serve|date=July 26, 2017|newspaper=The Hill|first=Aida|last=Chavez}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Biden condemned [[Brunei]]'s new [[LGBT rights in Brunei|LGBT]] [[Death penalty for homosexuality|death penalty law]], tweeting: \"Stoning people to death for homosexuality or adultery is appalling and immoral. There is no excuse\u2014not culture, not tradition\u2014for this kind of hate and inhumanity.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Brunei defends tough new Islamic laws against growing backlash |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brunei-islamiclaws-idUSKCN1RB0E1 |first=A. |last=Ananthalakshmi |agency=Reuters |date=March 30, 2019 }}</ref> He suggested the Trump administration's hostility to LGBT rights was a poor example for countries like Brunei.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joe Biden Lays Out His Case to LGBTQ Voters at HRC Dinner |url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2019/6/02/joe-biden-lays-out-his-case-lgbtq-voters-hrc-dinner |first=Neal |last=Broverman |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=June 2, 2019 |location= |format=Video}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegations of inappropriate physical contact and sexual assault ===\n{{further|Joe Biden sexual assault allegation}}\n\nPhotographs and videos exist that show Biden in close proximity to women and children, including kissing, gripping, [[Eskimo kissing|nose rubbing]] and touching, which several media outlets described as inappropriate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/3/29/18241598/joe-biden-lucy-flores-touching-women-media-history-explained |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |title=Lucy Flores isn't alone. Joe Biden's got a long history of touching women inappropriately.|last=McGann|first=Laura|date=March 29, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-2020-harvey-weinstein_n_5a0a0ba8e4b00a6eece3a13e |title=Joe Biden 2020 Is A Terrible Idea In A Post-Weinstein America |last=Terkel |first=Amanda |date=November 15, 2017 |website=HuffPost |access-date=December 30, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/3713264/joe-biden-stephanie-carter-shoulder-rub/ |title=America Shouldn't Tolerate 'Biden Being Biden' |last=Markowitz |first=Karol |date=February 18, 2015 |website=Time |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNewYork\">{{cite web |title=Biden Charms Photographers, Frightens Children at Final Swearing-In as VP |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/joe-biden-final-congressional-swearing-in-as-vp/2083691/ |website=NBCNewYork |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Biden has described himself as a \"tactile politician\" and admitted this behavior has caused trouble for him in the past.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-joe-biden-kiss-lucy-flores-20190329-story.html|title=Nevada Democrat accuses Joe Biden of touching and kissing her without consent at 2014 event |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |last=Brice-Saddler |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, former Nevada assemblywoman [[Lucy Flores]] alleged that Biden had touched her without her consent at a 2014 campaign rally in Las Vegas. In an op-ed, Flores wrote that Biden had walked up behind her, put his hands on her shoulders, smelled her hair, and kissed the back of her head, adding that the way he touched her was \"an intimate way reserved for close friends, family, or romantic partners\u2014and I felt powerless to do anything about it.\"<ref name=\"O'Connor\">{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=Lydia |title=Ex-Nevada Assemblywoman Says Joe Biden Inappropriately Kissed Her |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-lucy-flores-kiss_n_5c9e8025e4b0474c08cea7aa |accessdate=March 29, 2019 |publisher=Huff Post |date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Biden's spokesman said Biden did not recall the behavior described.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Jessica |title=Former Nevada Candidate Accuses Biden Of Unwanted Touching, Which He Doesn't 'Recall' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/29/708232869/former-nevada-candidate-accuses-biden-of-unwanted-touching-which-he-doesnt-recal |accessdate=March 29, 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, Amy Lappos, a former congressional aide to [[Jim Himes]], said Biden touched her in a non-sexual but inappropriate way by holding her head to rub noses with her at a political fundraiser in Greenwich in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-biden-grabbed-aide-20190401-vl7chim3hrdjtcwu2tszrhozzm-story.html |title= Connecticut woman says then-Vice President Joe Biden touched her inappropriately at a Greenwich fundraiser in 2009 |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |last=Vigdor |first=Neil |date=April 1, 2019 |accessdate=April 1, 2019}}</ref> The next day, two more women came forward with allegations of inappropriate conduct. Caitlin Caruso said Biden placed his hand on her thigh, and D.J. Hill said he ran his hand from her shoulder down her back.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/437069-two-more-women-accuse-biden-of-inappropriate-touching|title=Two more women accuse Biden of inappropriate touching |first=Michael |last=Burke |date=April 2, 2019 |website=TheHill |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/02/us/politics/joe-biden-women-me-too.html |title=Biden's Tactile Politics Threaten His Return in the #MeToo Era |first=Sheryl Gay |last=Stolberg |first2=Sydney |last2=Ember |date=April 2, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=December 30, 2019 }}</ref> In early April 2019, three women told ''The Washington Post'' Biden had touched them in ways that made them feel uncomfortable.<ref name=\"WaPoColl\">{{cite web |last1=Viebeck|first1=Elise|last2=Viser|first2=Matt|last3=Itkowitz|first3=Colby| title=Three more women accuse Biden of unwanted affection, say apology video doesn't quell concerns |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/biden-says-hell-adjust-his-physical-behavior-as-three-more-women-come-forward/2019/04/03/94a2ed2c-5622-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, Tara Reade said that in 1993, while she was a staffer in Biden's Senate office, he had inappropriately touched her several times.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Riquelmy |first1=Alan |title=Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office |url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The Union |date=3 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210312/https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |archivedate=1 April 2020 |quote=\"He used to put his hand on my shoulder and run his finger up my neck.\"}}</ref> Biden apologized for not understanding how people would react to his actions, but said his intentions were honorable; he went on to say he was not sorry for anything he had ever done, which led critics to accuse him of sending a mixed message.<ref>Multiple sources:<br>{{Cite news|last=Heffernan|first=Virginia|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-heffernan-joe-biden-non-apology-20190406-story.html|title=Joe Biden is sorry, not sorry|date=April 6, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|access-date=April 7, 2019}}<br>{{Cite news|last1=Ember|first1=Sydney|last2=Martin|first2=Jonathan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/03/us/politics/joe-biden-women-video.html|title=Joe Biden, in video, says he will be 'more mindful' of personal space|date=April 3, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 28, 2020}}<br>{{Cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/04/03/bidens-new-video-is-well-done-its-still-non-apology/|title=Biden's new video is well done. But it's not an apology|date=April 3, 2019|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=March 28, 2020}}<br>{{Cite news|last=Epstein|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-03/biden-offers-no-apology-for-touching-but-vows-to-change-style|title=Biden offers no apology for touching but vows to change style|date=April 3, 2019|newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Reade accused Biden of pushing her against a wall and digitally penetrating her on [[Capitol Hill]] in 1993. On April 9, 2020, she filed a police report with the [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|Washington Metropolitan Police]] alleging she was sexually assaulted in spring 1993. Biden was not named in the report,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaffe |first1=Alexandra |title=Former Senate staffer accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault |url=https://apnews.com/d922da60baa91121f4529fe51a0fd55a |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=Associated Press |date=13 April 2020}}</ref> but Reade later said it was about him.<ref name=\"nytimesallegations\" />{{refn|group=nb|According to Reade, she did not share the entirety of her story earlier because she had faced backlash following her 2019 statements due to her previously expressed support of Putin.<ref name=\"nytimesallegations\" />}} Biden's 2020 presidential campaign has denied the allegation.<ref name=\"nytimesallegations\">{{cite news |last1=Lerer |first1=Lisa |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414043025/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |archivedate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sexual-assault-allegation-by-former-biden-senate-aide-emerges-in-campaign-draws-denial/2020/04/12/bc070d66-7067-11ea-b148-e4ce3fbd85b5_story.html|title=Sexual assault allegation by former Biden Senate aide emerges in campaign, draws denial|date=12 April 2020|accessdate=14 April 2020|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington, D.C.|first1=Beth|last1=Reinhard|first2=Elise|last2=Viebeck|first3=Matt|last3=Viser|first4=Alice|last4=Crites}}</ref>\n\n== 2020 presidential campaign ==\n\n{{Main|Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign}}\n{{See also|2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries}}\n[[File:Joe Biden kickoff rally May 2019.jpg|thumb|right|Biden at his presidential kickoff rally in [[Philadelphia]], May 2019]]\n\n=== Speculation and announcement ===\n\nBetween 2016 and 2019, media outlets often mentioned Biden as a likely candidate for president in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/trailguide/la-na-trailguide-updates-201612-htmlstory.html#joe-biden-wouldnt-count-out-a-2020-run-for-president-but-he-was-asked-in-an-emotional-moment |title=Joe Biden wouldn't count out a 2020 run for president. But he was asked in an emotional moment |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 5, 2016 |date=December 5, 2016 |last=Memoli |first=Michael }}</ref> When asked if he would run, he gave varied and ambivalent answers, saying \"never say never.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/07/politics/joe-biden-colbert-interview-2020-buzz/ |title=Biden stokes 2020 buzz on Colbert: 'Never say never' |work=CNN |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |date=December 7, 2016 |last=Wright |first=David }}</ref> At one point he suggested he did not see a scenario where he would run again,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/4593693/joe-biden-stephen-colbert-2020-run/ |title=Joe Biden Discussed Running in 2020 With Stephen Colbert: 'Never Say Never' |work=Time Magazine |accessdate=December 8, 2016 |date=December 7, 2016 |last=Lang |first=Cady }}</ref><ref name = \"Revesz\">{{cite news|last=Revesz|first=Rachael|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/joe-biden-think-tank-research-centre-university-pennsylvania-delaware-white-house-staff-cancer-a7526881.html|title=Joe Biden: I will not run for president in 2020 but I am working to cure cancer|work=[[The Independent]]|date=January 13, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> but a few days later, he said, \"I'll run if I can walk.\"<ref name=\"IfICanWalk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/17/magazine/joe-biden-i-wish-to-hell-id-just-kept-saying-the-exact-same-thing.html|title=Joe Biden: 'I Wish to Hell I'd Just Kept Saying the Exact Same Thing'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|last=Alter|first=Jonathan|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> A [[political action committee]] known as [[Time for Biden]] was formed in January 2018, seeking Biden's entry into the race.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wvik.org/post/new-quad-city-super-pac-time-biden |title=New Quad City Super PAC: \"Time for Biden\"|last=Charnetzki |first=Tori |publisher=[[WVIK]] |date=January 10, 2018 |accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBiden said he would decide whether to run or not by January 2019,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/07/17/joe-biden-president-january-decision/793771002/ |first=Christal |last=Hayes |title=Joe Biden says he will decide whether he's running for president by January |work=USA Today |access-date=July 18, 2018 |date=July 17, 2018 }}</ref> but made no announcement at that time. Friends said he was \"very close to saying yes\" but he was concerned about the effect another presidential run could have on his family and reputation, as well as fundraising struggles and perceptions about his age and relative centrism.<ref name=bidenclose>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/02/joe-biden-close-running-president-despite-doubts/581956/ |title=Biden's Anguished Search for a Path to Victory |work=The Atlantic |access-date=February 9, 2019 |date=February 4, 2019 |first=Edward-Isaac |last=Dovere }}</ref> On the other hand, he was prompted to run by his \"sense of duty\", offense at the Trump presidency, the lack of foreign policy experience among other Democratic hopefuls, and his desire to foster \"bridge-building progressivism\" in the party.<ref name=bidenclose/> He launched his campaign on April 25, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/former-vice-president-joe-biden-jumps-into-white-house-race/2019/04/25/093ff596-0aef-11e9-88e3-989a3e456820_story.html |title=Former vice president Joe Biden jumps into White House race |last=Scherer |first=Michael |date=April 25, 2019 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=April 25, 2019 |last2=Wagner |first2=John}}</ref> He chose [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], as his campaign headquarters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philly.com/news/joe-biden-2020-presidential-campaign-philadelphia-headquarters-20190516.html|title=Joe Biden chooses Philadelphia for 2020 presidential campaign headquarters |first=Jonathan |last=Tamari |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign ===\n\n[[File:Joe Biden (49536511763).jpg|thumb|Biden in [[Henderson, Nevada]], February 2020]]\n\nOn July 15, 2019, the nonprofit Biden Cancer Initiative announced it would cease operations for the foreseeable future. Biden and his wife left the initiative's board in April as an ethics precaution before starting his presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last=Braun |first=Stephen |url=https://www.apnews.com/97adeafe979943808a3abe963e089135 |title=Biden cancer nonprofit suspends operations indefinitely |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=July 15, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715151134/https://www.apnews.com/97adeafe979943808a3abe963e089135 |archivedate=July 15, 2019 |accessdate=July 16, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, it was reported that President Trump had pressured Ukrainian president [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] to investigate alleged wrongdoing by Biden and his son [[Hunter Biden]].<ref name=\"pressure\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine Pressured on U.S. Political Investigations|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=September 20, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Despite the allegations, as of September 2019, no evidence has been produced of any wrongdoing by the Bidens.<ref>Multiple sources:\n\n* {{cite news |last=Isachenkov |first=Vladimir |title=Ukraine's prosecutor says there is no probe into Biden |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/ukraines-prosecutor-says-there-is-no-probe-into-biden |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 27, 2019 |quote=Though the timing raised concerns among anti-corruption advocates, there has been no evidence of wrongdoing by either the former vice president or his son.}}\n* {{cite news |title=White House 'tried to cover up details of Trump-Ukraine call' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49842895 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=September 26, 2019 |quote=There is no evidence of any wrongdoing by the Bidens.}}\n* {{cite news |last=Timm |first=Jane |title=There's no evidence for Trump's Biden-Ukraine accusations. What really happened? |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/there-s-no-evidence-trump-s-biden-ukraine-accusations-what-n1057851 |accessdate=October 1, 2019 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=September 25, 2019| quote=But despite Trump's continued claims, there's no evidence of wrongdoing on the part of either Biden.}}</ref> The media widely interpreted this pressure to investigate the Bidens as trying to hurt Biden's chances of winning the presidency, resulting in [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|a political scandal]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176 |date=September 21, 2019 |title=Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son |last3=Volz |first=Alan |last=Cullison |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ballhaus |first3=Dustin |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/ |date=September 20, 2019 |title=Is Trump Trying to Get Ukraine to Take Out Biden for Him? |last=Mackinnon |first=Amy |work=Foreign Policy |access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> and [[impeachment of Donald Trump|Trump's impeachment]] by the House of Representatives.\n\nBeginning in 2019, Trump and his allies falsely accused Biden of getting the Ukrainian prosecutor general [[Viktor Shokin]] fired because he was ostensibly pursuing an investigation into [[Burisma Holdings]], which employed Hunter Biden. Biden was accused of withholding $1{{nbsp}}billion in aid from Ukraine in this effort. In 2015, then-vice president Biden pressured the Ukrainian parliament to remove Shokin because the United States, the European Union and other international organizations considered him corrupt and ineffective, and in particular was not assertively investigating Burisma. The withholding of the $1{{nbsp}}billion in aid was part of this official policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2019/oct/11/donald-trump/trump-ad-misleads-about-biden-ukraine-and-prosecut/|title=PolitiFact\u2014Donald Trump ad misleads about Joe Biden, Ukraine and the prosecutor|website=@politifact}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/09/27/quick-guide-trumps-false-claims-about-ukraine-bidens/|title=Analysis &#124; A quick guide to Trump's false claims about Ukraine and the Bidens|first=Glenn Kessler closeGlenn KesslerThe Fact|last=CheckerEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/23/politics/fact-check-trump-ukraine-hunter-biden-joe-biden/index.html|title=Fact check: What Trump has been getting wrong on Biden and Ukraine|first=Daniel|last=Dale|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>In March 2016 testimony to the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], former ambassador to Ukraine [[John E. Herbst]] stated, \"By late fall of 2015, the EU and the United States joined the chorus of those seeking Mr. Shokin's removal\" and that Joe Biden \"spoke publicly about this before and during his December visit to Kyiv\". During the same hearing, assistant secretary of state [[Victoria Nuland]] stated, \"we have pegged our next $1{{nbsp}}billion loan guarantee, first and foremost, to having a rebooting of the reform coalition so that we know who we are working with, but secondarily, to ensuring that the prosecutor general's office gets cleaned up.\"{{cite web |title=Ukrainian Reforms Two Years After the Maidan Revolution and the Russian Invasion |work=senate.gov |url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/03%2015%2016%20Ukrainian%20Reforms%20Two%20Years%20After%20the%20Maidan%20Revolution%20and%20the%20Russian%20Invasion.pdf |date=March 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThroughout 2019, Biden led his Democratic rivals in the national polls and was widely considered the [[front-runner]] in the Democratic presidential primaries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wpsdlocal6.com/news/nbc-wsj-poll-former-vice-president-joe-biden-frontrunner-in/article_24e6b0ee-2256-11ea-9a8d-e79be1ad7f68.html|title=NBC/WSJ poll: Former Vice President Joe Biden frontrunner in race for Democratic nomination|date=December 19, 2019|work=NBC News|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/biden-is-the-front-runner-but-there-is-no-clear-favorite/|title=Biden Is The Front-Runner, But There's No Clear Favorite|last=Silver|first=Nate|date=January 10, 2020|work=FiveThirtyEight|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> After disappointing showings in the Iowa and New Hampshire primary contests in early 2020, he fell to second place behind [[Bernie Sanders]] in mid-February.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/|title=National President: Democratic primary Polls|last=Mehta|first=Aaron Bycoffe, Ritchie King and Dhrumil|date=2018-06-28|website=FiveThirtyEight|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/10/joe-biden-national-poll-113302|title=Biden plummets in new national poll, ceding top spot to Bernie|last=Oprysko|first=Caitlin|date=February 10, 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> After winning the popular vote in the [[2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|South Carolina primary]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/b9872b58b495fd17044f359338ab3f2a|title=Biden wins South Carolina, aims for Super Tuesday momentum|last=|first=|date=February 29, 2020|work=Associated Press|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> and the withdrawal and subsequent endorsements of Pete Buttigieg and Amy Klobuchar, Biden made large gains in the March{{nbsp}}3 [[Super Tuesday]] primary elections and regained the front-runner position.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Montanaro |first1=Domenico |title=5 Takeaways From Super Tuesday And Joe Biden's Big Night |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/04/811868704/5-takeaways-from-super-tuesday-and-joe-bidens-big-night |publisher=NPR}}</ref> Biden expanded his lead with strong victories in four states (Idaho, Michigan, Mississippi, and Missouri) on March 10.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/2020-primary-election-takeaways/index.html|title=5 takeaways as Biden takes command of Democratic race on Super Tuesday II|date=March 11, 2020|work=CNN|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the suspension of the campaign of [[Bernie Sanders]] on April 8, 2020, Biden became the presumptive nominee for the presidential election.<ref name=\"NYT4-8-2020\"/> On April 13, Sanders endorsed Biden's candidacy in a live-streamed discussion from their homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/us/politics/bernie-sanders-joe-biden-endorsement.html|title=Bernie Sanders Endorses Joe Biden for President|last1=Ember|first1=Sydney|last2=Glueck|first2=Katie|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, former President [[Barack Obama]] endorsed Biden.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Merica |first=Dan |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/politics/obama-endorses-biden/index.html |title= Obama endorses Biden for president in video message |date=April 14, 2020 |work=CNN |access-date=April 14, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n{{Main|Political positions of Joe Biden}}\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|+ Joe Biden's ratings from advocacy organizations\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Group\n!rowspan=\"3\"| Advocacy issue(s)\n!colspan=\"3\"| Ratings\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Lifetime\n!colspan=\"2\"| Recent<ref>{{cite web |title=Joe Biden on the Issues |url=https://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm |publisher=OnTheIssues.org |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! Rating !! Date\n|-\n| [[AFL\u2013CIO]] || labor unions || 85%<ref name=aflcio>{{cite web |title=AFL-CIO Democratic Forum|url=http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|work=Elections 2008|publisher=Annenberg Political FactCheck|accessdate=April 4, 2013|date=August 8, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524230844/http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|archivedate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> || 85% || 2007\n|-\n| [[American Public Health Association|APHA]] || [[public health]] || || 100% || 2003\n|-\n| [[Citizens for Tax Justice|CTJ]] || [[progressive tax]]ation || || 100% || 2006\n|-\n| [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] || [[Minority group|minorities]] & [[affirmative action]] || || 100% || 2006\n|-\n| [[League of Conservation Voters|LCV]] || [[environmental protection]] || 83%<ref name=LCV1>{{cite web |url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/sites/scorecard.lcv.org/files/LCV_Scorecard_2008.pdf |title=National Environmental Scorecard |date=2008 |accessdate=December 31, 2019 }}</ref> || 64%<ref name=LCV1 /> || 2008\n|-\n| [[National Education Association|NEA]] || [[State school|public education]] || || 91% || 2003\n|-\n| [[Alliance for Retired Americans|ARA]] || [[senior citizen]]s || || 89% || 2003\n|-\n| [[Campaign for America's Future|CAF]] || [[energy security]] || || 83% || 2006\n|-\n| [[Peace Action|PA]] || peace and [[disarmament]] || || 80% || 2003\n|-\n| [[Human Rights Campaign|HRC]] || [[LGBT social movements|gay and lesbian rights]] || || 78% || 2006\n|-\n| [[NARAL Pro-Choice America|NARAL]] || abortion rights || ~72%<ref>{{cite web |url=https://justfacts.votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/53279/joe-biden-jr |title=Joe Biden, Jr.'s Ratings and Endorsements |work=votesmart.org |accessdate=December 31, 2019 }}</ref> || 75%<ref name=pvsnaral>{{cite web|title=Vice President Joseph 'Joe' Robinette Biden, Jr.'s Special Interest Group Ratings|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/53279/joe-biden-jr|work=Special Interest Group Ratings|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref> || 2007\n|-\n| [[Citizens United for Rehabilitation of Errants|CURE]] || [[Rehabilitation (penology)|criminal rehabilitation]] || || 71% || 2000\n|-\n| [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] || [[civil and political rights]] || 80%<ref name=ACLU1>{{cite web|last=Head|first=Tom|title=Joe Biden on Civil Liberties|url=http://civilliberty.about.com/od/ussenators/p/joe_biden.htm|work=Civil Liberties News and Issues|publisher=About.com|accessdate=June 3, 2013|year=2008}}</ref> || 91%<ref name=ACLU2 /> || 2007\n|-\n| [[Cato Institute|Cato]] || [[free trade]] and [[libertarianism]] || || 42% || 2002\n|-\n| [[United States Chamber of Commerce|US CoC]] || [[Corporation|corporate]] interests || || 32% || 2003\n|-\n| [[Christian Coalition of America|CCA]] || Christian [[family values]] || || 16% || 2003\n|-\n| [[National Taxpayers Union|NTU]] || lowering taxes || || 2%<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden|url=http://www.ntu.org/state/legislator/joe-biden|publisher=NTU|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> || 2008\n|-\n| [[National Right to Life Committee|NRLC]] || restrictions on abortion || || 0% || 2006\n|-\n| [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] || gun ownership || || F || 2003\n|}\n\nBiden has been characterized as a [[New Democrats|moderate Democrat]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=John |last=Kruzel |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/may/06/joe-biden/joe-biden-claims-he-was-staunch-liberal-senate-he-/ |date=May 6, 2019 |title=Biden says he was a staunchly liberal senator. He wasn't |website=[[PolitiFact]] |access-date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> He supported the [[fiscal stimulus]] in the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Assessing the Recovery Act: 'The best is yet to come'|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/op-ed-vice-president-joe-biden-todays-usa-today |accessdate=April 5, 2013|publisher = obamawhitehouse.archives.gov |date=February 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pbs27jan11\">{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Biden: Mubarak Is Not a Dictator, But People Have a Right to Protest|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/politics/jan-june11/biden_01-27.html|accessdate=April 5, 2013|newspaper=PBS Newshour|date=January 27, 2011}}</ref> the increased infrastructure spending proposed by the Obama administration;<ref name=\"pbs27jan11\" /> [[mass transit]], including [[Amtrak]], bus, and subway subsidies;<ref>{{cite news|last=Hockenberry|first=John|title=Vice President Joe Biden pushes mass transit spending|url=http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|accessdate=April 5, 2013|newspaper=The TakeAway|date=April 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719151247/http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|archivedate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> [[same-sex marriage]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=May 6: Joe Biden, Kelly Ayotte, Diane Swonk, Tom Brokaw, Chuck Todd|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/47311900/ns/meet_the_press-transcripts/t/may-joe-biden-kelly-ayotte-diane-swonk-tom-brokaw-chuck-todd/|accessdate=April 5, 2013|newspaper=Meet the Press|date=May 6, 2013}}</ref> and the reduced military spending in the Obama administration's fiscal year 2014 budget.<ref>{{cite web|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Statement by Vice President Biden On the Bipartisan Debt Talks|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2011/06/23/statement-vice-president-biden-bipartisan-debt-talks |work=Press Release|publisher=obamawhitehouse.archives.gov |accessdate=April 6, 2013|date=June 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hellman|first=Chris|title=Competing Visions: President Obama, Rep. Paul Ryan, Sen. Patty Murray, and House Progressives Release Budget Proposals for 2014|url=https://www.nationalpriorities.org/analysis/2013/budget-proposals-2014/|publisher=National Priorities Project|accessdate=June 3, 2013|author2=Mattea Kramer|date=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome political scientists gauge ideology by comparing the annual ratings by the [[Americans for Democratic Action]] (ADA) with the ratings by the [[American Conservative Union]] (ACU).<ref>{{cite news|author=Mayer, William|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A28761-2004Mar27|title=Kerry's Record Rings a Bell|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=August 24, 2008|date=March 28, 2004 |quote=The question of how to measure a senator's or representative's ideology is one that political scientists regularly need to answer. For more than 30 years, the standard method for gauging ideology has been to use the annual ratings of lawmakers' votes by various interest groups, notably the Americans for Democratic Action (ADA) and the American Conservative Union (ACU).}}</ref> Biden has a lifetime [[liberalism in the United States|liberal]] 72% score from the ADA through 2004, while the ACU awarded Biden a lifetime [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] rating of 13% through 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/2005-11-11-judiciarycommitteeprofiles_x.htm |title=Judging Judge Roberts: A look at the Judiciary Committee |newspaper=USA Today |date=September 12, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2008 |author=Kiely, Kathy }}{{Dead link|date=September 2010 |bot=H3llBot }} See also: {{cite web|url=http://www.acuratings.org/2008senate.htm |title=2008 U.S. Senate Votes |publisher=[[American Conservative Union]] |accessdate=March 20, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330124737/http://www.acuratings.org/2008senate.htm |archivedate=March 30, 2009 }} Lifetime rating is given.</ref> Using another metric, Biden has a lifetime average liberal score of 77.5%, according to a ''[[National Journal]]'' analysis that places him ideologically among the center of Senate Democrats as of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biden's Senate Vote Record |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/conventions/co_20080823_9669.php |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=August 23, 2008 |work=[[National Journal]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827100649/http://www.nationaljournal.com/conventions/co_20080823_9669.php |archivedate=August 27, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Almanac of American Politics]]'' rates congressional votes as liberal or conservative on the [[political spectrum]], in three policy areas: economic, social, and foreign. For 2005\u201306, Biden's average ratings were as follows: the economic rating was 80% liberal and 13% conservative, the social rating was 78% liberal and 18% conservative, and the foreign rating was 71% liberal and 25% conservative.<ref name=\"aap-08\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 363. In 2005, the ratings were E 73 26, S 83 10, F 76 15; in 2006, E 87 0, S 73 26, F 65 34.</ref> This has not changed significantly over time; his liberal ratings in the mid-1980s were also in the 70%\u201380%&nbsp;range.<ref name=\"cby-44\"/>\n\nVarious [[Interest group|advocacy groups]] have given Biden scores or grades for how well his votes align with their positions. The [[American Civil Liberties Union]] gives him an 80% lifetime score,<ref name=ACLU1 /> with a 91% score for the 110th Congress.<ref name=ACLU2>{{cite web|url=http://action.aclu.org/site/VoteCenter?congress=110&repId=199&session_num=0&page=legScore|title=ACLU Congressional Scorecard|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|accessdate=August 25, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030020320/http://action.aclu.org/site/VoteCenter?congress=110&repId=199&session_num=0&page=legScore|archivedate=October 30, 2008}}</ref> Biden opposes drilling for oil in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] and supports governmental funding to find new energy sources.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |title=Arctic Power\u2014Arctic National Wildlife Refuge\u2014Presidential Candidates views on ANWR, The Democrats |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807162357/http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |archivedate=August 7, 2008 }}</ref> He believes action must be taken on [[global warming]]. He co-sponsored the Sense of the Senate resolution calling on the United States to be a part of the United Nations climate negotiations and the [[Global Warming Pollution Reduction Act of 2007|Boxer\u2013Sanders Global Warming Pollution Reduction Act]], the most stringent climate bill in the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |magazine=[[Grist (magazine)|Grist]] |date=January 3, 2008 |accessdate=May 4, 2008 |url=https://grist.org/article/biden_factsheet/ |title=A look at the environmental record of Joe Biden, Barack Obama's running mate }}</ref> The [[AFL\u2013CIO]] gave Biden an 85% lifetime approval rating,<ref name=\"aflcio\"/> and he voted for the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA).<ref>{{cite news |title = Final Senate Vote on NAFTA |url = http://www.citizen.org/print_article.cfm?ID=15960 |publisher=Public Citizen |accessdate =August 22, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080608182639/http://www.citizen.org/print_article.cfm?ID=15960 |archivedate = June 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Distinctions ==\n\nBiden has received [[honorary degree]]s from the [[University of Scranton]] (1976),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matrix.scranton.edu/about/ab_degree_recipients.shtml |title=Honorary Degree Recipients |publisher=[[University of Scranton]] |year=2008 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720153525/http://matrix.scranton.edu/about/ab_degree_recipients.shtml |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref> [[Saint Joseph's University]] ([[Doctor of Laws|LL.D]] 1981),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sju.edu/ir/documents/HonDegreeRecip_IR2008.pdf |title=Honorary Degree Recipients |publisher=[[Saint Joseph's University]] |accessdate=August 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904003527/http://www.sju.edu/ir/documents/HonDegreeRecip_IR2008.pdf |archivedate=September 4, 2008 }}</ref> [[Widener University School of Law]] (2000),<ref name=\"wid-veep-elect\">{{cite web |url=http://law.widener.edu/NewsandEvents/Articles/2008/de110508bidenvpelect.aspx |title=Senator Biden becomes Vice President-elect |publisher=[[Widener University School of Law]] |date=November 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105150946/http://law.widener.edu/NewsandEvents/Articles/2008/de110508bidenvpelect.aspx |archivedate=January 5, 2009 }}</ref> [[Emerson College]] (2003),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emerson.edu/emersontoday/index.cfm?action=3&articleID=782&editionID=52 |title=Senator Biden to Address 123rd Commencement Rites On May 19 |publisher=[[Emerson College]] |date=May 2003 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060918144250/http://www.emerson.edu/emersontoday/index.cfm?action=3&articleID=782&editionID=52 |archivedate=September 18, 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> his alma mater the [[University of Delaware]] (2004),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.udel.edu/PR/UDaily/2004/biden052904.html |title=Honorary Degree Citation for Joseph R. Biden Jr. |publisher=[[University of Delaware]] |date=May 29, 2004 |accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref> [[Suffolk University Law School]] (2005),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2005/05/23/commencements_boston_globe/ |title=Commencements |work=Boston Globe |date=May 23, 2005 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105144404/http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2005/05/23/commencements_boston_globe/ |archivedate=January 5, 2009 }}</ref> his other alma mater [[Syracuse University]] ([[Doctor of Laws|LL.D]] 2009),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.syr.edu/awards/honorary_1.html |title=SU Archives: Awards and Honors\u2014Recipient of Honorary Degrees |website=archives.syr.edu |access-date=February 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730115922/http://archives.syr.edu/awards/honorary_1.html |archive-date=July 30, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Doctor of Laws|LL.D]] 2013),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archives.upenn.edu/digitized-resources/docs-pubs |title=Documents & Publications &#124; University Archives and Records Center |website=archives.upenn.edu}}</ref> [[Miami Dade College]] (2014),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article1963844.html |title=Vice President Joe Biden hails need for immigration reform at Miami Dade College graduation |publisher=}}</ref> [[Trinity College, Dublin]] ([[Doctor of Laws|LL.D]] 2016),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tcd.ie/news_events/articles/us-vice-president-joe-biden-receives-honorary-doctorate-from-trinity-college/6965 |title=US Vice President Joe Biden Receives Honorary Doctorate from Trinity College |first=Trinity News and Events, Trinity College |last=Dublin |website=www.tcd.ie}}</ref> [[Colby College]] ([[Doctor of Laws|LL.D]] 2017),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2017/04/17/joe-biden-former-vice-president-to-speak-at-colby-college-commencement/ |title=Joe Biden to speak at Colby College commencement |date=April 17, 2017 |publisher=}}</ref> [[Morgan State University]],(DPS 2017),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://themsuspokesman.com/6943/campus-news/former-vice-president-joe-biden-is-msus-spring-2017-commencement-speaker/ |title=Former Vice President Joe Biden Is MSU's Spring 2017 Commencement Speaker\u2014The MSU Spokesman |date=April 14, 2017 |publisher=}}</ref> and the [[University of South Carolina]] ([[Doctor of Public Administration|DPA]] 2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sc.edu/uofsc/announcements/2014/04_biden_to_speak_at_uofsc_commencement.php |title=Vice President Joe Biden to deliver UofSC commencement address\u2014University of South Carolina |website=www.sc.edu}}</ref>\n[[File:Joe Biden Receives Presidential Medal of Freedom.jpg |left |thumb |President Obama presents Biden with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom |Presidential Medal of Freedom with Distinction]], January 12, 2017]]\n\nBiden also received the Chancellor Medal (1980) and the George Arents Pioneer Medal (2005) from [[Syracuse University]].<ref name=\"nd051009\">{{cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/news/politics/wire/sns-ap-us-biden-commencement,0,5937836.story |title=Biden tells Syracuse University graduates they have special opportunity to help shape history |author=Kates, William |work=Newsday |date=May 10, 2009 |accessdate=May 11, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"nd051009\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sunews.syr.edu/story_details.cfm?id=2601 |title=Five SU alumni to be honored with Arents Awards |publisher=[[Syracuse University]] |date=May 25, 2005 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060907182627/http://sunews.syr.edu/story_details.cfm?id=2601 |archivedate=September 7, 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Biden received ''[[Working Mother]]'' magazine's Best of Congress Award for \"improving the American quality of life through family-friendly work policies\".<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://biden.senate.gov/press/press_releases/release/?id=dca94360-b4ac-4bed-a41e-b7c27f42b4a1 |title=Biden Honored for Making a Difference for Working Families |publisher=[[U.S. Senate]] |date=August 12, 2008 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081125111957/http://biden.senate.gov/press/press_releases/release/?id=DCA94360-B4AC-4BED-A41E-B7C27F42B4A1 |archivedate=November 25, 2008 }}</ref> Also in 2008, he shared with fellow senator [[Richard Lugar]] the [[Government of Pakistan]]'s [[Hilal-i-Pakistan]] award \"in recognition of their consistent support for Pakistan\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSTRE49R5I120081028 |title=Pakistan gives awards to Biden, Lugar for support |agency=Reuters |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |first=Zeeshan |last=Haider}}</ref> In 2009, [[Kosovo]] gave Biden the Golden Medal of Freedom, the region's highest award, for his vocal support for its independence in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jtMFK8wLcamElXQlmEBh0CEBE9dQ |title=Biden ends Balkans tour, heads to Lebanon |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=May 22, 2009 |accessdate=May 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBiden is an inductee of the [[Delaware Volunteer Firemen's Association]] Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvfassn.com/awards.cfm?id=2 |title=Hall of Fame |publisher=[[Delaware Volunteer Firemen's Association]] |accessdate=September 16, 2008}}</ref> He was named to the [[Little League Hall of Excellence]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.littleleague.org/learn/museum/World_of_Little_League/HallofExcellence.htm |title=Hall of Excellence |publisher=[[Little League Baseball]] |accessdate=April 10, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430225626/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/museum/hallofexcellence.htm |archivedate=April 30, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2016, Biden received the [[Freedom of the City|freedom]] of [[County Louth]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=\"talkofthetown\">{{cite web |url=https://www.talkofthetown.ie/biden-receives-freedom-of-county-louth-on-visit-to-cooley-peninsula/ |publisher=talkofthetown.ie |title=Biden receives Freedom of County Louth on visit to Cooley Peninsula &#124; Talk of the Town |accessdate=January 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 12, 2017, Obama surprised Biden by awarding him the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom |Presidential Medal of Freedom with Distinction]] during a farewell press conference at the White House honoring Biden and his wife. Obama said he was awarding Biden the Medal of Freedom for \"faith in your fellow Americans, for your love of country and a lifetime of service that will endure through the generations\".<ref name=\"bostonglobe11217\">{{cite news |title=Obama awards Biden Presidential Medal of Freedom |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2017/01/12/obama-awards-biden-presidential-medal-freedom/5zhMW6IRJFAreoJLB0FXWN/story.html |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=Boston Globe |date=January 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shear |first1=Michael D. |title=Obama Surprises Joe Biden With Presidential Medal of Freedom |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/12/us/politics/joe-biden-presidential-medal-freedom.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> It was the first and only time Obama awarded the Medal of Freedom with the additional honor of distinction, an honor his three predecessors had reserved for only President [[Ronald Reagan]], [[Colin Powell]] and [[Pope John Paul II]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden surprised with Presidential Medal of Freedom |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/latest-news/article126184169.html |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=The Miami Herald |date=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 2018, the [[University of Delaware]] renamed its School of Public Policy and Administration the Joseph R. Biden, Jr. School of Public Policy and Administration. The Biden Institute is housed there.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.udel.edu/udaily/2018/december/joseph-biden-school-public-policy-administration/ |title=Biden School &#124; UDaily |website=www.udel.edu}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n{{Main|Electoral history of Joe Biden}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | Election results\n|-\n!Year\n!Office\n!Election\n!Votes for Biden\n!%\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|1970\n|